<FIRST>u a AM-ChevronFire     04-11 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chevron Fire,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire, Explosion At Chevron Plant; 6 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire erupted Monday at a Chevron oil
refinery plant, injuring at least seven workers and sending
100-foot flames shooting into the sky.
   The fire apparently started at 12:46 p.m. when an explosion
shook a 100-foot-tall column in a refinery processing plant where
gasoline is manufactured, said Hal Holt, a Chevron spokesman.
   Thick black smoke and flames rose into the sky as about 40
firefighters from Chevron and the city of Richmond battled the
blaze, which was declared under control about four hours later,
Holt said.
   ``The fire is still burning and we have not been able to get in
to assess the cause or the totality of damage,'' said Holt, who
refused to estimate a damage amount.
   Three Chevron operators were flown to Brookside Hospital in San
Pablo where a hospital spokesman said they were in stable condition
with second degree burns. One man suffered burns over 70 percent of
his body and the other two had burns over 20 percent to 30 percent
of their bodies.
   Another Chevron operator was taken to Doctor's Hospital in
Pinole, where he was reported in stable condition after being
treated for smoke inhalation, according to the nursing supervisor.
   Alta Bates Hospital in Berkeley reported that one Chevron fire
marshal was admitted with second degree burns on his face, ears and
neck and was having respiratory difficulties, said hospital
spokeswoman Carolyn Kemp.
   At least two other people were reported injured but there was no
immediate word on the extent of their injuries.
   The facility is Chevron's second largest refinery on the West
Coast and produces about 265,000 barrels of crude oil daily.
</TEXT>
