<FIRST>r w PM-Soviets-BandFlap     04-11 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviets-Band Flap,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Reverses Itself, OKs Coast Guard Band's Soviet Appearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a policy reversal, the State Department has
agreed to let the U.S. Coast Guard Band perform this June at a
Leningrad concert commemorating last year's U.S.-Soviet arms treaty.
   Earlier this year, the Leningrad City Council invited the
Connecticut-based military band to play with the Leningrad Military
District Band in a joint concert June 22 in honor of the first
anniversary of the treaty banning intermediate-range nuclear
missiles.
   The U.S. Embassy in Moscow embraced the idea, according to Rep.
Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., but higher-level officials in Washington
rejected it without explanation.
   Gejdenson and officials at the Coast Guard Academy in New
London, Conn., protested the State Department decision to scuttle
the trip.
   In a letter last month to Janet G. Mullins, the department's
legislative liaison, Gejdenson said he could not understand ``what
reason could possibly exist for refusing this gracious and generous
invitation during this period of excellent relations.''
   The State Department told Gejdenson on Monday that the trip was
back on.
   ``The band shows the best of America,'' the congressman said.
``The Russian people will love it.''
   One source said State Department officials feared the trip would
interfere with a concurrent visit by U.S. military officials and
were uneasy about the idea of having an American military unit
performing in the Soviet Union.
   But Gejdenson said he believes the reluctance stems from the
problems Americans have with responding to glasnost, the Soviets'
new policy of openness.
   ``It's just symbolic of the difficulty of the new opportunities
in the relationship with the Soviet Union. Even the simplest and
smallest symbol that they're willing to try ... was a major hurdle
to get across,'' Gejdenson said.
   Ms. Mullins and State Department officials for Soviet affairs
could not be reached for comment following Gejdenson's
announcement, which came late Monday afternoon.
   Leningrad officials are paying for the band's hotel, meals and
local transportation, Gejdenson said. The U.S. government has to
supply air travel to the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
