<FIRST>r i PM-Arias-Figueres     04-11 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arias-Figueres,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Interrupts North American Trip to Visit Ailing Ex-President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS A. SANDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Oscar Arias interrupted
his North American trip to visit his ailing mentor, former
President Jose Figueres.
   ``I come to see my friend, one of the greatest leaders that
Costa Rica and Latin America has ever had,'' Arias told reporters
Monday as he entered San Jose de Dios Hospital in the nation's
capital.
   ``When his health failed, we realized how much Don Pepe meant to
us,'' said the president, who was to later resume his trip to the
United States and Canada.
   Figueres, 83, has been hospitalized since Friday with a heart
ailment. Although doctors initially said they feared his death was
imminent, by Monday they said he had improved considerably.
   All day long, hundreds of people called the hospital to ask
about the health of the former president affectionately known as
Don Pepe. Figueres was president of Costa Rica three times and in
1948 abolished the army.
   At a recent public event Arias confessed that ``Don Pepe is like
my second father and has been my political guide.'' Both men belong
to the National Liberation Party, which Figueres founded in 1953.
   ``I want to tell all of you that I am glad to find Don Pepe so
well and I think he is recovering quickly,'' Arias told reporters.
``He always has encountered force against adversity in his life and
that force has come from God.''
   Arias refused to comment to journalists on his tour of North
America and his debt talks with U.S. and Canadian officials.
</TEXT>
