<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 0144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Lead-Schools     04-11 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lead-Schools,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lead Found in Same Model Water Coolers Used by Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lead-Tanks List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Water fountains with excessive levels of lead
because of tanks lined with the toxic metal are being used at
elementary and secondary schools, and more than 100 models have
unhealthy levels, the government says.
   The exact number of coolers with the lead-lined tanks is not
known, but the Environmental Protection Agency did say that more
than a million other coolers are in use that have lead soldering or
lead in some other form.
   Although the EPA lacks the authority to order lead testing in
schools, a law enacted last year requires states to begin a program
to assist school districts in testing for lead in drinking water.
Many such programs are under way.
   EPA officials also said Monday they would soon issue a detailed
guide for school officials on how to testfor unhealthy lead levels,
and the agency listed more than 100 manufacturers' model numbers
for fountains in which lead levels were found to be of concern.
   The EPA said Monday it discovered the lead-lined tanks while
inspecting 22 coolers provided by the Navy. The nine with
lead-lined tanks were all models like those used in schools.
   Those coolers, all made by Halsey Taylor Co., mostly had lead
levels of more than several hundred parts per billion, the EPA
said. In some cases, when long-standing water was tested, the level
was more than 1,000 parts per billion, the EPA said.
   The EPA considers a lead level of 20 parts per billion in water
to pose health risks especially if a child is exposed to lead
poisoning from other sources as well.
   Lead is a toxic metal that is harmful to health even at low
levels of exposure and poses increased risks to children. It can
cause damage to the brain and nervous system and lead to learning
disabilities, hearing impairment, and interference in the formation
of red blood cells, according to the EPA.
   ``There are a few hundred thousand children who have enough lead
from other sources so when lead from drinking water is added at
levels of 20 parts per billion there will be some adverse health
impact,'' said Mike Cook, head of the EPA water contamination
office, in an interview.
   The agency also said that three major manufacturers of school
water coolers have acknowleged that more than a million coolers
have some lead components _ usually lead soldering at joints. Two
other companies did not reply to the inquiries and another said it
manufactured no coolers with lead soldering.
   The agency gave no specific levels of lead in water from all the
coolers cited by model numbers, but said the coolers were singled
out only after levels were found to be in the unhealthy range.
   After the EPA issues a final list of coolers with lead-lined
tanks later this year, the Consumer Products Safety Commission
intends to seek their recall by the manufacturer, said David
Schmeltzer, director of compliance at the commission.
   EPA officials said that school water fountains likely account
for only a ``very small'' part of the lead exposure that faces
youngsters. In some cases it's uncertain whether the high lead
levels in some model coolers was from the coolers or water pipes
that feed the coolers.
   In addition to the nine lead-lined coolers from the Navy, the
EPA received two additional coolers with lead-lined tanks from
school officials in Portland, Maine, Cook said.
   The law that was passed last year also requires the EPA to
issued detailed guidelines on how to detect lead contamination in
school water systems and sets a timetable for replacing or fixing
coolers that pose a health hazard because of lead contamination.
   The coolers cited by model number were manufactured by three
companies _ Halsey Taylor, EBCO Manufacturing Co., and Sunroc Corp.
The EPA said two other companies have yet to reply to inquiries on
lead content in their coolers and a third said it produced no
coolers with lead components.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
