<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Whistleblowers     04-11 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Whistleblowers,240</SECOND>
<UNK>Bush Signs Whistleblower Protection Bill</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed a bill to protect
federal whistleblowers who report government waste and fraud,
calling it a ``significant improvement'' over a version vetoed by
President Reagan.
   The bill signed by Bush on Monday gives more job protection to
federal employees who disclose misdeeds and mismanagement in their
agencies.
   ``The true whistleblower is a public servant of the highest
order,'' Bush said at a bill-signing ceremony in the Old Executive
Office Building attended by the measure's congressional sponsors.
   Reagan vetoed a similar measure last fall.
   Stripped from the new version _ which was approved unanimously
in the Senate and by a voice vote in the House _ is a provision
opposed by Reagan that would have permitted the Office of Special
Counsel to go to court on behalf of whistleblowers.
   Reagan protested this would have resulted in federal agencies
fighting court battles against each other.
   The new version ``addresses the chief constitutional concerns
raised by earlier versions of this legislation,'' Bush said. ``The
bill I am signing today is a significant improvement over
legislation enacted by Congress last year.''
   Under the new act, employees fighting for their jobs would face
less stringent standards of proof that their firing or demotion
came as the result of whistleblowing.
   The Office of the Special Counsel, established eight years ago
to investigate civil service abuses, would become an independent
agency.
</TEXT>
