<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PLO-Israel     04-11 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PLO-Israel,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Rejects Israeli Plan For Elections In Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO has rejected an Israeli proposal
to hold elections among Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   Wafa, the PLO news agency, said the proposal by Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir is ``nothing but a reactivation of the
self-autonomy scheme of the Camp David accord, which the PLO and
our entire Palestinian people already have rejected.''
   George Habash, head of the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, said in a statement issued in Damascus, Syria:
   ``We will not allow the Shamir plan to pass. We will not allow
elections to be held under enemy army bayonets. We will not allow
the creation of a substitute leadership whatever their name or
color might be.''
   Habash's Marxist organization is the second-largest group in the
Palestine Liberation Organization after Yasser Arafat's Fatah, the
main Palestinian fighting force.
   Under Shamir's plan, proposed last week in Washington,
Palestinians would choose representatives for negotiations about an
interim settlement in the territories.
   An Israeli government official in Jerusalem quoted Shamir on
Monday as saying he was willing to discuss participation in
proposed elections by Palestinians from outside the territories.
   The official said those elected also might consult during
negotiations with the PLO, with which Shamir refuses to deal,
because ``no one can think the PLO is an element you can totally
ignore.''
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
the PLO should ``explore practical ways to advance the peace
process.'' He declined to say whether the United States was asking
the PLO to endorse Shamir's plan, which received President Bush's
qualified support.
   The Wafa report, quoting a PLO spokesman it did not identify,
said elections in the occupied lands should be held under
international supervision after Israel withdraws.
   ``The idea of elections is totally unacceptable in the shadow of
Israeli occupation and this proposal is nothing but a maneuver
aimed at undermining efforts undertaken by several world powers to
achieve a just settlement in the Middle East,'' the report said.
   In the U.S-mediated Camp David accords that lead to the 1979
peace treaty, Egypt and Israel agreed to limited autonomy for
Palestinians in the territories that Israel captured from Jordan
and Egypt in 1967.
   The PLO spokesman said Israel should turn over the territories
to a U.N. supervisory force for a transition period during which
elections would be held.
   On Friday, PLO chairman Arafat said Shamir's proposal was
``inappropriate, as usual.''
   Monday's PLO statement reiterated calls for an international
peace conference on the Middle East involving all parties
concerned, ``including the Palestinian state'' proclaimed Nov. 15
by the Palestine National Council, which acts as the PLO
legislature.
   It is the first PLO mention of the Palestinian state as the
representative of Palestinians at an international forum. Previous
references have been to the PLO itself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
