<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 0203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SocialSecurity     04-11 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Security,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chaos Overwhelms Special Line to Social Security Office, Witnesses
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who called an expanded toll-free
telephone service offered by the Social Security Administration met
with busy signals, endless waits on hold and misinformation when
they did get through, witnesses told a Senate panel.
   Judith Price of Akron, Ohio, told the the Senate Special
Committee on Aging that she was put on hold three times for 20
minutes, then told she would have to wait 30 days for the answer to
a question on moving her mother's checks into a new account.
   A phone representative neglected to tell Kathryn Lippert of
Pittsburgh that she needed to file a claim to get a widow's
benefit, and she said it took five months to wade through red tape
before the problem was solved.
   ``I would like to point out that for the past five months, I
have only received my own Social Security check, which is $70 less
than my rent alone,'' she told the panel on Monday.
   The administration began the 800-number service last October,
hoping to improve convenience and accessibility to the public by
making phone representatives available for 12 hours per day,
instead of eight. The system, in which calls to local Social
Security offices are routed to any of 37 national ``teleservice''
centers, has been implemented so far in 60 percent of the nation
and received 22 million calls.
   The service was touted in two mailings to a total of 36 million
beneficiaries in December and February.
   Lawmakers began hearing about the system after national busy
signal rates reached 43 percent in January, followed by 35 percent
in February.
   The rate dipped to 9 percent in March, but only after calls
dropped from 4.8 million in March to 3.4 million in February, and
after SSA brought in staff members in from other offices to answer
calls, a General Accounting Office official testified.
   ``While the reassignment of staff contributed to the reduction
of this busy signal rate for March, it raises questions about the
impact on the operations of the field facilities,'' Joseph Delfico
of GAO's Human Resources Division said in a prepared statement.
   John Sturdivant, president of the American Federation of
Government Employees, told the panel that SSA Commissioner Dorcas
Hardy ``has created sweatshop conditions for teleservice
employees.''
   ``She is pressuring employees to complete calls in an average of
200 seconds,'' he said, adding that the employees are being denied
sick leave.
   SSA said it reduced the busy signal rate in March partly through
the use of a system to reroute calls during peak calling times.
   ``As we have identified problems and gained experience with the
system, we have been able to modify our procedures along the way in
order to improve our performance,'' Hardy told the panel.
   ``This will be the largest 800-number in the world,'' she said
in a prepared text. ``I want it to be the best.''
   A survey conducted by SSA in February found that 84 percent of
callers interviewed were satisfied with the phone service and 98
percent thought they had been treated courteously, the
administration said.
   Hardy said the latest survey placed the system-wide accuracy
rate at 94 percent.
   But GAO's Delfico said that an SSA study last December found
that the number of incorrect 800-number responses ranged from 2.5
percent for a question on disability benefits to 22.9 percent for a
question on the annual earnings test for people 70 years old and
over.
   The service handled 22 million calls during its first six months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
