<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-Race     04-11 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Race,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oily `Response Team' Dawdled, Lost Race Against Clock</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Allyeska-Exxxon in 2nd graf, Wendie in 14th graf cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It lacked the proper equipment and dawdled
when it should have been racing against the clock, but the
oil-smeared ``response team'' promised to revise its contingency
plan and do better next time.
   The Allyeska-Exxxon Response Team was the last of the 103 teams
to cross the finish line in the 14th-annual Ski-to-Sea Relay near
Juneau.
   ``We were well-prepared. We had a good plan. But, darn, the
thing just wasn't adequate,'' team member Jim Nordlund said Monday.
   Nordlund said his team was neither sanctioned nor supported by
Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. nor Exxon Corp., the companies blamed
for the slow response to the Valdez oil spill. It was just
coincidence that team members had crude oil on their faces and
clothes, he said.
   In fact, all but one of the team members work for the
Legislature, which is no stranger to oil companies.
   Each team included a downhill skier, who began the relay at the
top of the Eaglecrest Ski Area and passed the baton to a
cross-country skier, two runners and a bicyclist.
   Nordlund, a legislative aide, noted his bicycle was not designed
for the job.
   ``We thought it was a state-of-the-art bike. It actually was a
little small. It wasn't large enough to deal with the size of the
race,'' he said.
   ``Well, it basically was a little kid's bike.''
   The downhill skier in Nordlund's team missed all the gates,
``and unfortunately there's a penalty each time you do that,'' he
said. ``I think she skied part of the way backwards.''
   Things got worse when the team's cross-country skier took over.
   ``He's our lawyer and he was dressed up in a suit and tie,
smoking a cigar,'' Nordlund recalled. ``After the start he realized
his cigar went out so he stopped and took the time to light it.
   ``He figured there just wasn't much of a hurry. Things were
under control. He had The Wall Street Journal with him and he read
that.''
   Wendie Marriott, who organized the weekend race as the city's
recreation supervisor, said she heard that the team's runners
actually ran _ backward.
   ``The team was purposely trying to come in last, which it did,''
she observed. ``The idea was to clean up the mess at the end of the
race.''
   Nordlund said the team learned a lot from the experience.
   ``We'll do it better next time,'' he said. ``You can trust us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
