<FIRST>r w PM-DCDrugWar-Glance     04-11 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC Drug War-Glance,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Components of New U.S. Drug Program in D.C.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC Drug War Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are some of the major
components of the federal effort to curb drugs and drug-related
violence in the District of Columbia proposed by national drug
control policy director William J. Bennett.
   _JAIL AND PRISON SPACE:
   Some 250 inmates now housed at the local jail will be moved to
federal prisons. The administration will find excess federal land
for construction of a 500-bed pretrial detention facility to be
built within one year. The federal Bureau of Prisons will build
within two years a 700-bed correctional institution for the
Washington-Baltimore area.
   _LAW ENFORCEMENT:
   Expansion of the current task force which combines federal,
state and local law enforcement officials to include 57 more people
including 25 FBI agents, 11 Drug Enforcement Administration agents
and five intelligence analysts from the Defense Department.
   In addition, the Pentagon will assign 10 military lawyers to
augment the U.S. attorney's staff and the local National Guard will
help the task force in an as-yet-undetermined way.
   The FBI will provide access to its own information and its
laboratory as well as perform forensic examinations of firearms and
other evidence found during drug-related murder investigations.
   _PUBLIC HOUSING:
   The Housing and Urban Development Department will ease
regulations covering eviction of drug offenders from federally
funded housing projects.
   HUD, with help from the local police, will try to revitalize
local housing projects by such actions as the issuance of photo
identification cards to legitimate tenants, erection of security
fences around projects, establishment of guarded entrances and
refurbishment of projects.
   _TREATMENT PROGRAMS:
   The Health and Human Services Department will authorize the
National Institute of Drug Abuse to establish three model
outpatient clinics that will provide at least 300 new treatment
slots by 1990. In addition, NIDA will provide immediate technical
assistance in the district's current treatment programs.
   _JOBS:
   The Labor Department will expand its local summer training and
education program, work with private employers to recruit more
young people for job-training programs, and grant $100,000 to
establish employee assistance programs for drug abuse in small- and
medium-sized businesses.
   _EDUCATION:
   The Education Department, which by law must increase funds for
drug prevention programs in Washington by 50 percent to $1.4
million, also will expedite applications for additional funds and
programs to help the drug education effort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
