<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Reagan     04-11 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Reagan,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Nixon Asks No Reagan-Bashing in Bush White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Richard Nixon didn't like
hearing that former President Reagan was the object of criticism by
some members of George Bush's White House.
   Nixon fired off a letter to Bush's chief of staff John Sununu
saying as much. Sununu issued a decree that any such bad-mouthing
was to cease.
   And the whole matter came to the attention of Bush, who wrote
Nixon a note on the subject, according to Nixon's spokesman.
   Fitzwater said Sununu sounded off during a recent senior staff
meeting, after a Knight-Ridder Newspapers Inc. story quoted several
current White House officials anonymously as comparing Reagan
unfavorably with Bush.
   The comparisons focused on Bush's active work shedule and
Reagan's reputation for leaving detail to aides and keeping short
hours.
   Fitzwater would not say whether the Nixon complaint caused
Sununu's order that aides refrain from criticizing the former
president.
   He said that Bush and Reagan speak frequently on the phone and
that Bush has the ``highest respect'' for the man who made him vice
president.
   ``Most of us owe our careers'' to the former president, he said,
noting that he and others, including Secretary of State James A.
Baker III, had worked in the Reagan White House.
   John Taylor, a spokesman for Nixon in Saddle River, N.J.,
confirmed that Nixon had written Sununu complaining about the
story. ``As a matter of fact, President Bush dropped President
Nixon a note last week,'' Taylor said.
   In a March 23 story, Knight-Ridder White House correspondent
Owen Ullmann quoted several top-level aides to Bush, including some
who had worked for Reagan, as saying such things as that Reagan
would still have been asleep at 7 a.m. _ the hour Bush usually
arrives at the Oval Office.
   Fitzwater dressed down Ullmann during Monday's White House news
briefing, accusing the reporter of making up quotes. Later in the
morning, Fitzwater apologized for the personal attack on Ullmann,
but didn't discuss any further the merits of the story.
   At the briefing, Fitzwater said that ``I don't know anybody who
has been bad-mouthing former President Reagan.''
   Fitzwater said that Sununu told staff aides, ``Don't get caught,
you know, making jokes or being lighthearted or anything about the
past.'' He quoted Sununu as saying, ``I don't know whether this is
true or not, but if it is, don't let it happen.''
</TEXT>
