<FIRST>r w PM-JunkParts     04-11 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Junk Parts,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Audit: Military Stuck with Millions Worth of Useless Parts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military has a multimillion-dollar
stockpile of useless spare parts because contractors fail to follow
specifications and the government neglects to check the shipments,
a Defense Department auditor told Congress.
   A two-year audit conducted at the Warner Robins Air Logistics
Center in Georgia concluded an estimated $104 million worth of
parts failed to conform ``to essential or critical operational
characteristics,'' according to a report released Monday to the
Senate Governmental Affairs Committee.
   The report detailed problems both with the way government
contractors ship out parts and the way the military accepts and
pays for parts without making sure they meet rigidly drawn
specifications.
   ``Obviously we have a lot of material out there that is not
combat-ready,'' Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, told a hearing of the
committee, which he chairs. ``I want to know why we are accepting
substandard parts.''
   Maj. Gen. Richard Smith of the Air Force Logistics Command told
Glenn he would order spot inspections of parts as they're delivered.
   And Brig. Gen. M.J. Pepe of the U.S. Army Defense Logistics
Agency told Glenn the Army has started to equip its depots with
equipment to test parts as they come in.
   ``It's obvious we need to do more checking,'' Pepe said. ``We
hadn't been doing enough checking.''
   In addition, since July 1988 competitive contracts have included
a one-year warranty requiring replacement or refund of substandard
parts, Smith said.
   Derek Vander Schaaf, deputy inspector general for the Defense
Department, said the audit covered spare parts chosen randomly from
the Warner Robins warehouse.
   About 58 percent, or $12.9 millon worth, of the gun parts tested
in the study were unusable. Only 8 percent of examined gun parts,
with such functions as feeding ammunition into 20mm and 30mm
aircraft-mounted guns, conformed to specifications, the audit
report said.
   Tests of mounted bearings, which are used in aircraft landing
gears and wing flaps and on helicopter main rotor heads, indicated
38 percent conformed to specifications and 30 percent were unusable.
   Below-standard parts routinely were accepted and used, though
the failure to conform to specifications meant they didn't last as
long as they would have if they met the standards, the report said.
   Vander Schaaf said auditors found numerous examples of
contractors who shipped defective parts to one branch of the
service, but other branches weren't told of the problems and gave
the same contractor orders for identical or similar parts.
   In one case, ``one part of the Air Logistics Center gave new
work to a contractor while another part of the same Logistics
Center hauled $1.5 million worth of the same contractor's parts to
the scrap yard,'' Vander Schaaf testified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
