<HEAD>Evacuations Ordered Over Fear of Toxic Smoke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a chemical plant sent smoke
billowing over a community east of here on Monday night, prompting
most of the town's evacuation, authorities said.
   There were unconfirmed reports that up to 35 people, including
one firefighter, suffered ill effects from the smoke, said Ventura
County sheriff's Sgt. Gary Backman.
   ``The deputies out there tell me you don't have to be out there
too long before you feel the pressure in your chest,'' he said.
   About 200 residents of Saticoy were evacuated from the northeast
portion of the unincorporated town a few hours after the blaze
began, but that was later expanded to include most of the town,
Backman said.
   The blaze erupted around 6 p.m. in a small chemical plant called
Pacific Intermediaries and continued burning five hours later.
   It was not immediately known what chemical was involved.
   ``It's a hazardous material that's water-reactant, which means
they can't use water to put it out, but they're about to dump about
50 tons of sand on it,'' a California Highway Patrol dispatcher
said late Monday night.
   A half-mile section of busy Highway 118 was shut down as a
precaution because of the smoke, and was expected to remain closed
through the night, the dispatcher said.
   Ventura is 75 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
