<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains Slightly, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar marginally rose against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices sharply rebounded on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 132.62 yen, down 0.09 yen from Monday's
close of 132.53 yen. The currency opened at 132.87 yen and
fluctuated within a range of 132.60-132.89 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
186.03 points Monday, recouped 250.56 points, or 0.76 percent, to
finish trading at 33,249.58.
   Dealers said the index started lower amid political
uncertainties prior to parliamentary testimony by Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita Tuesday morning about receiving political
donations from the firm at the center of a major stock-profiteering
and bribery scandal.
   Takeshita said he had received about $1 million from the firm.
He denied taking bribes and continued to fend off opposition calls
for his resignation.
   Investors were reassured as Takeshita said nothing new, a dealer
at a major securities firm said on condition of anonymity.
   Opposition parties have stalemated parliamentary proceedings,
demanding a full accounting of governing Liberal Democratic Party
politicians' involvement in the scandal surrounding information
services conglomerate Recruit Co.
   On the foreign exchange, participants mainly adjusted their
dollar positions due to a lack of market-affecting incentives, said
a trader at the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Currency traders reacted to Takeshita's statements by buying
yen, pushing the dollar slightly lower, he said.
   ``The yen edged up as some investors got relieved and bought the
currency because Takeshita didn't say anything shocking before the
Parliament this morning,'' he said.
