<FIRST>r a PM-HaitianHijack     04-11 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Haitian Hijack,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haitians Face Air Piracy Charges In Hijack of Missionary Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Duer, Cap Haitien cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Haitian soldiers who fired their way aboard a
small plane before hijacking it to Florida were being questioned
about their role in a recent failed coup attempt in Haiti,
authorities and witnesses said.
   The plane was carrying eight people, including three American
missionaries, when the Fort Lauderdale-bound flight was hijacked
Monday. No one was injured.
   Passengers said the soldiers did not threaten them and had hoped
to talk to President Bush.
   The two were to be arraigned this afternoon on air piracy
charges charges, said Paul Miller, an FBI spokesman.
   Witnesses said the pair ran out waving guns and shooting in the
air Monday on the tarmac at Cap Haitien airport on Haiti's northern
coast, and forced their way onto the twin-engine Cessna 402.
   They threw down their weapons and surrendered upon arrival at
Miami International Airport, the FBI said.
   ``These guys were pretty upset,'' said pilot Duer Smedley.
``They were desperate to get out of Haiti. They're not like
terrorists from Lebanon. They are not looking to hurt anyone. They
are just looking for a way out of the country.''
   Guillaume Berlioze, 25, and Fadael Milord, 29, both of the
Haitian capital Port-au-Prince, were armed with a .38-caliber
revolver, an assault rifle and a 40mm anti-tank shell, the FBI said.
   They were questioned by the FBI and transferred to the
Metropolitian Correctional Center.
   Miller said investigators weren't certain of the motive behind
the hijacking, but, ``there are indications that they are against
the government.'' Police sources at Cap Haitien, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the hijackers had deserted from the
Dessalines Battalion.
   The battalion, with 750 soldiers, is one of two military units
that tried to bring down Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, Haiti's military
president, on April 2.
   By Monday, Avril's loyal 1,100-member Presidential Guard
appeared to have quieted rebellious outbreaks.
   Smedley said the pair told him they wanted to talk to Bush after
they surrendered.
   ``I asked him where he wanted to go and he said `Miami, Miami, I
have a lot of things to tell Bush,''' the pilot said.
   ``The military has been fighting down there for the last week,''
Smedley said. ``I think these guys were just on the losing side. I
got the impression that they thought if they stayed in Haiti, they
would be killed.''
   Passenger Larry Keyser, a missionary from South Barrington,
Ill., said the hijack was frightening at first.
   ``They scared us,'' Keyser said. ``But they were basically
harmless. They actually expected President Bush to be waiting for
them outside the plane.''
   ``They were more scared then we were,'' said another missionary,
Cindy Kato of Tallahassee.
   Kato, Keyser and the other missionary aboard, Rob Wilkins, also
of South Barrington, are members of the Missionary Aviation
Fellowship of Redlands, Calif.
   Four Haitians also were on the flight, said fellowship
spokeswoman Donna Burns.
   The Christian fellowship was founded in 1945 and operates 145
aircraft, primarily to fly doctors, medical supplies and
missionaries to Third World countries.
   In October 1987, a fellowship single-engine plane was hijacked
in Suriname. The pilot was held by a rebel guerrilla group before
being released unharmed.
</TEXT>
