<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 0529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hostages     04-11 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon Hostage Came Within Minutes Of Being Released, Sister Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teacher Brian Keenan, who marked his third
anniversary as a hostage in Lebanon today, came within 10 minutes
of being released in January before something mysteriously went
wrong, said his sister, Elaine Spence.
   ``Our hopes were highest in January and we now know that Brian
was 10 minutes away from being released,'' Mrs. Spence said in a
British Broadcasting Corp. radio interview.
   ``He was clean shaven. He had fresh clothes. His hair was cut
and he was ready for release.''
   Mrs. Spence said that she and her sister Brenda Gillham were
wating patiently at a hotel in Dublin with a plane standing by to
fly them to Syria as soon as they received word their brother was
free.
   ``Then suddenly, within a split second, our hopes died,'' she
said. ``We don't know what went wrong and we still don't know what
happened.''
   Mrs. Spence did not indicate the source of the family's
information.
   Keenan, 38, disappeared while walking to work at the American
University of Beirut on April 11, 1986. No one has claimed
responsibility for holding him.
   The Belfast man has dual British and Irish citizenship.
   Mrs. Spence also said she was bitter that the controversy over
author Salman Rushdie may have hampered efforts to release her
brother.
   Britain and Iran broke diplomatic ties in February after Iranian
leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini called for the murder of
Rushdie, a British citizen, for his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
Many Moslems consider the book blasphemous.
   ``With the like of the Salman Rushdie case, yes, I did get very
bitter with him,'' Mrs. Spence said. ``Salman Rushdie was a Moslem,
a person of the Moslem faith. There was my brother. His life was
held against Salman Rushdie's.''
   Mrs. Gillham said: ``It has been a very, very hard three years.
We have had no life whatsoever because our whole life revolves
around Brian. We keep thinking of him, even in our sleep.
   ``We dream about Brian, about the people holding him, what they
are fighting about and hope someday he'll come back to us.''
   Keenan is one of 15 foreigners, nine of them Americans, missing
in Lebanon. The longest-held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped on March
16, 1985.
   On Monday, Jill Morrell, girlfriend of missing British
journalist John McCarthy, met Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe,
but said she was ``disappointed'' in the government's strategy to
secure the hostages' release.
</TEXT>
