<FIRST>r i PM-France-Crash     04-11 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Crash,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twenty-Two Die In Crash Of Chartered Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALENCE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators dug through the wreckage of
a twin-engine Fokker 27 aircraft today hoping to find the flight
recorders that might shed light on why the plane crashed, killing
all 22 people aboard.
   There was no immediate explanation for what caused the plane to
smash into a 300-foot cliff in the wooded, mountainous area 15
miles east of Valence at about 9:10 p.m. Monday.
   Within a few hours of the crash, rescue workers had recovered
the bodies of the 19 passengers and three crew members aboard the
Uni-Air plane, chartered by Europe Aero Service, en route to
Valence from Paris.
   The plane broke apart from the impact, spreading wreckage over
several hundred yards, police in Valence said. They said victims'
bodies were taken to a nearby chapel for identification.
   Valence is located on the Rhone River, 41 miles south of Lyon.
   Investigators searched this morning for the flight data recorder
and cockpit voice recorder that might reveal what happened in the
final moments of the flight.
   Air controllers at the regional center near Lyon said the pilot
reported a routine approach to the airport and no particular
problems during his last contact, about eight minutes before the
aircraft's scheduled arrival.
   They said the plane was flying at an altitude of about 3,000
feet when it disappeared from radar.
   There was a light fog, a ceiling of about 5,000 feet and fair
visibility at the time of the crash.
   ``The plane passed about a dozen meters above my house and right
away I knew that it would not clear the cliff,'' said a resident of
the village of Barbiere adjacent to the crash site.
   ``Then I heard a terrifying explosion and I called the fire
department,'' said the man, who declined to provide his name.
   On March 4, 1988, another twin-engine Fokker 27 en route from
Nancy to Paris crashed in the countryside, killing 23 people. The
final report from that investigation provided no reason for the
crash.
</TEXT>
