<FIRST>r a PM-SalernoPlea     04-11 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salerno Plea,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Fat Tony' Salerno Pleads Guilty To Extortion, Racketeering Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man described by prosecutors as one of
the nation's most powerful crime bosses pleaded guilty for the
first time and cried before a federal judge as he admitted to
extortion and racketeering.
   Anthony ``Fat Tony'' Salerno, the 78-year-old reputed former
boss of the Genovese crime family, told the judge Monday he was
guilty of trying to wrest control of a Morris County sand-pit
business and trying to extort $500,000 from its owner, Andrew
Giordano.
   Salerno already is serving a 100-year sentence for his 1986
conviction as a mob boss in the New York trial of the Mafia's
ruling ``Commission.''
   Salerno could be sentenced to an additional five years in prison
and fined up to $10,000 in the New Jersey case.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. said the New Jersey charges
were warranted despite Salerno's long prison sentence.
   ``The purpose of this indictment was not to increase his
sentence, but to demonstrate to the citizens of New Jersey the
dangers posed by La Cosa Nostra, and the degree to which the
highest levels of the Mafia have infiltrated and affected their
lives,'' Alito said.
   Salerno's attorney, John Jacobs, said the guilty pleas did not
mean Salerno participated in the offenses.
   ``It was an accommodation to avoid trial,'' said Jacobs, who
pointed out that a medical condition caused by a 1981 stroke
affects Salerno's emotional state and caused him to cry at Monday's
hearing.
   Special U.S. Attorney Jeffrey A. Bronster said the reputed crime
boss's plea shows he was involved in the allegations.
   ``He has pleaded guilty to the charges, I'd say that's admitting
his guilt,'' Bronster said.
   The gravelly voiced Salerno walked into the courtroom with the
aid of a cane.
   He repeatedly answered ``Yes'' when Judge John W. Bissell asked
him if he understood the charges and wished to plead guilty. He
cupped his hands over his face and cried several times.
</TEXT>
