<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     04-11 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Shell Christian Positions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners today shelled a Christian
army position outside Beirut and tension rose about a possible
violent Moslem response to the expected arrival of two French ships
with humanitarian aid.
   Police said no casualties were reported from the brief Syrian
howitzer barrage against the deserted town of Souk el-Gharb, about
15 miles southeast of Beirut.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing
rules, said ``there was no response from the Christian side to the
barrage.''
   Shells fired by army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's mostly
Christian troops and by Syrian army gunners exploded in Christian
and Moslem districts on Monday, killing two people and wounding 15.
   That raised the toll to 180 people killed and 619 wounded since
the current round of civil war fighting erupted on March 8.
   Aoun had declared a ``war of liberation'' against Syrian forces.
The Syrians have responded by shelling the 310-square-mile
Christian enclave.
   Syria is the country's main power broker with 40,000 troops
deployed in predominantly Moslem areas covering 70 percent of
Lebanese territory under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   France, which ruled Lebanon from the end of World War I until
independence in 1943, has voiced concern about the fate of
Lebanon's Christian community and sent a special envoy in an effort
to contain the crisis.
   The French government has not specified an arrival date for two
ships carrying humanitarian aid that set sail for Lebanon last
week, but press reports in Paris and Beirut said they were due
Wednesday.
   One vessel carries fuel and food. The other is a hospital ship
with beds, surgical facilities and medical supplies.
   There are fears the ships' arrival could trigger heavier
fighting.
   Lebanese Moslem and leftist leaders have rejected their share of
the French aid. Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt, whose Progressive
Socialist Party militia is Syria's main ally in the current
confrontation with the Christians, also warned the French ships
against docking at any Christian port.
   The French envoy, Jean-Francois Deniau, accused Syria of trying
to block his mission by ordering its gunners last week to shell the
French embassy in Beirut's Christian suburb of Hazmiyeh where he
was staying.
   Deniau, vice president of the national assembly's foreign
affairs committee, warned today that opening fire at the French
ships ``would be an act of war against France.''
   The present confrontation broke out after Aoun ordered a
blockade of militia-run ports that have been stripping the state
treasury of about $100 million annually in taxes.
</TEXT>
