<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia 1stLd-Writethru   04-11 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0489,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Not Leaving Namibia, South African Authorities Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 12-18, `South Africa...its forces.' with eight grafs
to UPDATE with guerrilla leader describing difficulty reaching guerrillas
and to move up Ahtisaari's reference to radio broadcasts; picks up last
graf pvs: Ahtisaari said...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN PARKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa today said black
nationalist guerrillas did not appear to be honoring an agreement
to leave Namibia so the territory's transition to independence can
resume.
   Guerrillas were to congregate at designated points so they can
be escorted to Angola under an agreement by South Africa, Angola
and Cuba.
   The agreement was reached in an effort to end fighting between
South African-led security forces and the guerrillas in northern
Namibia. The bloodshed began April 1, the day a U.N.-sponsored
truce was to begin as part of Namibia's transition to independence
after 74 years of South African rule.
   Chief Inspector Kierie du Rand of Namibia's paramilitary police
reported ``a few skirmishes'' with South-West Africa People's
Organization guerrillas today and Monday.
   Du Rand put the latest death toll in the fighting at 265
guerrillas and 28 security force members.
   He said there was no sign that guerrillas were honoring an
agreement to cross the border north to Angola.
   ``About 10 small groups of three to seven men each have crossed
into Angola since Sunday, but that could be to re-supply themselves
or to rest,'' du Rand said. ``There is no indication of any major
movement north to the assembly points.''
   South Africa says about 1,900 SWAPO fighters began entering
Namibia on April 1, violating the U.N. agreement that calls for the
guerrillas to remain at their Angola bases until mid-May.
   It said the incursion might have been a deliberate attempt to
take advantage of the late deployment of a U.N. monitoring force,
and thus influence Namibian elections later in the year.
   Some Namibian observers said SWAPO units apparently did not know
they were breaking the peace accord by entering the territory.
   SWAPO leader Sam Nujoma contended in Angola that some guerrillas
had been in Namibia all along, and had a right to be there. On
Sunday, reportedly under pressure from his Angolan and Cuban
allies, Nujoma ordered his fighters to leave Namibia.
   U.N. representative Martti Ahtisaari said messages were being
broadcast on radio advising guerrillas to go to churches in the
north as a preliminary step before reporting to U.N. assembly
points.
   Nujoma said Monday in a radio interview with the British
Broadcasting Corp. that there is confusion about how to spread word
of the withdrawal to his fighters. He said radio broadcasts were
useless because the guerrillas had no radios.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I and, until last
year, defied U.N. resolutions demanding that it withdraw. It has
agreed to a U.N.-brokered regional peace accord with Cuba and
Angola.
   Under the agreement, Cuba is pulling 50,000 troops out of
Angola, where they had fought Angolan rebels backed by South Africa.
   About 100 British and Australian troops moved into northern
Namibia under the U.N. flag Monday to help monitor the SWAPO
pullout. The guerrillas had until Saturday to leave but Louis
Pienaar, South African administrator general in Namibia, said the
deadline might not be strictly enforced if SWAPO needed more time.
   In Oshakati, a military stronghold in northern Namibia, police
Chief Inspector Derek Brune said helicopter gunships were used
Monday in a skirmish at Ruacana, near the Angolan border.
   ``We are not going out to look for SWAPO at this stage. We are
giving them a chance to gather at the assembly points,'' he said.
   Ahtisaari said no official cease-fire was in effect but that
South Africa would restrain its forces.
   Ahtisaari said each assembly point would be staffed by 10 U.N.
soldiers and five monitors, and would fly blue and white U.N.
flags. He said other U.N. personnel, monitoring the Cuban
withdrawal in Angola, would escort SWAPO fighters to Angolan bases.
</TEXT>
