<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-MoneyFound     04-11 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Money Found,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Finds 100 Million Yen In Bamboo Thicket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 39-year-old restaurant owner looking for bamboo
shoots in a thicket found a bag containing about 100 million yen
($758,000), police said today.
   A police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
money may be connected with some crime because no one reported it
missing, although it apparently had been in the bamboo thicket for
several years.
   He said Seiei Sato, who owns a small shop that serves grilled
meat on a stick, reported the discovery to police today.
   The official said about a quarter of the cash had rotted and
other bills were damp and fragile. Some of the money _ all
10,000-yen bills _ was bundled with bank tape dated from 1985 to
1986.
   He said the bag was found in a thicket about 35 feet from a road
in Kawasaki, just south of Tokyo.
   Under Japanese law, Sato can have the money if no one claims it
within six months.
   In 1980, Hisao Onuki, a company driver, found 100 million yen
wrapped in a cloth in the Ginza, a major Tokyo shopping district.
The owner of the money did not turn up and the money went to Onuki.
