<FIRST>r a PM-Fusion 1stLd-Writethru a0491 04-11 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0491,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Tech, Texas A&amp;M Researchers Duplicate Fusion Experiment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `Researchers at ...' to CORRECT to show that
Texas researchers have not definitively concluded they achieved fusion.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The container holding heavy water and an
electrode resembled a high school chemistry experiment. Only the
beeps of a neutron counter showed that nuclear fusion might really
be happening at room temperature.
   ``There's no question it's fusion,'' said Bill Livesay, a
metallurgist who worked on the project at Georgia Institute of
Technology here. ``I still don't believe it, even though I see it.''
   Researchers at Georgia Tech and at Texas A&amp;M University in
College Station, Texas, on Monday announced the results of separate
experiments that they said appeared to confirm a University of Utah
experiment that aroused tremendous skepticism when it was announced
last month.
   James Mahaffey, a senior researcher at Georgia Tech, said the
school's experiment began detecting the release of subatomic
neutron particles last weekend, a sure sign of fusion.
   ``It's open season on fusion,'' Mahaffey said.
   B. Stanley Pons, the chairman of the Utah chemistry department,
said he was elated and relieved by the announcements. He and a
colleague, Martin Fleischmann of the University of Southampton,
England, sent scientists around the world scrambling with their
March 23 announcement of a controlled fusion reaction.
   ``This is just incredible,'' Pons said in Salt Lake City. ``If
they indeed have measured the neutron production, that's a real
breakthrough. My sincere congratulations to Georgia Tech.''
   Nuclear fusion _ the melding together of two atoms with an
accompanying release of energy _ normally requires enormously high
temperatures. It is the energy source of the sun and hydrogen bombs.
   Scientists have sought for decades to harness fusion's power
because it holds the potential to provide an almost unlimited
supply of relatively clean, cheap energy.
   Unlike nuclear reactors that use fission _ the splitting of
atoms _ to derive power, fusion doesn't generate significant
radioactive waste.
   In the Georgia experiment, which was kept behind lead shielding,
probes that normally measure 40 neutrons an hour in background
radiation were measuring 600 an hour.
   Mahaffey cautioned that his team had not confirmed whether the
process produces more energy than it consumes.
   Texas A&amp;M researchers said their experiment generated a net
1.144 watts of energy in the form of heat. They didn't measure
neutrons.
   The Texas researchers believed the output was the result of
fusion but said they weren't ready to rule out the possibility that
a chemical reaction was the cause.
   ``This is a very unusual result, and we have not totally
dismissed the possibility of some unusual chemical process which we
might have not accounted for and we are currently exploring this
possibility further,'' said Charles Martin, an electro-chemist at
Texas A&amp;M.
   As in Utah, both the Georgia and Texas researchers used a
palladium electrode to pass electric current through heavy water, a
form of water that contains a heavy isotope of hydrogen. The
Georgia researchers said they cut the time needed for the palladium
to soak in heavy water by first baking it in a vacuum.
   ``There is a need for much more money for research in this area
if it is going to get the attention it deserves,'' said Martin.
``But that's not surprising since this didn't exist two weeks ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
