<FIRST>r a PM-ConfederateHome 1stLd-Writethru a0493 04-11 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Confederate Home, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0493,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closing Of Confederate Home Was Inevitable: Board</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 6th graf pvs, `In exchange ...' to ADD
that residents were not available for interviews; Note language in 12th
graf pvs, ``They've been ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RM1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN HAYWOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Confederate Home for Women, where eight
elderly daughters of Civil War soldiers were told they would be
taken care of for life, was doomed to close because of dwindling
financial support, its chairman said.
   Janet Burhans, president and chairman of the Board of Managers
for Needy Confederate Women, said Monday she was too embarrassed to
say how much money remained in the trust fund that supports the
home and women.
   The women, ages 84 to 98, will be moved to more modern quarters
20 miles outside of Richmond to make way for the Virginia Museum of
Fine Arts.
   The two-story building is nestled among the magnolias behind the
museum. Once the women are moved, the antiques filling the home
will be sold and the museum will move in.
   The women had signed over their belongings and any future
inheritances in exchange for their support at the home. They will
lose dozens of worn but valuable antiques in use in the home.
   In exchange for the home, the state will pay the cost for the
women to live at a suburban retirement center.
   Officials at the home declined requests to interview the
residents on Monday.
   The home _ with its parquet floors, arched doorways, marble
fireplace, antique furniture and portraits of Confederate heroes _
was built in 1931 and now needs extensive repairs, Ms. Burhans said.
   She said replacing the roof cost $300,000. The home also needs
new plumbing and a new heating system, which would cost four times
that amount, she said.
   ``The state was not going to appropriate the money to repair the
home as a residence for eight ladies,'' she said. As many as 79
women once lived there.
   Not all the board members were in favor of moving the women.
   ``The museum wants our home,'' said board member Faye Oliff.
``They want it so bad.
   ``They've been like damn vultures waiting for the ladies to die
so they can get it.''
   Ms. Oliff said she tried unsuccessfully to persuade other board
members to open the home to paying descendants of Confederate
soldiers. The board also denied her proposal that a smaller home
for the women be opened about eight blocks away.
   Ms. Burhans said watching the women leave will be hard. They
will be taken to see a retirement home this week.
   ``They are very well-adjusted,'' said Holly C. DeJarnette, the
home's administrator.
   The home's board is to meet Thursday to decide where the women
will go, Ms. Burhans said.
</TEXT>
