<FIRST>r a PM-DeadwoodGambling     04-11 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deadwood Gambling,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Rush City Hopes to Recapture Boom Times With Return to Gambling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEADWOOD, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in the town where Wild Bill Hickok
was gunned down in a card game were asked today to take their
community back to the days of the Wild West and approve poker,
blackjack and slot machines.
   Under an amendment to the South Dakota Constitution last year,
gambling limited to $5 bets will be allowed if 60 percent of
Deadwood voters approve it.
   Mayor Tom Blair predicted gambling would attract at least
200,000 additional tourists a year. He estimated gaming could
generate $500,000 to further promote tourism by restoring an Old
West look to the Gold Rush town.
   ``While we're trying to go forward economically, we're going to
the past to give us that boost,'' Blair said.
   A recent telephone survey of 900 of Deadwood's 1,200 registered
voters confirmed widespread support for legalized gambling, the
mayor said.
   A muted minority has opposed gambling as promoting lawlessness.
   ``There is opposition here in town, and it's basically on moral
grounds,'' said the Rev. Don Hadrick of the United Methodist Church.
   Hickok, the U.S. marshal and frontiersman, was shot in the back
of the head during a poker game at a saloon called No. 10 in 1876.
Legend has it he was clutching a pair each of aces and eights,
ever-after known as the ``dead man's hand.''
</TEXT>
