<FIRST>r a PM-DefenseInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a04hestatepostheleftamonthagotojointhecommission.Inthepost
04-11 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Operation Ill Wind' Jury Deliberates Second Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New lead with jury resuming deliberation; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, The four women.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury resumed deliberating today whether
three executives with a California company took part in the bribery
of a Navy official in order to win a $24 million contract from the
military.
   The four women and eight men weighing the case against Dale
Schnittjer, Eugene Sullivan and George Kaub began studying the
evidence at mid-afternoon on Monday, exactly a week after the trial
started.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Williams allowed jurors to go home
after they failed to reach a verdict in eight hours.
   All three defendants are former vice presidents at Teledyne
Electronics in Newbury Park, Calif. All are charged with
conspiracy, bribery and wire fraud for a scheme the government says
involved paying bribes to a Navy engineer in exchange for his
confidential information about a $24 million contract to build
hand-held radar equipment.
   Kaub is also charged with two counts of making false statements.
All the charges carry sentences of five years, except for bribery,
which carries a 15-year penalty. The fine is $250,000 on each count.
   ``This was a case about bribery, cheating and lying _ that's
exactly what it was,'' said assistant U.S. attorney Joseph Aronica,
summing up the case in his closing argument.
   The government tried to show in the trial that Schnittjer, Kaub
and Sullivan knew a private consultant hired by Teledyne
Electronics had paid bribes to Stuart Berlin, the Navy engineer.
   But defense attorneys depicted their clients as victims of a
conspiracy perpetrated by Berlin, private consultants William
Parkin and Fred Lackner and Michael Savaides, Teledyne's marketing
representative in Washington.
   Stanley Mortenson, Schnittjer's attorney, said his client had
``nothing to do in that decision'' to pay Parkin, he said. ``Dale
Schnittjer is innocent.''
   Parkin, Berlin, Lackner and Savaides have pleaded guilty and are
cooperating with the government in the first trial arising from the
``Operation Ill Wind'' investigation that began nearly three years
ago. The investigation, which focused on the $150-billion-a-year
purchasing system at the Defense Department, attracted national
attention when search warrants were issued for offices
coast-to-coast last June.
   Teledyne Industries, the parent company of the electronics firm,
also pleaded guilty to conspiracy and making false statements. The
company paid a total of $4.3 million in fines, penalties and
damages.
   Mark Tuohey, Kaub's lawyer, said the executive was trapped
without knowing it by the actions of Parkin and his associates.
   ``This was their own conspiracy ... their conspiracy to defraud
Teledyne and then hide the ball,'' he said, referring to Parkin and
his compatriots. ``My client was kept in the dark,'' said George
O'Connell, Sullivan's attorney.
   But Aronica said the Teledyne executives were part of the scheme
to defraud the government. They were responsible for agreeing to
pay Parkin $10,000 in November 1985 to help win the radar contract.
   Once the contract was awarded, Parkin's deal called for him to
receive $150,000, a portion of which he got before Ill Wind was
made public.
   ``But for these defendants, the grease for the skids would not
have flowed,'' Aronica said.
   ``They aided and abetted in getting the money to Parkin,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
