<FIRST>r a PM-EmbattledEducator 1stLd-Writethru a0464 04-11 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Embattled Educator, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0464,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Schools Chief, Criticized About Leadership Abilities, May
Lose Job</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to DELETE mention of racial issue, which
is unsupported. PICKS UP 12th graf pvs, `You really ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's first black school superintendent may
lose his job four years after many hailed his hiring as another
step in healing racial bitterness that stemmed from court-ordered
busing.
   The Boston School Committee is expected to vote whether to renew
the contract of Laval S. Wilson. Even though the committee voted
8-5 in October to rehire him, months of debate has changed some
members' minds.
   A recent straw poll showed six opposing renewal, five favoring
it and two undecided.
   Wilson's detractors say he lacks leadership abilities and accuse
him of not doing enough to lower the high dropout rate.
   Supporters of the 53-year-old Chicago native say he needs more
time to develop his programs and begin new ones. They also say
Wilson is dedicated and hard-working.
   The city has been rocked by racial tension and violence in the
years following the 1974 desegration order.
   ``This isn't a racial issue, it's a competence and quality
issue,'' said Peggy Davis-Mullen, a white member of the board.
``He's a diligent worker, but his approach isn't meeting the needs
of the children of Boston.''
   Although the school budget has increased in four years by about
$100 million, to $361 million, Mrs. Davis-Mullen said the dropout
rate has gone up. ``I don't think he has a firm grasp of the type
of students we have here,'' she said.
   In 1972, enrollment was 96,000, 60 percent of them white. Today,
there are 59,000 students, 24 percent white.
   School committee member Jean McGuire, who in 1985 voted against
hiring Wilson because of his conservative philosophies, said the
superintendent deserves more of a chance. She is one of four black
members on the board.
   ``You really can't get anything done changing horses in
midstream. Just changing who it is right now isn't going to change
a thing,'' she said. The system has had eight superintendents in
the last 19 years.
   Wilson also is backed by members of the Vault, the nickname for
a group of 25 prominent bankers and business executives interested
in education and urban issues.
   Vault Chairman Harold Hestnes, a lawyer, said Monday that
Wilson's difficulties were based on the size of the school
committee and its competing constituencies.
   ``Working with a 13-member school committee seems impossible to
me,'' Hestnes said. ``It's a difficult system under the best of
circumstances and he isn't in the best of circumstances.''
   Two committee members met with Wilson on Monday night, but
declined to comment.
   Wilson also has declined to comment. He did not return telephone
messages on Monday. His attorney, Fletcher Wiley, said the
committee was obligated to rehire him based on October's vote.
   Recently, at the request of the school committee, Wilson gave
himself a report card. He gave himself high marks for dedication,
for raising math and reading scores on national standardized tests
and for lowering the dropout rate.
   Test scores have risen only marginally, and the dropout rate is
in dispute.
   By Wilson's figures, fewer youngsters are quitting school. Other
school system figures, however, show increasing attrition in class
size between ninth grade and graduation day. The class of 1983 was
33 percent smaller than when it began; the class of '87 eroded by
40 percent.
   He said he could do better at sharing power and consulting with
community groups and parents. But his bottom line was that he
needed more time.
   ``The Boston public schools didn't develop problems overnight,
and neither Laval Wilson nor any other superintendent will solve
them overnight,'' Wilson wrote in the assessment.
   He said if he kept the job, he would push his Boston Education
Plan, which focuses on improving math and reading and giving
principals and teachers more latitude.
   One problem he's faced in the contract negotiations has been his
timing.
   Last fall, for example, he asked for an $18,000 housing
allowance on top of his $95,000 salary. The request came at a time
when school budget cuts loomed. After much criticism, he withdrew
the allowance proposal. He now is asking for a three-year contract
starting at $95,000, with future raises linked to what is given to
teachers and administrators.
   Shortly after he was hired, he was granted his request for a
$15,000 raise.
</TEXT>
