<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0518 04-11 0813</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0518,0837</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youths Protest After Gunman In Israeli Army Uniform Shoots Arabs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to update with three Jewish men detained.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs ``Police opened fire...'' </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said today they were holding three
Jewish men in connection with a submachine gun attack in which one
Palestinian was killed and three others were wounded.
   The announcement came shortly after police fired rubber bullets
at stone throwers, wounding one in the leg, during an hourlong
funeral march for the slain Palestinian.
   The three detainees ``are suspected of being linked to what
happened yesterday'' but are not suspected of the actual shooting,
Jerusalem Police spokesman Uzi Sanduri said.
   He declined to identify the men beyond saying two were from
Jerusalem and one lived elsewhere in Israel. The suspects were
detained Monday night and were still in custody, Sanduri said.
   Mourners decried Israel during the funeral procession through
the Temple Mount compound, some shouting ``We warn the Jews:
Mohammed's army will return.''
   Police opened fire after one youth smashed a window with his
fist and others broke two windows with rocks.
   About 1,000 relatives and friends took part in the funeral march
for Khaled Shawish, the 26-year-old blacksmith killed Monday when
an attacker, dressed in army fatigues and believed to be an
Israeli, opened fire with an Uzi submachine gun.
   The gunman, who escaped on foot, also wounded three other
Palestinians in the attack outside the Jaffa Gate entrance to the
Old Walled City of Jerusalem.
   A caller claiming to represent a Jewish extremist group claimed
responsibility for the shootings.
   Earlier today, several dozen masked Palestinian youths gathered
at Shawish's Old City home, waving Palestinian flags and vowing
revenge against Jews. Police watched from nearby rooftops.
   One youth, masked with a kafiyyeh and hoisted on the shoulders
of another, shouted: ``We should teach the Jews a lesson.
Everything Jewish in this town should be burned. We should prove
that this is Palestinian and teach them a lesson of what a
Palestinian state means.''
   Other youths shouted ``Revolution against the occupier!'' and
``We want a Palestinian state!''
   One Associated Press reporter taking notes was grabbed and
threatened by masked youths. Another was hit in the stomach with a
rock.
   In Arab east Jerusalem today, most merchants shuttered their
shops in a general strike called to protest Monday's shootings.
   A general strike today virtually closed the occupied Gaza Strip,
where leaflets from the Moslem fundamentalist Hamas movement urged
residents to protest the deportation of more than 40 Palestinians
by Israel during the 16-month Palestinian uprising.
   In the occupied West Bank city of Hebron, merchants shut their
shops today to mourn a 22-year-old Palestinian who was shot to
death in a clash with soldiers on Monday night.
   The death raised to 423 the number of Palestinians killed in the
uprising. Eighteen Israelis also have died.
   Arab reports said four Palestinians were wounded by army gunfire
during stone-throwing protests today in Gaza, including a
90-year-old woman who was hit by a bullet in the left leg in the
Shati refugee camp.
   Stoning protests were reported in Ramallah and several
neighboring West Bank camps, but there were no reported casualties.
   In Tel Aviv today, an Israeli teen-ager stabbed and wounded two
Arab youths from the Gaza Strip, injuring one of them seriously,
police said. The stabbings occurred during an argument that began
when the Palestinian youths sought to park their truck and unload
chickens outside a butcher shop, police spokesman Dalia Gilad said.
   Israel radio said the butcher's 17-year-old son threatened the
Palestinians and then stabbed them.
   An anonymous caller telephoned reporters Monday night to claim
responsibility for the shootings in Jerusalem for the Sicarites, a
group named after Jewish assassins who fought the Roman forces
nearly 2,000 years ago.
   The caller, who spoke Hebrew with a French or North African
accent, said the shootings were in retaliation for stone-throwing
attacks on Jews during the Palestinian uprising.
   Jerusalem police spokesman Uzi Sandouri said police were ``quite
sure the assailant was Jewish'' but had not determined his motive.
   Sicarites members have asserted responsibility or been blamed
for at least eight arson attacks against Israeli moderates. But
they have not attacked Arabs directly and there were no known
casualties in the previous incidents.
   Monday's shootings came as tensions ran high in the Old City.
About 350,000 Jews and 135,000 Arabs live in east Jerusalem, which
Israel seized in 1967 from Jordan and has annexed.
   Police Minister Chaim Bar-Lev announced Monday that some
Palestinian youths would be barred from praying at one of Islam's
holiest sites, the Al Aqsa mosque in Jerusalem, because of rioting
there Friday.
   During the riot by an estimated 4,000 Palestinians, rocks were
thrown near the Western Wall, Judaism's holiest shrine. Twelve
people were reported injured and 37 Arabs were arrested.
</TEXT>
