<FIRST>r a PM-ArchbishopNamed     04-11 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Archbishop Named,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>Named Baltimore Archbishop Appointed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop William Keeler of Harrisburg, Pa., was
named leader today of the nation's oldest archdiocese.
   Keeler, 58, succeeds Archbishop William D. Borders, who
submitted his resignation in accordance with church law after
turning 75 in October.
   Keeler, bishop in Harrisburg since 1984, was chairman of the
U.S. Bishop's Committee for Ecumenical and Interreligious Affairs
and arranged meetings between the pope and other faith groups
during the pope's U.S. visit in 1987.
   The Baltimore archdiocese covers nine counties and serves
438,000 Catholics. It was founded 200 years ago.
   A native of San Antonio, Texas, Keeler grew up in Lebanon, Pa.,
and earned degrees from St. Charles Seminary in Philadelphia and
Pontifical Gregorian University in Rome. He was ordained in 1955.
   Borders had headed the Baltimore archdiocese since 1974.
</TEXT>
