<FIRST>r a PM-ChevronFire     04-11 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chevron Fire,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire, Explosion At Chevron Plant; 6 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire and explosion at a Chevron
refinery shot flames 100 feet into the air and injured at least
seven workers fighting the blaze, authorities said.
   The fire, which burned for four hours Monday and sent a black
cloud over much of the eastern San Francisco Bay, cut production
capacity at Chevron's second-largest West Coast refinery by 25
percent, the company said.
   Chevron would not speculate on the amount of damage or predict
when the refinery, which produces gasoline and jet fuel, would be
back at full production.
   To make up the loss, Chevron said it will increase shipments
from its other Western refineries and from other areas, including
the Gulf of Mexico.
   Chevron was investigating the cause of the blast.
   At least four workers were hospitalized in stable condition with
burns or smoke inhalation, authorities said.
   There was no immediate word on the condition of others reported
hurt.
   Gas oil, which is processed into gasoline, burned during the
fire but did posed no danger to the public, said Chevron spokesman
Hal Holt.
