<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-US     04-11 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-US,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Open Letter Asks Bush To Stop Outside Interference in Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 600 international writers,
scientists, religious leaders, academics and artists have signed an
open letter asking President Bush to stop outside interference in
Nicaragua.
   Signatories ask Bush not to meddle in regional peace efforts and
to lift a U.S. trade embargo imposed against the leftist Sandinista
government four years ago. They suggest Bush talk directly to
Nicaraguan officials.
   ``We believe that good faith must be translated into actions.
This is the moment for you to restore direct dialogue with
Nicaragua,'' says the letter.
   A Spanish version was released to local and foreign journalists
by President Daniel Ortega's press office in Managua. An aide said
the letter would be published in New York today.
   It was signed, among others, by Cuban dancer Alicia Alonso,
Spanish poet Rafael Alberti, American actor Ed Asner, Italian film
director Bernardo Bertolucci, Brazilian composer Chico Buarque de
Holando and American composer and conductor Leonard Bernstein.
   Other signatories included actress Geraldine Chaplin and authors
Carlos Fuentes, Graham Greene, Gunter Grass and Gabriel Garcia
Marquez.
   Central American nations should be allowed to ``resolve on their
own their own affairs, without any foreign interference,'' the
letter said.
   ``Peace in Nicaragua must immediately be re-established.''
   To help bring peace, it said, foreign countries must support
accords reached by the five Central American presidents Feb. 14 in
El Salvador.
   At the February summit, Ortega promised to institute democratic
reforms and hold elections in February 1990, 10 months earlier than
planned.
   Ortega also freed nearly 2,000 National Guards jailed for almost
a decade since the July 1979 triumph of the Sandinista revolution.
   Ortega and the presidents of Guatemala, El Salvador, Costa Rica
and Honduras also agreed to produce by mid-May a plan for
dismantling the Nicaraguan rebel force known as the Contras.
   Some 11,000 Contra rebels, along with their families, have been
living at border camps in Honduras since Congress cut off lethal
aid to the U.S.-backed guerrillas in February 1988.
   Ortega has criticized Bush's recently announced proposal for a
Contra aid package of up to $45 million in humanitarian aid over 10
months.
   The Nicaraguan leader maintains it would hurt regional peace
efforts.
</TEXT>
