<HEAD>East, Midwest in Cold Snap; North Carolina Gets Rare April Snow</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with North Carolina snowfall, latest
in 110 years; Picks up 5th graf, `Snow showers ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A deep-freeze settled over the South today, bringing rare April
snow to North Carolina, while the Southwest continued to enjoy
unseasonably warm weather.
   Up to 4 inches of snow blanketed parts of North Carolina.
Wilmington, N.C., had its latest snowfall of the season in the 110
years that records have been kept.
   Freeze warnings were in effect over the central and southern
Appalachians, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, Missouri, Arkansas,
Oklahoma, and parts of Texas, Louisiana, Mississippi, Delaware,
Maryland, Virginia, the Carolinas and Alabama.
   Warm weather continued in the Southwest, with early-morning
readings in the 50s and 60s across much of California, southern
Nevada and southern Arizona.
   Rain fell along the East Coast from southeast Virginia across
the eastern half of the Carolinas and southeast Georgia to northern
Florida. The rain turned to snow and sleet in the northern and
central North Carolina.
   Snow showers also were scattered across portions of New York
state and northern New England, and light snow fell over western
Minnesota.
   Clear skies prevailed over the Pacific Northwest and much of the
Southwest. Today's forecast called for snow showers over Upper
Michigan and northern Wisconsin; rain or snow showers over southern
Wisconsin and scattered across southeastern New England; rain from
eastern Virginia across eastern sections of the Carolinas and
southeast Georgia to central Florida; and scattered showers over
southern Texas and the southern High Plains.
   Highs were expected to be in the 30s from eastern North Dakota
to upper Michigan and in northern Maine; in the 40s from the
northern Plains across the Great Lakes region and northern Ohio
Valley to the northern and middle Atlantic Coast; in the 70s across
the Florida Peninsula, from western Oregon across northern and
coastal California and western Nevada and southern New Mexico to
southwest Texas; in the 80s and 90s in the desert Southwest and the
interior of California; and in the 50s and 60s in much of the rest
of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 14
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 84 degrees at Las Vegas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 37 fair; Boston 33 cloudy; Buffalo 27 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 43 rain; Cincinnati 24 fair; Cleveland 29 fair;
Detroit 24 fair; Miami 71 fair; New York 37 cloudy; Philadelphia 37
cloudy; Pittsburgh 23 fair; Portland, Maine, 29 cloudy; Washington
38 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 32 partly cloudy; Chicago 31 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 40 fair; Denver 32 partly cloudy; Des Moines 27
fair; Indianapolis 27 fair; Kansas City 32 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 32 partly cloudy; Nashville 30 fair; New Orleans 47 partly
cloudy; St. Louis 33 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 41 fair; Anchorage 35 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 84 windy; Los Angeles 60 foggy; Phoenix 78 fair; Salt Lake
City 51 windy; San Diego 62 cloudy; San Francisco 51 partly cloudy;
Seattle 49 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 25 fair; Toronto 28 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
