<FIRST>u a PM-Eastern 2ndLd-Writethru a0527 04-11 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0527,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions Make Wage Pact But Hurdles Still Remain for Eastern Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `The unions ...' to change attribution; INSERTS
graf after 18th graf pvs, `Former Defense ...' to UPDATE with Carlucci's
name surfacing as possible trustee; SUBS next-to-last graf pvs to CLARIFY;
DELETES redundant final graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>RONALD BLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' unions agreed to big wage
concessions with Peter V. Ueberroth but added a demand that must be
resolved if the former baseball commissioner is to take control of
the airline by tonight's deadline.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent, Texas Air Corp.,
must accept those changes in the $464 million deal if the purchase
is to go forward, said sources speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The unions demanded that the bankruptcy court appoint a trustee
to operate Eastern as the airline emerges from Chapter 11, union
sources said.
   A union legal adviser told The Associated Press the demand was
aimed at assuring ``speedy and orderly transition.''
   ``We're more than a little concerned about what can happen while
Lorenzo is on his way out,'' the source said.
   An exhausted Ueberroth told reporters outside the courthouse
Monday evening, ``We have one more major bridge to cross ... and
that's right here in this courthouse. That bridge must be crossed.
... There's no guarantee we will cross it.''
   Ueberroth's deal with Texas Air is scheduled to expire at
midnight.
   ``We have not yet seen a copy of the agreement. We understand it
is very complex and we will study it,'' Texas Air spokesman Art
Kent said late Monday from the company's headquarters in Houston.
   ``There's no agreement as far as we're concerned,'' said Bruce
Zirinsky, a lawyer for Eastern who attended the New York meetings.
   After four days of intense negotiations, Ueberroth announced
that his investor group had reached ``a historic labor
partnership'' with leaders representing Eastern's Machinists,
pilots and flight attendants unions.
   Sources said the five-year agreement gives the unions a 30
percent share of Miami-based Eastern in exchange for $210 million
in pay cuts and work-rule concessions. The accord must be ratified
by rank-and-file members.
   Ueberroth and other parties to the talks have declined to give
details because of a gag order imposed by Bankruptcy Judge Burton
R. Lifland. Ueberroth said talks would continue today in an effort
to get Eastern, the nation's seventh-largest airline, back in the
air.
   Eastern has been largely grounded since Machinists struck March
4 and pilots and flight attendants walked out in support. The
airline filed for bankruptcy protection five days later.
   Under the agreement, the Machinists union would give up about
$150 million in wage and benefit cuts or ``essentially what Lorenzo
wanted us to take before the strike,'' a union source said. The
figures are smaller for other unions because after Lorenzo bought
Eastern three years ago, the pilots and flight attendants accepted
pay cuts, but the Machinists did not.
   The pact must be approved by Eastern's major creditors as well
as Texas Air.
   The agreement was reached early Monday in Washington, and
participants flew rival Pan Am Corp.'s shuttle to New York and
continued talks at the bankruptcy courthouse in Manhattan.
   Lawyers for Eastern and some of its creditors were at the
courthouse meetings.
   Former Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci also was present for
some of the meetings, but he declined to identify his role.
Carlucci is a vice chairman of the Carlyle Group, a Washington
investment firm.
   Union sources said Carlucci's name surfaced several weeks ago as
a possible candidate for the trustee position.
   Court-appointed examiner David I. Shapiro was instrumental in
forging the agreement with the unions, sources said. He had been in
almost non-stop meetings with Ueberroth's representatives in
Washington since Thursday night.
   ``It wouldn't have happened without him,'' said a participant in
the talks. Shapiro gave the impression he would have ``thrown
people in jail'' if they had walked out of the discussions, the
source said.
   The agreement also would cover 11,000 non-union employees,
including reservation clerks, ticket agents and clerical workers,
Ueberroth said.
   A representative of non-union employees, Mary Grace Shore, said
her group objected to not being represented in the talks.
   Eastern has said it could resume 80 percent of its pre-strike
schedule within about 10 days after a final agreement is approved
by all parties, although some union officials have said it could
take 45 days or longer.
</TEXT>
