<FIRST>r w PM-SovietEmigration     04-11 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Emigration,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>12 Long-Term `Refuseniks` Permitted to Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve long-term Jewish ``refuseniks,'' many
of whom were denied exit visas on grounds they knew state secrets,
have received permission to leave the Soviet Union, according to
the National Conference on Soviet Jewry.
   They are the largest single group to be granted visas at one
time since the summit meeting between former President Reagan and
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev last December in New York.
   Included in the list are Aleksandr Piatetsky of Kiev, who has
waited 15 years for a visa, Mark Berenfeld of Moscow, 12 years; and
Inna Gorenshrain of Leningrad, 12 years.
   Shoshana S. Cardin, chairman of the Soviet Jewry group, said in
a statement Monday: ``While we are encouraged by the resolution of
the cases of so many long-term refuseniks, we regret that many who
seek to emigrate are still denied their right to do so ....''
   Emigration from the Soviet Union last month was the highest
since October 1979.
   Knowledge of sensitive information was given frequently in the
past as a reason for denying visas to Jewish scientists or others
who had been involved in government work. One of the reforms
pledged by Gorbachev was to ease the restriction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
