<SECOND>PM-UN-Israel,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir to U.N.: No Need For Help Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel
emerged from talks with Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
today and said he sees no need for U.N. assistance in arranging
peace in the Middle East.
   Shamir, head of the right-wing Likud bloc, rejects the concept
of an international peace conference under U.N. auspices on the
grounds that Israel would be pressured to trade land for peace.
   ``The secretary-general expressed the general willingness and
readiness of the United Nations to help when it is asked for it,
and is ready always to do something,'' Shamir told reporters after
his 30-minute meeting with Perez de Cuellar.
   ``For the moment, there is not any necessity for it; if it will
be necessary, we will not hesitate to ask for it,'' said Shamir.
   ``I don't think that we see at this moment any special role for
the United Nations. If there would be any proposal connected with
the United Nations, we will discuss it with the
secretary-general,'' he added.
   Shamir is promoting a peace plan based on holding elections in
the Israeli-occupied territories so Palestinians could choose
representatives to negotiate with Israel over the future status of
the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Most Palestinians, including the Palestine Liberation
Organization, have rejected the concept of elections held under
Israeli rule, and insist on an independent Palestinian state.
</TEXT>
