<SECOND>PM-Chemical Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0496,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>1,500 Flee Homes Over Fear of Toxic Smoke</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with evacuees returning, road reopening.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,500 people evacuated when a fire
and explosions at a chemical plant sent smoke billowing over their
community were allowed back in their homes today after the fire
burned itself out.
   Two firefighters were hospitalized for treatment of headaches
and nausea after being exposed to fumes from the blaze Monday
evening at the Pacific Intermediates plant, said county Fire
Department spokeswoman Laura Kidd.
   The unincorporated community of Saticoy, about 75 miles from
downtown Los Angeles, was evacuated overnight because of possibly
toxic fumes.
   Battalion Chief Dick Perry said early today that more than 100
firefighters responded to the blaze but had to let it burn itself
out rather than risk exposure to toxic chemicals. The plant blends
chemicals for pharmacies.
   The company stocked acids, cyanide, explosive hydrogen and
corrosives, including some chemicals that react with water, Perry
said.
   ``Because of the chemicals, you can't use water on it. The fire
is burning through the roof with 75- to 100-foot flames,'' said
Denise Beaumont, another Fire Department spokeswoman.
   Firefighters hosed down an adjoining business and set up dikes
to prevent the possibly contaminated water from reaching the Santa
Clara River.
   Perry said Pacific Intermediates was cited last year for having
larger quanitities of chemicals than allowed on the premises. The
citation for violating county ordinances has yet to reach court, he
said.
</TEXT>
