<SECOND>PM-France-Prison Hostages,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prisoners Take Guards Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POISSY, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two hundred inmates today took 12 guards
hostage at a prison west of Paris, a Justice Ministry spokesman
said.
   About 300 police _ including several companies of riot police
wearing helmuts and carrying clubs _ encircled the prison.
Negotiations were under way between the deputy director and four
inmates.
   The guards were being held in the first-floor central hall, an
area that houses about 450 prisoners serving long sentences, the
ministry spokesman said.
   The prisoners, who did not have weapons, took the guards captive
at midday, the spokesman said. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   An unidentified official in Poissy told Agence France-Presse the
inmates ``offered no coherent demands and complained of
disciplinary problems.''
   After a dispute between a guard and inmate Monday night, the
prisoners refused to resume their normal routine this morning. They
later took the guards hostage, the ministry spokesman said.
   In November 1988, 250 inmates at the prison 23 miles west of
Paris occupied the central hall for 13 hours to protest ``bad
conditions of detention'' before returning peacefully to their
cells.
