<HEAD>Turkish Women March for Secular Society</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 women marched, sang, and
carried banners Tuesday to show their opposition to Moslem
fundamentalist groups advocating a return to Islamic law.
   The march, organized by labor unions and women's groups,
commemorated the 61st anniversary of Turkey becoming a secular
state under Kemal Ataturk. The women also expressed support for the
country's Western-style government.
   On April 10, 1928, the Turkish Parliament amended the
constitution to say that the young republic was a ``secular
state.'' Until then, the constitution established Islam as the
state religion.
   Pro-Western Turks and authorities are worried over spreading
Islamic fundamentalism. The fundamentalist Prosperity Party won
almost 10 percent of the vote in last month's local elections.
