<FIRST>r i AM-Nepal-India     04-11 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nepal-India,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomats Ask India to Supply Gas for Their Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign missions in Nepal have urged
India, which has halted most exports and transit to this landlocked
country in a border dispute, to let their diplomats have more
gasoline, diplomats said Tuesday.
   India closed most border checkpoints after Indo-Nepalese trade
and transport treaties expired March 23, effectively imposing an
economic blockage that has caused fuel, medicine and food shortages
and led to rationing.
   On Monday, news reports in Bangladesh said the move completely
shut down its nation's exports to Nepal, which were transported
through India.
   At the United Nations, about 50 Nepalese demonstrated Monday to
protest the border closings and appealed to India to reopen them.
   India closed 13 of 15 checkpoints along the 1,090-mile border
after the treaties expired. Nepal wants two new treaties, while
India demands a unified treaty combining transport and trade
agreements.
   In a statement Tuesday to Katmandu's 19 diplomatic missions, the
Foreign Office said diplomatic personnel could approach India for
supplies for their use since India's sanctions were aimed at the
Nepalese and not foreigners residing in Nepal.
   The diplomats made the request at a Friday meeting at the Indian
Embassy, said an Asian diplomat on condition of anonymity.
   One Western diplomat, also speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the weekly government gas ration for diplomats has been
reduced from 5.3 gallons per car immediately after March 23
closings to 4 gallons.
   Private motorists in Katmandu can buy 1.6 gallons a week, and
taxi drivers are allowed 15 liters. The rationing has led to long
queues at filling stations.
   For cooking fuel, housewives have turned increasingly to Nepal's
already dwindling forests because of a shortage of kerosene.
   ``We just get a ration of three liters (0.7 gallons) a week for
a family of seven members. Do you think it would be enough to
prepare the meals?'' asked one woman, Maya Devi Sakya.
   In Dhaka, the United News of Bangladesh news agency said more
than 20,000 tons of fertilizer sold to Nepal remains stockpiled in
Bangladesh ``for want of transit facilities through India.''
   The two neighbors have had friendly ties for years, but Nepal
has developed friendly political and economic ties with China,
which it borders along the Tibetan region. The Katmandu government
recently bought Chinese arms for its 30,000-strong military and
said they were needed to defend against domestic terrorist threats.
   India fought a bitter border war with China in 1962, and
relations still are strained.
   Nepal says it cannot play favorites in strategic politics and
needs good relations both nations. Its trade with China via Tibet
is minimal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
