<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-JailCamps     04-11 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jail Camps,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Authorizes County To Seize Property For `POW Style' Jail Camps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has authorized the sheriff to
seize public or private property for ``POW-style'' camps to relieve
jail overcrowding.
   District Judge Michael Schattman issued the order Monday in an
attempt to get the state to pay for housing its prisoners in county
jails.
   The state is under a federal court order to keep its prisons
below capacity and has refused to accept prisoners from most Texas
counties, leaving local jails overcrowded with inmates who have
been sentenced to state prison.
   County officials want to be reimbursed for housing such
prisoners.
   Schattman instructed Sheriff Don Carpenter to ``requisition on
the credit of the state of Texas'' any property needed for
temporary jails. Carpenter said he believes a warehouse in Fort
Worth would be a good site for a prison camp.
   The judge also instructed the sheriff to ask Gov. Bill Clements
to send National Guardsmen to patrol the compounds. If the governor
refuses, the judge authorized the sheriff to deputize as many
guards as he needs.
   The judge said the sheriff could set up ``however many POW camps
are needed'' to relieve jail overcrowding.
   Ryder Scott, general counsel to the governor, said state
officials are awaiting a copy of the ruling before deciding what
action to take.
   Officials said about 2,600 inmates are being held in the county
jail designed for 1,970 prisoners, and 1,100 of them are awaiting
transfer to state prison.
   The injunction resulted from a suit filed against the county by
former inmate Billy Wayne Markham, who claims he was raped and
beaten by other prisoners and alleged that the assaults resulted
from jail overcrowding.
   The judge ruled that the county jail is illegally overcrowded.
</TEXT>
