<FIRST>r i AM-MuseumStrike     04-11 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Museum Strike,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Closes Paris' Most Popular Tourist Attraction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Museum security workers turned away busloads of
visitors from the Pompidou art center Tuesday for the 13th day,
demanding Paris' most popular tourist attraction provide more jobs,
higher wages and better benefits.
   About 1,200 employees working in other departments of the
multifaceted center went on a 24-hour strike today in solidarity
with the security workers.
   Helene Ahrweiler, the center's new director, said their demands
are ``trifling matters.'' She was more concerned about cutting
costs, and said she is canceling a $1 million Andy Warhol
retrospective.
   Defiant guards turned away thousands of European tourists on
spring vacations who flooded the city.
   ``You can't come in. Can't you read the signs? We're on
strike,'' said one guard at the 12-year-old center.
   The Georges Pompidou center tops the Eiffel Tower as the
capital's most popular attraction.
   Mrs. Ahrweiler said she wants to find a global solution to
personnel problems.
   ``I'm the president of the whole center, and I want to avoid the
isolation of the various departments,'' she said in a telephone
interview.
   She was to meet today with Culture Minister Jack Lang to discuss
``the status, career development and salary policies of all museum
workers.''
   The center, built in 1977 to accommodate 5,000 visitors a day,
now welcomes five times that number.
   Mrs. Ahrweiler said she would make changes in management and
cancel shows to cut costs.
   ``We can make substantial savings,'' she said. ``I'm stopping
the Andy Warhol retrospective.''
   The restrospective, organized by and now displayed at the Museum
of Modern Art in New York, was to run in 1990 and cost the Pompidou
Center nearly $1 million.
</TEXT>
