<FIRST>u p PM-LAMayor 1stLd-Writethru a0479 04-11 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Mayor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0479,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tom Bradley Seeks Fifth Term as LA Mayor at Age 71</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs with no turnout figures immediately available,
turnout expected to hit a record low; PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `Even a ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters went to the polls today with Mayor Tom
Bradley so heavily favored for an unprecedented fifth term that
turnout was expected to hit an all-time low.
   Bradley, 71, needed to capture at least 50 percent of the votes
against nine opponents to avoid a June 6 runoff for the four-year
office. None of the candidates runs on a party line.
   The only serious challenger, freshman City Councilman Nate
Holden, has accused Bradley of ignoring his roots and the city's
impoverished south side and favoring big business and foreign trade.
   ``He's been in office too long,'' said Holden, who like Bradley
is black. ``They're not going to vote for him out of habit
anymore.''
   On Monday, City Clerk Lee Lee Martinez predicted turnout of 25
percent to 30 percent _ ``a historical low for a mayoral election.''
   Turnout figures were not immediately available this morning.
   But Bradley, the son of sharecroppers and grandson of slaves,
has managed to escape responsibility for many of the city's
problems, including drugs and gangs.
   Even a current investigation of Bradley by the city attorney's
office for performing consulting work with two banks that do
business with the city seemed to have had little effect on the
mayor. Bradley has returned the $18,000 fees he was paid and called
the charges politically motivated.
   Pollsters and would-be candidates conclude that Bradley, a
congenial former city police lieutenant and councilman, has managed
to be associated with Los Angeles' emergence as a Pacific Rim
economic power and growth as a multi-ethnic cultural center.
   The city's population is swelling past 3 million, making it the
nation's second-largest, and more than 70 languages are spoken.
   Bradley's name has been carefully linked to projects such as the
profitable 1984 Summer Olympics, the development of a skyscraper
skyline downtown, the revamping of Los Angeles International
Airport, where the international terminal bears his name, and the
construction of a multibillion-dollar rail-line transit system,
Metro Rail.
   His stewardship has been less linked in the public mind with
criminal infestation, illegal drug trafficking, street congestion,
overbuilding, pollution and a failing sewage system.
   In a recent Los Angeles Times poll, 65 percent surveyed said
their quality of life worsened during the Bradley years to the
point that half have recently considered moving.
   However, in another Times' poll, 78 percent of Hispanics, 70
percent of whites and 68 percent of blacks had a favorable
impression of the Democratic mayor.
   ``They (the public) are not holding him accountable for it. The
drugs and the gangs are causing it. But they don't think Tom
Bradley is causing it. He's a lucky politician,'' said Joe Cerrell,
a Los Angeles-based political consultant who has known Bradley
since he was a police lieutenant in the 1950s.
   Arnold Steinberg, a political pollster and consultant, said a
docile media and a perception that the city's problems are so huge
that they appear unsolvable add to Bradley's aura of immunity.
   The other mayoral hopefuls were socialist Joel Britton, an oil
refinery worker; singer-dancer Eileen Anderson; teachers Raul Reyes
and Maria Elizabeth Munoz; consultant Khushro Ghandhi; aerospace
worker Stewart Alexander; politician Leonard Earl Miropol and
political scientist Gary Passi.
   Other Los Angeles races included eight of the city council's 15
seats, city attorney, controller and school board members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
