<FIRST>r w PM-US-Pakistan     04-11 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Pakistan,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistani Leader to See Bush June 6-7</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan will
meet with President Bush during a two-day visit to Washington in
June, the White House said today.
   The official visit by the first woman leader of a Moslem country
will be June 6 and 7, said Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater. During
the trip she will be honored at a White House dinner.
   The president welcomes her trip as a chance to ``demonstrate our
support for the free elections which recently returned democratic
government to Pakistan,'' Fitzwater told reporters.
   ``The visit should offer an opportunity to further strengthen
the friendship and close cooperation between our two nations in the
wake of the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan and other important
developments in the region.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35, was elected Nov. 17 when her populist party
defeated the right wing in the country's first free election since
a coup ousted her father 11 years earlier.
   Her party also captured 92 seats in the 237-member assembly, by
far the most of any party.
   During the recent international fracas over Salman Rushdie's
book ``Satanic Verses,'' Ms. Bhutto was embroiled in the
controversy between Western nations and her country's neighbor
Iran, whose leaders called for the death of Rushdie because of the
book's alleged blasphemous passages.
   She declined to endorse the death threat but said Moslems should
have the right to protest against blasphemy.
