<HEAD>Police: Pager Undermines Drug Dealer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was arrested on drug charges got an
unwelcome phone call on his beeper at the police station, where
officers returned the call and found a prospective drug buyer on
the other end.
   Michael Williams, 26, told authorities he used the beeper in his
car-wash business and ``because I've got a lot of girlfriends and a
lot of friends.''
   Wayne County Circuit Judge Michael Talbot ruled Monday that
$4,297 found on Williams must be forfeited to police because it
came from a drug sale. Williams had said the money came from his
car-wash business.
   Authorities also found less than a gram of cocaine on Williams
when they arrested him Nov. 11, 1988. He faces a misdemeanor drug
trial in Dearborn Heights District Court.
   The person who called asking to buy drugs got suspicious and
hung up after officers tried to arrange a time and place for the
deal, said Sgt. Jim Schwall. The person's identity was never
discovered.
