<DOCNO> AP890411-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Warrior'sRing     04-11 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warrior's Ring,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ring Returned To WWII Flier's Family After 40 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRANDON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Marsman and Harold Christiansen live
half a world apart, but Christiansen has given the younger man a
link to the father he never knew, an aviator shot down over
Indonesia in World War II.
   Christiansen had carried a wedding band belonging to Robert
Marsman, an aviator in the Dutch Royal Navy, since the ring was
given to him by natives on an Indonesian island in 1945.
   ``I kept that ring all these years thinking that some day,
somewhere we would find Marsman's widow,'' Christiansen said in a
telephone interview from his home in New South Wales, Australia.
``All we had to go on was the name `Dorothy' that was on the inside
of the ring.''
   With the help of members of Marsman's old 18th Squadron and a
lot of luck, Christiansen finally made contact with the family in
Brandon in 1987. The retired major mailed the ring to the Marsman
family and later traveled to Mississippi to visit the flier's widow
and son.
   ``Completing this has been one of the highlights of my life,''
said Christiansen.
   ``There's no way to tell you what this has meant to me,''
Marsman said. ``I was two weeks old when his Mitchell bomber went
down and all I knew from childhood was that he was missing in
action and that's all my mother ever knew.''
   Christiansen said his unit was assigned to sweep through Kai
Island in search of lingering Japanese or Australian and Dutch
soldiers.
   ``I was given the ring by the head man of the island, who told
me about this flier whose body had washed up on the beach,''
Christiansen said.
   ``The head man asked that I find `Dorothy,' the name enscribed
on the ring,'' and told him that name tags showed the flier's name
was Robert Marsman, Christiansen said.
   At the end of the war, the Dutch government did not yet have
complete records and ``nobody I contacted seemed to know about
Dutchmen flying into those islands. It was not until three or four
years ago that I was able to get on the trail,'' Christiansen said.
   He spotted the name Robert Marsman in a book written by Gordon
Wallace and detailing the history of the 18th Squadron, and wrote
Wallace asking help.
   Wallace contacted Dutch officials who were able to search their
completed files and learned Dorothy's maiden name and that she
lived in Mississippi.
   The elder Marsman, whose parents were in the Dutch East Indies
and were captured by the Japanese, joined the Dutch Royal Navy and
was sent to Mississippi to learn to fly B-25.
   At Jackson, Robert Marsman and 16-year-old Dorothy Jean Usry of
Brandon met, fell in love and married.
   ``It is a good feeling to know that this is finally settled,''
said Dorothy Baker, who later remarried and lives in Jackson.
``Seeing that ring was a real surprise, a shock. All I ever knew
was the fact that his plane had exploded in mid-air over those
islands.''
   The family is trying to get Marsman's remains, buried in a war
cemetery in Indonesia, returned to Mississippi and buried in a
small cemetery for Dutch pilots who died in training.
   ``He wanted to be buried back here if anything happened to
him,'' said Mrs. Baker. ``And it would mean a lot for Larry.''
   However, efforts to secure help from the American and Dutch
governments to exhume the body haven't been successful so far.
   ``The United States trained him and he fought for freedom,''
Larry Marsman said. ``He wanted to be buried here because he felt
his family was here. I know this sounds silly, but I think that's
why this ring has worked its way back through all these years. He's
telling me to do something and I pray that I can.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
