<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSBrothers-Koop     04-11 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Brothers-Koop,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surgeon General Honors Hospitality To AIDS Brothers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop has
praised Sarasota for its support of a family driven from their
hometown in an adjacent county because three brothers were exposed
to the AIDS virus.
   Koop on Monday presented the city a certificate praising its
hospitality toward the Ray family, who settled here last year after
battling town officals over an order banning the sons' attendance
at public schools in Arcadia.
   Ricky, 12, Robert, 11, and Randy Ray, 9, are hemophiliacs who
doctors suspect became exposed to the virus that causes acquired
immune deficiency syndrome through contaminated blood products.
   The Ray boys, doctors say, show no symptoms of AIDS and pose no
threat to other children in a casual school environment.
   The boys and their parents, Louise and Clifford Ray, fled
Arcadia in 1987 when their home burned down, months after the
family won a federal court order returning their sons to school
despite protest of other parents.
   The preceding school year, school officials banned the three
youngsters from attending classes because they tested positive for
the AIDS virus. The family later received a $1.1 million settlement
from the school district.
   The family settled in Sarasota in September, and have attended
school since without incident.
   ``Sarasota has demonstrated that it's one of those good
communities that does react to families in need ... and comes to
their calling and provides opportunities for them,'' Koop told an
audience of about 400 people.
</TEXT>
