<FIRST>r a PM-AssaultWeapons     04-11 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Assault Weapons,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maryland Legislature Enacts Waiting Period For Assault Gun Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers have passed a requirement for a
seven-day waiting period and criminal background checks for buyers
of assault weapons.
   Gov. William Donald Schaefer is expected to sign the bill,
passed late Monday in the closing hours of the 1989 General
Assembly session.
   Under the measure, State Police would check the background of a
prospective gun buyer for evidence the individual was a drug
addict, alcoholic, convicted felon or was mentally deranged. An
individual with such a background can be denied a gun.
   Purchases of 24 semiautomatic handguns and rifles are affected.
   Earlier in the 90-day session, legislators considered banning
the sale of semiautomatics altogether.
   Last year, Maryland banned cheap handguns known as Saturday
Night Specials.
   Lawmakers have been continued pressure from the National Rifle
Association, which is worried the state is stepping on citizens'
rights to own guns.
   Lawmakers around the nation turned their attention to
semiautomatic weapons after a drifter opened fire on a Stockton,
Calif., schoolyard in January with an AK-47 rifle and killed five
children before committing suicide.
</TEXT>
