<FIRST>r a PM-ChildrenThreatened     04-11 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children Threatened,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Graffiti Threats Renew Fears At Rural School Complex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROOKLYN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anxious parents pulled 10 to 20 children
out of classes after a drawing of an assault rifle and the words
``You're Dead'' were found on a school that received telephone
death threats 10 days earlier.
   Police said the graffiti found Monday appeared to be the work of
juveniles and not of the anonymous woman who made the phone threats.
   But officials of this rural community's school system reinstated
tight security imposed after the first threats, including locked
doors and police escorts for morning and afternoon bus runs.
   The security was a drastic change at the Brooklyn School, which
had an open-door policy at its three buildings serving 850 pupils
in kindergarten through ninth grade.
   ``We have to face the fact it's probably not wise to have such
freedoms,'' said schools Superintendent Louise Berry. ``It's sad.
It's really an end of an era.''
   She said officials would also look into different types of
security, including intercoms at doorways.
   ``If your child forgot a book, it used to be you could walk
right in and hand it to him,'' said Mary Beth Leonard, who came to
pick up her 11-year-old son Monday.
   Nearly a third of all pupils were kept home April 3, but the
rate of absenteeism dropped to about 15 percent the following day
and returned to normal by the end of last week. The usual rate is 5
percent to 7 percent, Berry said.
</TEXT>
