<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast     04-11 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Asks Arabs to Withhold Judgment on Shamir Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States urged skeptical Arab
governments on Tuesday to withhold judgment on an Israeli proposal
for Palestinian elections until it is developed into a more formal
plan.
   ``This is a step-by-step process,'' State Department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler said. ``You have to crawl before you walk.''
   President Bush endorsed the proposal last week when Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir presented it to him at the White
House. Subsequently, the Palestine Liberation Organization and the
Arab League rejected it outright.
   The Bush administration declined to take that as a final answer.
   ``It is not unusual in a process for different parties to stake
out more extreme positions, especially at the beginning of the
process,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   The U.S. official said Shamir's proposal had ``potential'' and
``there are lots of questions to explore. We plan to do so in the
days and weeks ahead.''
   For instance, Ms. Tutwiler said Secretary of State James A.
Baker III would discuss the proposal with Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze during a visit to Moscow May 10-11.
   ``We are asking all those who are committed to peace to give us
a chance to explore and develop these ideas,'' the spokeswoman said.
   Shamir's proposal is to hold elections among the 1.4 million
Palestinian Arabs who live under Israeli control on the West Bank
and in Gaza. The leaders they chose would negotiate arrangements
for five years of local self-rule.
   Afterward, Israel, the Palestinians, Jordan and Egypt would
negotiate an overall settlement for the territories the Arabs lost
in the 1967 Six-Day War.
   Clovis Maksoud, the Arab League representative here, denounced
the Israeli proposal on Monday as a device ``to buy more time for
Israel and to diffuse the mounting pressure within the United
States and throughout the world as well to thwart the Palestinian
uprising.''
   Maksoud said Shamir sought to find through elections ``a
boneless or a toothless Palestinian negotiator who ratifies his
conquest.''
</TEXT>
