<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PaSong     04-11 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pa Song,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania House Votes To Be 49th State With Official Song</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pennsylvania House has voted to have
a state song, ``Pennsylvania,'' which would make the Keystone state
the 49th state to have an official tune. Only New Jersey would be
left songless.
   The House voted 135-59 for the measure Monday, sending it on to
the Senate.
   Efforts to put one special song on the books have for years been
tangled in politics as lawmakers pushed constituents' creations.
   State Government Chairman Frank Oliver said a special committee
of music educators and professionals chose ``Pennsylvania'' from
more than 200 selections. The process left no room for politics, he
said.
   The song features the chorus, ``Pennsylvania, Pennsylvania, may
your future be filled with honor everlasting as your history.''
   The two-verse ditty was written about 20 years ago by Eddie
Khoury and Ronnie Bonner. ``I feel great, I feel greatly honored.
What can I say?'' Khoury, a retired prison administrator, said in a
telephone interview.
   Under the legislation, Khoury and Bonner would still hold the
copyright to the song as its publishers. But the state ``can use
the song in any manner it sees fit,'' Khoury said.
   During debate, one lawmaker bellowed out a song he wrote about
three years ago lamenting Pennsylvania's song-less state.
   State Rep. James Gallen launched into the nameless song a
cappella to the cheers and applause of his fellow House members.
``Without a song, there's no way to celebrate,'' he sang in a
slightly off-key baritone.
   ``Without a song Pennsylvania is out of tune. Without a song,
we're the off-key stone state. We've got a state dog, flower and
fish and even a state bug.
   ``But what good is our bug, if we are unable in song it to
plug.''
   State Rep. Gerard Kosinski said he would oppose the bill for
``Pennsylvania.''
   ``In my mind, the only state song is the `Pennsylvania Polka,'
'' he said.
</TEXT>
