<FIRST>r a AM-Pignapping     04-11 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pignapping,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Hamstrung In Search For Missing Pig</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALUMET CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiffany Marie has been abducted, all
900 easy-going pounds of her, leaving her owners distraught and
police hamstrung.
   ``We want her back,'' owner Bob Urbanski said. ``We'll pay a
ransom. No questions asked.''
   He said Tuesday that the 2-year-old sow disappeared Sunday night
from the post where she was tied in an unfenced yard behind the
family-run pet store in this south Chicago suburb.
   Tiffany Marie is white with small brown spots. She's partial to
corn chips and strawberry whipped cream pie but will eat just about
anything except pickles and sour grapes.
   ``She's so gentle and just grunts at us when we're around,''
said Barbara Urbanski, who runs the pet shop with her husband and
children, Debbie and Bob. ``She's housebroken and part of the
family.''
   She's also part of the community. Tiffany Marie has become a
minor celebrity, featured in articles and seen on television while
she waded in her little pool or ducked the sun beneath her beach
umbrella in front of the store.
   Police were notified, but Chief Steven Rhoads said it will be
tough cracking the case. There was no ransom note but there have
been crank calls.
   The Urbanskis fear the crooks might try to sell the animal. Hog
prices Friday were listed at $37.50 per hundredweight. But Debbie
Urbanski noted that a diet of people food had spoiled the pig's
future as pork.
   ``She weighs 900 pounds, but that's probably all fat,'' she
said. ``Tiffany does not eat pig food. She eats what we do and
people come by and leave things for her to eat. Prime ribs,
doughnuts, cookies, White Castle hamburgers, anything.''
   The pig disappeared once before, wandering after her feed bucket
when a gust of wind carried it off. ``We found her half a block
away at a Dairy Queen, where people were feeding her ice cream,''
Urbanski said.
</TEXT>
