<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Refugees     04-11 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Refugees,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>150,000 Refugees from Beirut in South Lebanon ^With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The horror of the fighting in Beirut has
sent 150,000 city residents fleeing for shelter in war-ravaged
south Lebanon.
   Many moved in with relatives. But hundreds are living in the
wilderness, sleeping in their cars, in orange groves, or on the
rough concrete gravel in unfinished buildings.
   A nine-month-pregnant woman is staying with her three children
and 45 other refugees at one of the incomplete structures. They
sleep on the ground without mattresses or blankets.
   ``I need milk to feed my children, and to give to my baby who is
due any minute now,'' said Alliyeh Khodor, 24. She fled her house
in southern Beirut on March 14, a week after the latest round of
fighting erupted between Christian and allied Syrian and Druse
forces around the capital.
   Police say at least 180 have been killed and more than 600
injured the fighting.
   U.N. peacekeeping force in southern Lebanon and the
International Committee of the Red Cross are trying to ease
refugees' plight with food handouts and blankets.
   ``So far we have been able to provide wheat, sugar, canned food
and blankets,'' said a Red Cross spokesman who refused to be
identified by name. ``But our stocks are running thin.''
   The influx has boosted the population of south Lebanon by 30
percent, causing acute food and gas shortages, said a police
spokesman who by custom is not identified by name.
   Spokesmen for the U.N. force said at least 45,000 migrants are
staying in the U.N. area of operations. The rest of the refugees,
which they estimate at 150,000, have fled to areas near the
southern Lebanese port cities of Sidon and Tyre.
   Some are trying to get back to their original homes inside
Israel's self-designated ``security zone,'' along the
Israel-Lebanon border which they fled during Israel's 1982 invasion.
   But Israeli military authorities and the Israeli-backed South
Lebanon Army of right-wing Christian fighters that controls the
zone are refusing to allow Moslem returnees.
   Ghazi Fadlallah, a 45-year-old taxi driver, said he has been
prevented from returning to the house he left nearly nine years ago
in the town of Aynata inside the Israeli-run enclave.
   ``I have since changed nine houses because they were either
destroyed or burned to the ground during Lebanon's endless wars,''
Fadlallah said.
   His wife and eight children squeeze with 27 other relatives into
his brother-in-law's two-room house in Hosh village, two miles
south of Tyre.
   His eldest son, Mohammad, 15, said shrapnel almost killed him
two weeks ago when a bomb crashed near the south Beirut tailoring
shop where he worked.
   Most refugees are Shiite Moslems from south Lebanon who fled the
Israeli invasions of 1978 and 1982 and bloody clashes between
feuding Shiite militias.
   Lines of people wait outside the state's central telephone
station in Tyre to call relatives left behind in the capital. The
station has only two functioning lines.
   ``Now it's Beirut. The hell there is unbearable. So I've come
back here,'' said Kamleh Sabbagh, 42. ``But my heart is still
there.''
   Malak Kabbani, 45, a Sunni Moslem waiting her turn, said she
left her house in west Beirut's Mosseitbeh district mainly because
water and power were cut off.
   ``We are used to the shelling, it does not scare us anymore.
It's much more difficult without electricity and water,'' she said.
   Yohanna Haddad, the Roman Catholic bishop of Tyre, said only
1,500 Christians are among refugees in Tyre.
   But police say tens of thousands of other Christians have fled
the Christian-held regions north and northeast of Beirut.
   Police say most managed to leave by small boats to open waters,
where a ship took them to the southernmost border town of Naqoura.
From there they crossed on foot to the ``security zone.''
</TEXT>
