<TEXT>
   Johns Hopkins University trustees have honored
an arms reduction negotiator by renaming the international studies
school The Paul H. Nitze School of Advanced International Studies.
   Dean George R. Packard said the vote Monday was not sought by
Nitze, a co-founder of the school in 1943. The school, located in
Washington, is a graduate school of international affairs
affiliated with the Johns Hopkins Foreign Policy Institute,
conceived in 1957 by Nitze.
   ``It is our way of expressing our thanks and respect to a man
who has made so much of the history which our students are
currently studying and who is always available to our faculty and
students for dialogue and consultation,'' Packard said.
   Nitze, 81, headed arms negotiating teams from 1981 to 1984 and
for the past five years was an arms negotiations adviser to
Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
