<FIRST>r i AM-OldCity     04-11 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Old City,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jerusalem's Old City: Fault Line of Arab-Israeli Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The walled Old City, dotted with shrines sacred
to Moslems, Jews and Christians, is the major fault line of the
Arab-Israeli conflict where tensions frequently burst to the
surface.
   On Tuesday, Palestinians buried an Arab resident of the Old
City's Moslem quarter who was shot by an Israeli dressed in army
fatigues. The angry Palestinians shouted: ``Teach the Jews a
lesson! Everything Jewish in this town should be burned!''
   ``We are living inside a powder keg,'' said Mohammed Sublaban,
40, the owner of a souvenir shop in the city's Moslem quarter.
``The slightest provocation can make all the resentments erupt to
the surface.''
   Responsibility for the submachine gun attack Monday was claimed
by a Jewish extremist group known as the Sicarites. The group,
which takes its name from ancient Jewish assassins of biblical
times, said it was avenging Palestinian stoning attacks on Jews.
   Tension in the Old City rose Friday when rocks hurled by
Palestinian rioters during a clash in the Al Aqsa mosque compound
fell on Jews worshipping at the adjacent Wailing Wall, the holiest
site in Judaism.
   ``Radicalism on both the Arab and Jewish sides have sharpened
the situation,'' Police Minister Chaim Bar Lev said on Israel
radio. ``Arabs throw rocks at the Temple Mount and a Jew kills
Arabs. There is no solution, it only heats up the conflict.''
   About 17,000 Moslems and 2,000 Jews live in separate enclaves
inside ancient Jerusalem's crowded square mile of narrow
cobblestone alleyways, houses and shops. Enemies yet neighbors,
they carry separate passports and rarely interact.
   ``These people will never integrate, it is not their purpose,''
Mayor Teddy Kollek said recently to explain the historic divisions.
``The most we can do is try to avoid clashes of interests.''
   Clashes have, however, been a hallmark of Jerusalem's history.
   The city has been conquered about 20 times from 587 B.C., when
the Babylonians exiled the Jews, to 1967 when Israel captured Arab
east Jerusalem and the walled Old City from Jordan and annexed it.
   In addition to the Jewish shrines, Moslems also have sacred
places in the Holy City, including Al Aqsa Mosque. The mosque is in
the Haram al Sharif, or Noble Enclossure, an area is called Temple
Mount by the Jews.
   Jerusalem is the capital of Israel and the Palestinians also
claim Jerusalem as the capital of a Palestinian state.
   For Christians, the Old City is a goal of pilgrims as the scene
of Christ's crucifixion and burial.
   Friday's riot at the Al Aqsa mosque compound prompted Bar Lev to
ban some Palestinians from the occupied territories from worshiping
there.
   The move elicited angry reactions from the Waqf, the Islamic
administrators of the Haram al Sharif, or Noble Sancutary in
Arabic. It is the third holiest site in Islam after Mecca and
Medina in Saudi Arabia.
   ``This is categorically unacceptable. It is an attack against
freedom of religion,'' said Sheik Mohammed Jamal. ``Bar Lev is
pouring oil on the fire. The result will only be more and more
fire.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
