<FIRST>r w AM-Crops-Weather     04-11 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crops-Weather,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Calls Winter Wheat's Condition ``Mostly Fair''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winter wheat across the nation is in ``mostly
fair'' condition, although the crop has declined in the central
Great Plains and the Pacific Northwest, a government report said
Tuesday.
   ``In Kansas, winter wheat condition deteriorated and was mostly
very poor to poor,'' the Joint Agricultural Weather Facility said.
``As fields broke dormancy, winterkill continued to become more
evident. Insect and disease problems, however, were below normal.''
   The facility, operated by the Agriculture and Commerce
departments, said the Oklahoma crop was mostly good to fair, and in
Texas winter wheat was reported in mostly fair to poor condition.
   Conditions were reported as of the week of April 3-9. Dry soils
since winter wheat was planted last fall have stunted development
severely in many areas.
   Elsewhere in the plains region, winter wheat in Nebraska was
said to be in mostly fair condition, although winterkill became
evident as the dormant crop began to green up this spring.
   The crop was reported mostly good to fair in Idaho and South
Dakota, and mostly fair to good in Colorado, Montana and Wyoming.
   In Oregon, winter wheat was mostly fair to good, with some
replanting in the Columbia Basin. The Washington crop was mostly
poor, with winterkill becoming more widespread in several counties.
   Winter wheat was said to be in mostly good to excellent
condition in California, and mostly good in the Corn Belt. In the
Delta and Southeast, the crop was reported in mostly good to fair
condition.
</TEXT>
