<FIRST>u a PM-NuclearBarge 1stLd-Writethru a0506 04-11 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Barge, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0506,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Briefly Halts Trip of Decommissioned Nuclear Reactor</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with fire aboard tugboat delaying
trip of barge for 7 hours, other details. Picks up in 4th graf, `The barge
...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire aboard a tugboat early today
briefly halted the Columbia River barge trip of a mammoth
decommissioned nuclear reactor bound for its burial site, the U.S.
Coast Guard said.
   The fire broke out in the tug's engine room about 3:30 a.m.,
when the barge carrying the reactor was just above Bonneville Dam,
and delayed the trip for about seven hours.
   There were no injuries and ``at no time was there any danger of
the reactor vessel going aground,'' said Wenday Anderson of the
Knapptown Corp. in Portland, which owns the tug.
   Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Guy Nolan said a backup tug was hooked up
to the barge carrying the reactor while a third tug was dispatched
from Portland.
   Nolan said he was unsure what caused the fire aboard the
Clarkston.
   Coast Guard vessels escorted the barge as it made its way
upriver toward a dump at the government's Hanford nuclear
reservation in Washington.
   About 50 demonstrators watched from the Interstate Bridge at the
edge of Portland as the barge passed by without incident just after
midnight, said Petty Officer David Clarke.
   The barge headed to the Hood River for the final leg of an
8,000-mile trip from Shippingport, Pa., through the Panama Canal
and up the Pacific coast.
   The Shippingport nuclear plant was shut down in 1982 and
dismantled. The barge carried its 1,000-ton reactor pressure vessel.
   The vessel, 45 feet high and 18 feet across, was emptied of its
uranium fuel and filled with concrete to keep residual
radioactivity from escaping.
   ``People are just concerned,'' Carolyn Dunn said at an earlier
demonstration by about 20 people at an Astoria pier. ``We just wish
it weren't happening.''
   The main fear is that radioactivity from the vessel will seep
into the Columbia from the dump site, she said.
   ``It's not what goes up the river that we worry about at this
point so much as what's going to come down the river in leakage
later,'' said Dunn.
   The U.S. Department of Energy has said the barge's cargo is no
threat to the public.
</TEXT>
