<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1454EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Scandal     04-11 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita in Reversal Says He Accepted Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita reversed himself
before Parliament on Tuesday, acknowledging he accepted $1 million
from a company at the hub of a political scandal that has prompted
calls for his resignation.
   Though Takeshita went before lawmakers seeking to clear his name
in the nationally televised session, opposition leaders and some
conservative analysts said he only raised more doubts.
   ``I'm not sure why Takeshita agreed to speak today,'' said
Keiichiro Nakamura, who served an an aide to former Prime Minister
Takeo Miki. ``But if it was to increase the people's trust in the
Liberal Democratic Party, he probably did more harm than good.''
   Takeshita and his party have been battered by disclosures the
Recruit Co., a huge publishing conglomerate, sold bargain-priced
stock to prominent bureaucrats and businessmen. In all, 14 people
have been arrested and three Cabinet ministers have resigned in
connection with the scandal.
   The government's embarrassment heightened last week with several
news reports that turned national attention to Recruit political
donations to Takeshita before he became prime minister .
   On Tuesday, Takeshita told a special session of the lower house
budget committee that between 1985 and 1987, he had received $1
million from Recruit and its subsidiaries.
   He said they gave the money to his political support groups in
the form of donations and purchases of fund-raising party tickets.
   Takeshita was finance minister and secretary-general of the
governing Liberal Democratic Party at the time.
   He earlier acknowledged that a former aide and a relative bought
12,000 Recruit subsidiary shares for a profit of about $190,000.
But he denied any personal involvement.
   On Tuesday, he stressed the legality of the Recruit donations,
which he called ``indispensible elements for vital political
activities.''
   Takeshita went on to reject opposition party assertions his
administration no longer has the credibility to lead the nation.
   Vowing to stay in office, Takeshita said, ``At a time when
distrust of politics is growing among the people, it is my
responsibility to see that reform is carried out.''
   Leaders of the governing party said his appearance would help
put the Recruit affair into perspective and allow the government to
move on to other business.
   ``I think (Takeshita's explanations) should serve to distinguish
(that the donations were legal) and should put a period on the
criticism,'' said Chief Cabinet Secretary Keizo Obuchi.
   But Nakamura said not all members of the governing conservative
party were persuaded.
   ``Opinion within the ruling party is split, but more and more
people are realizing that the party just can't win elections with
Takeshita as its leader,'' he said.
   Elections for half of the seats in the upper house of Parliament
will be held this summer.
   Political analysts say no clear successor is ready to take over
Takeshita's job, and the opposition acknowledges it does not
control the votes needed to oust him.
   By acknowledging the donations, Takeshita reversed a statement
he made before lawmakers last October, when he denied receiving any
Recruit funds ``whatsoever.''
   ``Takeshita attempted to clear his name,'' Kanji Kawasaki, a
Socialist legislator who questioned Takeshita, said. ``But by
admitting to the flow of such large amounts of money, he has only
deepened the suspicions which surround him.''
   ``Takeshita simply lied until the truth was uncovered .... The
people of Japan will not be satisfied,'' said Kawasaki.
   Recruit sold unlisted shares in a real-estate subsidiary to
about 160 political, business and government officials at low
prices in 1986. Buyers of the shares received handsome profits when
the shares soared in value shortly after they were listed on the
market.
   Prosecutors say Recruit was trying to influence policies of the
labor and education ministries regarding the company's major
activity, publishing job placement magazines.
   No politicians have been arrested in the scandal, but
prosecutors have been reported to question several of them.
</TEXT>
