<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     04-11 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Militants Reject Cease-Fire Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest Tamil militant group
Tuesday rejected a one-week cease-fire offered by President
Ranasinghe Premadasa, who sought to end six years of ethnic
violence that has claimed 12,500 lives.
   ``The government is only interested in getting our weapons and
has not put forward anything worthwhile,'' said a leader of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne told reporters Monday that
while troops operations were suspended, the militants should give
themselves up at 228 centers across the country. He said 104
militants, all Sinhalese, had surrendered before the centers were
set up.
   Premadasa offered the one-week truce beginning Wednesday to both
ethnic Tamil and majority Sinhalese militants. He said the military
would suspend offensives against the Tamil rebels during that time.
   The offer was part of a peace package that included general
amnesty, seats in Parliament and jobs for the militants on this
island off the southern coast of India.
   ``We will not agree to any cease-fire so long as the Indian arms
remain in Sri Lanka,'' the rebel leader told The Associated Press.
   In New Delhi, India, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said India had
decided to withdraw some of its peacekeeping troops from Sri Lanka.
Spokesman Aftab Seth did not give details, saying only that a
``significant'' number would be pulled out.
   India moved in 50,000 troops to disarm the Tamil militants under
a July 1987 accord that aimed to end a Tamil insurgency in the
northern and northeastern provinces. The Liberation Tigers group
refused to accept the accord because it said the pact did not meet
enough of its demands for self-rule.
   In January, India withdrew an estimated 3,000 soldiers, saying
it did so out of respect for public wishes in Sri Lanka. Opponents
of the 1987 accord had feared Indian troops might remain on the
island indefinitely.
   Tamil militants in Sri Lanka launched a campaign in 1983 for an
independent homeland, citing discrimination by the Sinhalese in
employment and education.
   In a backlash, Sinhalese extremists of the Marxist People's
Liberation Front have killed more than 2,500 people since January.
They oppose the government's plan to grant Tamils limited autonomy.
   They have not reacted to the truce offer. In addition, the
government had no immediate reaction to the rebels' rejection.
   Also Tuesday, two gunmen from Sinhalese group broke into a house
outside Colombo and killed Sarat Algama, the twin brother of senior
military officer Brig. Lakshman Algama, officials said.
   Tamils, mostly Hindus, comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people. Sinhalese, who are mainly Buddhists, make up 75
percent of the population and control the government and military.
</TEXT>
