<FIRST>r a AM-ChevronFire     04-11 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chevron Fire,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Controlled At Huge Plant; Last Flames Expected Out Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fire at in Chevron's huge
east San Francisco Bay refinery cut the plant's gasoline and jet
fuel production cut by 25 percent, the company said.
   Monday's blast sent towering clouds of sooty smoke boiling into
the sky from the 4{-square-mile Richmond plant and injured eight
workers and firefighters with burns, smoke inhalation and shock.
   Firefighters decided to allow the blaze to burn itself out and
residual pockets of fuel continued burning Tuesday.
   The burned unit, a cracking column which separates crude oil
into its various components from light fuels to heavy lubricants,
produced about 10 percent of the West Coast's oil requirements, the
company said.
   Chevron spokesman Glenn Weaver could not say if the production
shortfall would cause any retail increase at the pumps in the
western states, but that Chevron planned to compensate by dipping
into inventories and increasing production at other refineries.
   ``It's hard to isolate what the movement in prices ... might be;
one thing we know is our costs will go up,'' he said.
   The company said the stricken unit could be out of commission
for at least two months, but management would not speculate on
repair and replacement costs.
   The 87-year-old plant handles 270,000 barrels of oil a day.
   Weaver said company investigators were still trying to determine
the cause of the lunch-hour eruption. The plant employs about 1,800
people.
   The Bay Area Air Quality Management District reported that
although the smoke did not register on monitoring stations near the
plant Chevron might be liable for a $1,000 fine ``for creating a
public nuisance.''
   The smoke was not toxic, said Contra Costa County Health
Director Mark Finucane, rating the smoke about as dangerous as that
produced in a fireplace.
</TEXT>
