<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     04-11 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Shell Christian Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners shelled Christian areas
Tuesday in spite of a 6-day-old truce called by the Arab League,
and Paris sent an envoy to work out a distribution plan for two
shiploads of French humanitarian aid.
   Police said the howitzer shells landed in a scattered pattern in
Christian territory and no casualties were reported. They said the
Christians held their fire.
   Moslem-Christian artillery duels began five weeks ago and
developed into the worst sectarian fighting since 1985 in Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war. Police give the casualties, nearly all
civilians, as 180 killed and 619 wounded.
   Gen. Michel Aoun, who commands the 20,000 Christians of
Lebanon's army, imposed a blockade March 6 on illegal militia-run
ports that deprive the government of an estimated $100 million a
year in revenue.
   Walid Jumblatt's Druse militia started shooting two days later
and Syrian gunners soon joined them. Syria has 40,000 soldiers in
Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   Bernard Kouchner, French minister for humanitarian assistance,
arrived ahead of the two ships carrying food, fuel and medical
supplies, which have caused an argument between Moslems and
Christians.
   Moslems claim France, from which Lebanon became independent in
1943, favors the Christians. The French government has expressed
concern over the fate of Lebanon's Christians.
   Kouchner spent 45 minutes with acting Premier Salim Hoss, who
heads a Moslem cabinet that has competed with a Christian
government led by Aoun since a political crisis began in September.
   Hoss convened his cabinet afterward, then issued a statement
saying the Moslem government rejected ``the French donation until
the French stand toward the Lebanese crisis is clarified.''
   Kouchner told reporters France was determined to deliver the aid
to ``all the Lebanese'' and would meet with several leaders to plan
the distribution.
   He said French policy ``supports a political settlement in
Lebanon.''
   Jumblatt has warned the French not to bring the ships into a
Christian port.
   Before meeting in west Beirut with Hoss, a Sunni Moslem,
Kouchner conferred with Aoun in Baabda, the Christian suburb where
the presidential palace is located. By unwritten agreement since
1943, Lebanon's president is a Christian, the premier a Sunni and
the parliament speaker a Shiite Moslem.
   The relief ships left for Lebanon last week. France has not said
when they will arrive, but they are expected Wednesday.
   One carries food and fuel. The other is a hospital ship with
beds, surgical facilities and medical supplies.
   Fear has been expressed that more fighting will accompany the
ships' arrival. A French envoy who was in Lebanon last week _
Jean-Francois Deniau of the National Assembly's foreign affairs
committee _ was quoted Tuesday as saying it ``would be an act of
war against France'' to fire on the ships.
   ``If they fire, it is clear that they want to destroy Lebanon,''
he was quoted as saying in the Tours, France daily La Nouvelle
Republique du Centre-Ouest.
   Youssef Aridi, a grocer in Moslem west Beirut, said: ``I think
Wednesday will be a bad day. I won't leave home. If they shell the
French, God knows what will happen.''
   Lebanon's latest government crisis began when President Amin
Gemayel's six-year term ended in September and Parliament could not
agree on a successor. Gemayel chose Aoun, the army comnmander, to
lead an interim administration and Moslems swore allegiance to
Hoss, the incumbent premier.
   The army also split on sectarian lines, with Aoun commanding the
Christians and Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib taking charge of the 22,000
Moslems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
