<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Iraq     04-11 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomats Say Iran-Iraq Peace Talks Resuming April 20 In Geneva</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers from Iran and Iraq will
try to break a deadlock in peace negotiations in a new round of
talks beginning April 20 in Geneva, diplomats said Tuesday.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar will mediate the
talks between Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati and his
Iraqi counterpart, Tariq Aziz, the diplomats said.
   The U.N. chief is expected to publicly announce the date for
resumption of talks Wednesday, said the diplomats, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Velayati and Aziz had previously agreed to hold a new round of
direct talks in the near future at an undisclosed site near U.N.
headquarters.
   No explanation was given for switching the site to Geneva, but
the change may have been made because Perez de Cuellar will be
touring Europe in late April. His itinerary has not yet been
announced.
   The peace talks ran into a stalemate in August after Iraq
demanded that Iran agree to a U.N. plan to clear war debris from
the Shatt-al-Arab waterway forming their southern border. The
waterway is Iraq's only outlet to the Persian Gulf.
   Iran refused. It says Iraq must withdraw from Iranian territory
it still holds before other issues can be addressed.
   The Persian Gulf War broke out in September 1980. At least 1
million people were been killed or wounded.
   The two sides signed a U.N.-mediated cease-fire in August,
beginning the talks aimed at a permanent settlement five days later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
