<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--ForestVolunteers     04-11 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Forest Volunteers,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Volunteers Help National Forests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last year more than 65,000 volunteers donated
time and muscle to help run the national forests, the Agriculture
Department said Tuesday.
   F. Dale Robertson, chief of the Forest Service, said the
volunteers contributed more than 1,900 person-years worth of work
valued at $25.5 million. Since the annual volunteer program began,
he said, more than 440,000 have participated, performing an
estimated $185 million worth of work.
   The volunteers serve as campground hosts, plant trees, maintain
trails, improve fish and wildlife habitat, patrol wildernesses,
assist scientists, write publications and help keep office records.
   Robertson said the program is open to groups and organizations
as well as individuals on a full-time, part-time or one-time basis
at most Forest Service locations.
   Further information can be obtained by writing: Volunteers in
the National Forests, Forest Service-USDA, Post Office Box 96090,
Washington, D.C. 20090-6090.
</TEXT>
