<FIRST>u i AM-Turkey-US     04-11 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-US,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkish Prosecutor Frees U.S. Citizens Accused of Proselytizing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public prosecutor freed Tuesday four
U.S. citizens detained a week ago on charges of violating laws that
prohibit proselytizing, the Anatolia news agency said.
   The four were freed following questioning by the prosecutor, the
agency said without further explanation.
   An Istanbul police chief, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said authorities are trying to find a way to deport the four, who
reportedly belong to an unidentified Christian fundamentalist group.
   Anatolia quoted officials of the prosecutor's office as saying
the investigation into the case is continuing to determine whether
the four should face trial.
   The four were detained April 4 as they distributed pamphlets
protesting the portrayal of Jesus in the film ``The Last Temptation
of Christ,'' outside a theater at the Istanbul Cinema Festival.
   Turkish law bans proselytizing and a conviction carries a
maximum 10-year jail sentence.
   Police identified the four as David Kim Wilson, 35, of Chicago,
and his wife Pamela Lynn, 32, of Des Moines, Iowa; Norma Cox, 45,
of Chicago; and Brian Scott Thorsvik, listed only as being from
Washington state.
   A police spokesman said the Wilsons were traveling as tourists
in Turkey, Cox was teaching English and Thorsvik was a university
student.
   Christians in Western countries demonstrated when Martin
Scorsese's ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' was released last
year, charging it is blasphemous because it depicts Jesus
hallucinating about marrying Mary Magdalene and having sex.
   A group of Moslem fundamentalists also protested in front of the
Turkish film festival April 4, calling the movie offensive to
Moslems.
   Iran has criticised Turkey for including the film and withdrew
its own entry from the festival program, Turkish newspapers
reported.
   Religious issues have strained relations between the two
nations, and both countries recalled their ambassadors for
consultations last week.
</TEXT>
