<FIRST>u w AM-NursingHomes-Lawsuit 1stLd-Writethru a0588 04-11 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Homes-Lawsuit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0588,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Groups Seek to Block Law's Provisions on Mentally Ill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 15, ``Earlier this,'' to CORRECT Coleman's title to
then-deputy director</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major nursing-home groups filed suit
against the government Tuesday to block provisions of a law
requiring nursing homes to turn away the mentally ill and mentally
retarded.
   The American Health Car Association and the American Association
of Homes for the Aging said the federal government is requiring
states to implement the law, which took effect Jan. 1, even though
the Department of Health and Human Services has issued no
regulations to guide them.
   They said the result is that the law will hurt the people it was
intended to help by denying them admission to nursing homes even
when no alternate care facilities are available.
   Nursing home applicants and patients who are mentally retarded
or mentally ill ``are being held hostage by this legislation and
its misguided implementation,'' said Sheldon Goldberg, president of
the American Association of Homes for the Aging, which represents
about 2,500 nursing homes.
   Though he did not cite specific instances in which mentally ill
or mentally retarded patients have been discharged from nursing
homes, he said his concern was ``that could happen in the future.''
   The suit was filed in U.S. District Court for the District of
Columbia, naming HHS Secretary Louis Sullivan. Department officials
had no immediate comment on the lawsuit.
   Under the law, nursing homes will lose federal Medicaid funds if
they accept patients who suffer from mental illness or mental
retardation unless they also need nursing home care. Nursing homes
get about 44 percent of their revenues from the federal-state
Medicaid program. Patients who have lived in a nursing home for
fewer than 30 months also must be screened for mental illness and
mental retardtion, under the law.
   Paul Willging, executive vice president of the American Health
Care Association, which represents about 9,000 nursing homes, said
that without regulations from the HHS, nursing homes don't know how
to define mental illness. The law exempts Alzheimer's disease, but
diagnosis of the condition is difficult and its victims are often
classified as mentally ill, he noted.
   Depending on how mental illness is defined, an estimated 26,000
to 208,000 current residents of the 1.5 million Americans in
nursing homes might have to be involuntarily discharged under the
law, he said.
   With few alternate care facilities available in most areas, he
said, many of these patients may be left homeless, without even
basic levels of care.
   Willging and Goldberg said the law is well-intentioned in that
it seeks to ensure that the mentally ill and mentally retarded get
the specialized treatment they need for their conditions.
   ``But it is equally important to provide some elementary
protections,'' Willging said. ``We demand the horse be put before
the cart.''
   The suit asks the court to put the screening requirements of the
law on hold until HHS issues implementing regulations. It also asks
the court to prohibit application of the rules to private-pay
patients.
   Restraining orders have been issued by courts in Idaho, Arkansas
and Texas in response to suits filed by nursing-home groups,
Willging said. A suit also has been filed in Louisiana, he said.
   Earlier this year, Terry Coleman, then-deputy director of HHS's
Health Care Financing Administration, said the law was an effort to
get states to develop group-home and community-based services for
the mentally ill and mentally retarded.
   Historically, it has been the states' responsibility to fund
services and facilities for the mentally ill, he said. To avoid
this cost, however, some states have sent these patients to nursing
homes, where Medicaid picks up the tab for those who cannot pay.
   More states have special facilities for the mentally retarded
because Medicaid helps pay for them, but nursing home care for
these patients is often cheaper, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
