<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1740EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Draft     04-11 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Draft,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Cut Length of Military Service for Graduates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Defense Ministry will cut the length of
military service required for students who have completed higher
education courses, the official Tass news agency said Tuesday.
   Under new regulations for conscription, students who graduate
this spring will be required to serve only one year in the military
instead of 18 months in the army and air force or two years in the
navy, the news agency said.
   The new regulations were expected to begin with the spring
intake of conscripts, Tass said.
   The Defense Ministry announced in March that students could
defer military service until after graduation, but it did not
specify the length of service that would be required.
   Previously, all Soviet men between the ages of 18 and 25 were
liable for the draft, and there were no exemptions for students.
   Changes in the conscription system have been under discussion
for the past five years, and the program of officer training is
also under review, according to the Communist youth newspaper
Komsomolskaya Pravda.
   The new rules apply only to conscripts and not officers or
officer candidates, Tass said. About 75 percent of Soviet military
personnel are conscripts.
   Changes in the draft law follow the announcement Dec. 7 by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev at the United Nations that Soviet
troop strength would be cut by 500,000 and military spending would
be reduced by 14 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
