<FIRST>r a AM-Cuba-TV     04-11 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-TV,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba Programming Interrupts S. Fla. Prime Time; TV Marti Retaliation?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viewers watching WCIX-TV were surprised when Cuban
television cut in briefly with a preview of ``Endless Love''
starring Brooke Shields and a shot of Giron, the site of the Bay of
Pigs invasion.
   And viewers switching past channel 3, a blank, unused channel in
Miami, also got a taste of Cuban government programming.
   Some think the interference Saturday and Monday was intentional,
a warning against the United States proceeding with plans for TV
Marti, an alternative to Cuba's state-controlled media and the next
step after the success of Radio Marti.
   ``The reason (Fidel) Castro may be doing this now is that the
legislation to authorize TV Marti is going to be debated on the
floor of the House this week,'' said Barbara Burris, an aide to
Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., chairman of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee and a key backer of Radio and TV Marti.
   ``Rep. Fascell anticipated this and has already cautioned the
administration that they'd better be prepared for this type of
action.''
   But it may instead have just been a rare combination of
technical difficulties and inopportune weather conditions, said Jay
Newman, vice president and manager at CBS-owned WCIX.
   His station experienced a power outage and briefly was off the
air Monday night when the Cuban signal appeared.
   ``We believe it was a unique combination of circumstance, us
going off the air, and of the wether being such that the signal
from Cuba was able to bounce full-strength onto our frequency,''
Newman said.
   Channel 3 carried a variety show and the Cuban government's
national news program Saturday.
   Angel Pino, a spokesman for the Cuban Interests Section in
Washington, would not confirm or deny the jamming was a warning
from Cuba.
   Cuban Foreign Ministry officials have suggested that if TV Marti
goes into operation, their government might retaliate by beaming TV
programs to the United States, even if the signal interfered with
American stations.
   The Reagan administration began considering TV Marti after
seeing the success of Radio Marti, which broadcasts news,
editorials and entertainment to Cuba under the auspices of the
Voice of America. Both are named after Cuban independence hero Jose
Marti.
   The TV Marti section of the annual House authorization bill is
based on a Senate version passed last year that provided $7.5
million for starting costs and a study to determine whether TV
Marti is viable.
   The study, released in January, endorsed TV Marti but cautioned
that Castro's ability to retaliate be weighed closely before
proceeding.
</TEXT>
