<FIRST>r a AM-NuclearBarge     04-11 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Barge,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tug Fire Causes Seven-Hour Delay in Barge's Journey</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA7</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOOD RIVER, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barge carrying a nuclear reactor
vessel resumed its trip up the Columbia River on Tuesday after a
fire aborad the tugboat pulling it caused a seven-hour delay.
   The fire broke out in the engine room about 3:30 a.m., when the
tug and the barge were just above Bonneville Dam, east of Portland.
The reactor vessel from Shippingport, Pa., is on the last leg of an
8,000-mile voyage to burial at the Hanford, Wash., nuclear
reservation.
   There were no injuries and ``at no time was there any danger of
the reactor vessel going aground,'' said Wendy Anderson of the
Knappton Corp. in Portland, which owns the tug.
   Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Guy Nolan said another tug was sent from
Portland and the barge Paul Bunyan got under way again about 10:45
a.m.
   It was not clear what caused the fire aboard the tug Clarkston,
Nolan said. ``We had a report that there were a few burned wires or
something,'' he said.
   The barge passed Portland's north edge Tuesday just after
midnight, as about 100 anti-nuclear activists protested on the
Interstate Bridge over the river.
   Coast Guard vessels have escorted the barge since it entered the
Columbia at Astoria Monday morning.
   The 1,000-ton reactor pressure vessel is expected to arrive
Wednesday at the Hanford nuclear reservation.
   The vessel, which is 45 feet high and 18 feet across, traveled
through the Panama Canal en route from Shippingport, Pa., where the
nuclear plant was shut down in 1982.
   Built of 6-inch-thick stainless steel, the vessel was emptied of
its uranium fuel and the U.S. Department of Energy said it is no
threat to public health.
</TEXT>
