<DOCNO> AP890411-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1916EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     04-11 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Provides Guarantees for Journalists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military, criticized for
killing two reporters last month, said Tuesday it will not fire on
journalists' vehicles even if they ignore or inadvertently run a
roadblock.
   Two reporters were killed and another seriously wounded in March
by soldiers manning roadblocks. The incidents are being
investigated, but the armed forces have acknowledged that in at
least one of the cases the soldier fired without provocation.
   In another development, President Jose Napoleon Duarte returned
to his duties at the Presidential Palace after five days of
convalescence from side effects of cancer treatment.
   A document containing instructions on military relations with
the press was signed Tuesday by Defense Minister Gen. Carlos Vides
Casanova. It says that if a news vehicle passes through a
roadblock, soldiers manning the position ``will limit themselves to
taking down the license plate number, to be reported to the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, which will take appropriate action. Under no
circumstances will the vehicles or their occupants be fired upon.''
   Security force roadblocks are common in zones where fighting is
heaviest in this Central American country, ravaged by nine years of
civil war between leftist guerrillas and the U.S.-backed government.
   News vehicles are identified by the local convention of
affixing, with tape, the large letters ``TV'' on the windshield,
sides, roof and back. They also fly small white flags out windows
or from antennae.
   The document, to be distributed in the form of an order to
military units nationwide, also prohibits the arrest of accredited
journalists discovered in battle zones without a safe-conduct
document from the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   Such passes are required for access to regions of frequent
fighting. Journalists who have entered such areas without the pass
have been arrested. The new regulation authorizes local commanders
only to take down the violator's name and affiliation, for relay to
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, which would administer any sanction.
   The new document also prohibits confiscation of equipment, film
or written material under any circumstances. Military authorities
in the past have temporarily impounded or confiscated such
material, prompting protests from the local correspondents'
association.
   ``We feel it is our obligation to establish regulations that, in
addition to improving our relationship with the media, allow both
of us to carry out our missions in the best possible manner,'' said
the document.
   Duarte's secretary Carmen Vallejos said the president met with
several ministers and other officials when he resumed his duties.
In a telephone interview, she described his mood as ``animated.''
   Duate, a 63-year-old Christian Democrat, is dying of liver
cancer. Chemotherapy intended to slow the advance of the disease
provoked severe nausea and vomiting last week. Duarte became
dehydrated and was confined to bed for intravenous feeding. He
temporarily delegated the presidency to Vice President Rodolfo
Castillo Claramount.
   Duarte's five-year term ends June 1, when he is to hand power
over to President-elect Alfredo Cristiani of the rightist
Republican Nationalist Alliance. Cristiani was elected March 19.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
