<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     04-11 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Soldiers Returning to Duty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Soldiers whose revolt was crushed
by loyal troops over the weekend have begun returning to duty after
Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril's military government promised not to punish
them.
   Radio Soleil, the Roman Catholic church radio station, said more
than 230 of the Dessalines Barracks' 750 soldiers had reported to
army headquarters by Tuesday morning.
   Foreign Minister Serge Elie Charles said Monday no rebels were
being held prisoner. The government has said they will be treated
``with dignity'' and no reprisals will be taken.
   Two gunmen identified as Dessalines deserters hijacked a
twin-engine airplane Monday that was carrying missionaries based in
Redlands, Calif., from Haiti to Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   The hijackers diverted the plane to Miami and surrendered. The
seven other passsengers and the pilot were not harmed.
   Avril's 1,100-man Presidential Guard based at the National
Palace stormed the adjoining Dessalines barracks Saturday to put
down a rebellion among soldiers demanding that the general give up
the presidency.
   Fighting began Friday night and lasted 20 hours. Avril told
reporters Monday most of the cartridges used initially were blanks,
in order to reduce casualties.
   He said the Saturday assault with live ammunition occurred after
mortar shells from the Dessalines Barracks landed near the palace,
killing three soldiers.
   Five soldiers were killed in the two days of fighting, and a
sixth died Sunday while trying to recover an unexploded grenade,
Avril said. He also reported one civilian killed and 43 soldiers
and 32 civilians wounded.
   It remained unclear whether Avril would disband the Dessalines,
widely regarded as the most repressive unit in Haiti's 7,000-man
army.
   Col. Guy Francois, its former commander, was said to have been
given temporary asylum in the Vatica Embassy. The government has
identified Francois as one of four leaders of a coup attempt April
2.
   Negotiations continued between the government and the 414-member
Leopards Battalion, the other unit that rebelled last week. Lt.
Col. Himmler Rebu, the commander, was deported after being named as
a conspirator in the coup attempt.
   Avril said 12 Leopards had not returned to their base, but the
battalion had accepted government authority.
   ``Everything is on the way to the re-establishment of order,''
Adjutant Gen. Andrei Jean-Pierre said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
