<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Drugs     04-11 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Czar Charged, Denies Connection with Narcotics Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug czar Miguel Angel Felix Gallardo,
believed to be the biggest cocaine dealer in Mexico, was charged
Tuesday with possession, trafficking and transportation of illegal
drugs.
   ``I don't know why they connect me with the cocaine business,''
he said in the 10th District Court after the charges were read. ``I
have never had that type of dealings.''
   The court is located inside the Southern Prison on the outskirts
of Mexico City. Felix Gallardo stood behind bars during the
proceeding.
   He was asked if he used drugs and he replied, ``Yes,
sporadically, but I'm not an addict.''
   Felix Gallardo was moved under heavy guard before dawn from the
Attorney General's office where he had been held since his arrest
Saturday in Guadalajara.
   Nine others arrested in the investigation, including several of
Felix Gallardo's aides and the chief federal anti-drug official and
five other ranking police officers in Sinaloa state, were jailed in
Mexico City's Northern Prison.
   Authorities on Monday seized some of Felix Gallardo's assets,
including a hotel, pharmacy, real-estate company, bank accounts and
other properties. No value was placed on the assets, but his net
worth is estimated to exceed $500 million.
   He was asked in court how much he earned. He said he could not
say.
   Judge Amado Guerrero Alvardo said the charges against Felix
Gallardo carry a sentence of seven to 15 years.
   The judge has three days to decide whether to issue an
indictment and then a year to review the evidence and present the
verdict.
   Attorney General Enrique Alvarez del Castillo on Monday called
Felix Gallardo ``the No. 1 drug trafficker in Mexico.''
   In the northwestern state of Sinaloa, judicial police patrolled
the residential zones in Felix Gallardo's hometown of Culiacan,
especially the districts where he owned property.
   Felix Gallardo, 43, was taken to the 10th District Court on the
basis of a warrant the court issued for him in 1986 after the
arrest of Hugo Devere Becerra.
   Parts of the 500-page court document read to Felix Gallardo were
based on testimony by Devere Becerra, who allegedly was Felix
Gallardo's partner for a year or two beginning in 1983.
   Devere Becerra also has been linked to other drug traffickers,
including Rafael Caro Quintero, who was arrested in the 1985
slaying of American DEA agent Enrique Camarena Salazar.
   Caro Quintero was sentenced in September 1988 to 34 years in
prison after being convicted on drug-related charges. He has not
been tried in the abduction, torture and killing of Camarena
Salazar. That case is in a court in the western city of Guadalajara.
   During Tuesday's hearing, Felix Gallardo denied knowing Devere
Becerra or at least four other reputed narcotics kingpins. He was
not asked about Caro Quintero.
   Alvarez del Castillo said Monday his office had no evidence
linking Felix Gallardo directly to the killing of Camarena Salazar,
but he said he was the ``intellectual author'' of the organization
that murdered the agent.
   Felix Gallardo was asked by the court what he did between March
and December of 1984 _ the period covered by Devere Becerra's
depositions.
   He said, ``During this period I was only dedicated to my hotel
business, and a concession for sales of building, along with
various businesses in which I'm up to date on tax payments.''
   He gave his profession as a businessman, said he was married and
had four children and had attended junior high school. He also said
he was a native of Culiacan and lived in Guadalajara.
   Felix Gallardo denied testimony in the court record that he used
several airplanes, including his own $1.5 million Aerocommander, to
transport drugs from South America to various parts of Mexico and
sometimes across the border to the United States.
</TEXT>
