<FIRST>r w AM-Engeleiter     04-11 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Engeleiter,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Engeleiter for Administration Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Small Business Committee voted on
Tuesday for the nomination of Susan S. Engeleiter to be chief of
the Small Business Administration, five months after she lost a bid
for the U.S. Senate.
   By a unanimous voice vote, the panel sent the nomination to the
full Senate, where her formal confirmation is expected as early as
next week.
   The Small Business Administration was persistently targeted for
elimination by former President Reagan as part of his deficit
reduction efforts. But Engeleiter, 37, told the lawmakers that the
agency's ``future is bright'' under President Bush.
   ``President Bush fully appreciates the importance of small
business to the American economy, and the importance of the Small
Business Administration to small businesses,'' she said in her
opening remarks.
   Engeleiter, the Wisconsin State Senate Republican leader, was
defeated in November by Democrat Herbert H. Kohl in the race for
the U.S. Senate seat vacated by William Proxmire, who retired.
   Her selection to head the Small Business Administration was
supported by several business groups, including National Small
Business United, the National Federation of Independent Business,
and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. She would be the first woman to
head the agency.
