<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-HospitalKillings 2ndLd-Writethru a0603 04-11 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Killings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0603,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Quiz Nurses Aid Who Gave Early Tip on 49 ``Mercy Deaths''
^Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with police comments, detail. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIE2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse's aide who reported a suspicious
death at a hospital last year was questioned Tuesday by police
investigating four other nurse's aides who confessed to what they
described as 49 ``mercy killings.''
   All the patients at Lainz Hospital were elderly _ 75 years or
older _ and were killed over the past six years with overdoses of
medicine or by water forced into their lungs. Police said they
doubted the claim of mercy killing because of the methods used.
   One investigator said the nurse's aides also admitted to killing
patients they considered a nuisance.
   After a Cabinet meeting Tuesday, Chancellor Franz Vranitzky
spoke of the case as ``the most brutal and gruesome crime in
Austria's history.''
   The killings prompted Vienna Mayor Helmut Zilk to evoke Nazi
medical experiments at Auschwitz and other death camps.
   ``The death angels of Lainz remind me of the death angels of
Auschwitz,'' Zilk said during a televised debate late Monday.
   Nurse's aides Maria Gruber, 25; Irene Leidolf, 27; Waltraud
Wagner, 30, and Stephanie Mayer, 50, are in custody, but no charges
have been filed. Three were arrested Friday and one Sunday.
   Police said Ms. Wagner admitted killing 39 patients, 22 of them
by forcing water into their lungs, and Ms. Mayer to killing five
patients, one with water.
   A fifth nurse's aide, Chilean-born Dorah Eugenie
Ferrada-Avendano, was on vacation when a warrant for her arrest was
issued, and she went to police Tuesday for questioning.
   Authorities said they doubted she was involved and speculated
the other four implicated her because she reported her suspicions
last year.
   The first deaths in the ward _ which has come to be known as
``The Death Pavilion'' _ occurred in 1983, but most were committed
in the last two years, police said.
   Max Edelbacher, a senior police investigator, said Tuesday that
questioning of nursing personnel substantiated the assumption of
``knowledge and suspicion'' about the crimes committed at the
hospital's First Medical Department. He said police got the
impression staff members did not take rumors about the deaths
seriously.
   Edelbacher told The Associated Press the total of patients
killed will probably rise above 49 with further investigation.
   As aides, the women were supposed to wash and feed patients, but
not to give injections, according to hospital officials.
   Austrian radio said Ms. Ferrada-Avendano told police she knew of
one murder and told a doctor about it.
   But Edelbacher said she knew of killings at the hospital two or
three years before she first mentioned her suspicion last year.
   He said that as a single woman coming from abroad and having to
look after a son, she was under constraint that made it hard for
her to approach authorities.
   Police Chief Guenter Boegl has said the overdoses administered
were insulin or tranquilizers.
   Police sources said aides plugged the noses of at least 23
victims and pumped water into their lungs. Investigators said each
nurse knew the others were killing patients, and in some cases two
nurses would act together.
   An unidentified man, confirming a newspaper interview, told
Austrian TV he saw Waltraud Wagner administer sleeping medication
to a 86-year-old male patient who died hours later. The man refused
to face the camera or give his name.
   Franz Pesendorfer, who heads the department where the murders
occurred, said he and his doctors could not have known about the
mass slayings because the crimes were committed in a secret and
sophisticated way.
   Edelbacher said police met ``a wall of silence'' when they tried
to get the name of the doctor said to have been told about
suspicious events in the ward.
   Zilk read a police statement that said the doctor, when finally
identified, refused to name his informant.
   The mayor appointed a commission to consider possible negligence
at the hospital, Vienna's fourth largest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
