<SECOND>AM-Grace Jones, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0642,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grace Jones Bailed On Cocaine Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with details on Jones, CORRECTS reference
to Stanley, her husband. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grace Jones, the flamboyant singer and
film actress, was freed from jail Tuesday after a court granted her
bail on a charge of possessing cocaine.
   Magistrate Carol Lawrence-Beswick freed the Jamaica-born Ms.
Jones on $2,700 bail on condition she returns for trial June 6.
   Ms. Jones, 36, who became a movie star in the James Bond film
``A View to a Kill,'' sat on a prisoner's bench, occasionally
conferring with her lawyer. She was not asked to enter a plea.
   Her lawyer, Tom Tavares-Finson, told the court the entertainer
is not a drug user, and is involved in the campaign against drug
abuse.
   Spectators packed the small courtroom. A crowd of about 200
gathered outside the courthouse, and some shouted support as she
left.
   Ms. Jones had been held in a police station cell since Saturday,
when police charge they found 0.006 ounces of cocaine wrapped in
two $2 Jamaican bills in her purse. If convicted, she probably will
be fined rather than jailed because of the small quantity of the
narcotic involved, court observers said.
   At Tuesday's hearing, Clerk of Court Alicia Jones opposed bail,
saying the actress would not be inclined to return for trial
because of her business obligations.
   But Tavares-Finson said it was because of recording and
advertising contracts that Ms. Jones wants to stand trial so she
can be cleared of the charge.
   Ms. Jones was arrested after police raided the Music Mountain
Recording Studio in the Kingston suburb of Stony Hill, which also
doubles as the home of her husband, record producer Chris Stanley.
   According to the prosecution, the entertainer was in a bedroom
when police approached. Police searched her handbag and allegedly
found a small quantity of cocaine wrapped in a $2 bill. At the
Stony Hill police station later, police searched her bag again and
found more cocaine wrapped in another $2 bill, the prosecution
alleged.
   Ms. Jones, who has been called the ``high priestess of
androgyny,'' is known for her crewcut and bizarre stage acts.
   She grew up in Syracuse, N.Y., and studied acting before
becoming a model in Manhattan. She appeared on the covers of Vogue
and Elle magazines. She now lives in Los Angeles and New York.
   As a singer, Ms. Jones capitalized on the disco boom. Her most
recent album, ``No Compromise,'' produced by Stanley, is scheduled
to come out in June.
</TEXT>
