<FIRST>r a AM-ArchbishopNamed     04-11 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Archbishop Named,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harrisburg Bishop Named Archbishop of Baltimore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop William H. Keeler was named Tuesday as
the 14th archbishop of the nation's oldeset archdiocese.
   ``I am honored and deeply grateful to our Holy Father for this
assignment,'' Keeler, 58, said at a news conference. ``I pledge to
Pope John Paul my loyalty, and I know that I have his support.''
   He will be installed May 23, succeeding Archbishop William D.
Borders, 75, who retired. Borders will continue to serve as
administrative leader of the archdiocese until Keeler's
installation.
   Keeler of Harrisburg, Pa., said he was both bewildered and
humbled.
   ``Bewildered because of my human limitations and also because it
meant leaving the Diocese of Harrisburg, where I have been as a
priest and bishop for so many years,'' he said.
   ``Humbled because of the new and heavier responsiblities and
because of a long line of great archbishops here,'' Keeler said.
   Keeler is considered a conservative. He has taken stances
against cohabitation, premarital sex, abortion and capital
punishment.
   Borders had a reputation as a liberal, supporting an increased
role for women and the laity in the church and opposing U.S. aid to
the government in El Salvador.
   In taking over the oldest archdiocese in the United States,
which observes its bicentennial this fall, Keeler will confront
such challenges as the alarming decrease in the number of Catholic
priests and nuns.
   Following church tradition, Pope John Paul II chose the new
archbishop after a secretive selection process in which the pontiff
considered the recommendations of U.S. bishops, the Vatican
ambassador to the United States and Vatican officials.
</TEXT>
