<FIRST>r i AM-GanderCrash     04-11 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gander Crash,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Testimony Won't be Taken During Review of Gander Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Supreme Court Justice Willard Estey said
Tuesday he will not hear new testimony in reviewing the disputed
investigation of a 1985 Gander, Newfoundland, airplane crash that
killed 256 Americans
   ``I'm giving a legal opinion; I'm not holding a hearing,'' Estey
said in a phone interview from his office in Toronto. ``I'm sitting
here reading tons of evidence.''
   Estey agreed last month to review a three-year investigation by
the Canadian Aviation Safety Board and deliver a report in 90 days
on whether it was adequate or if further investigation or even a
new inquiry is warranted.
   A letter from Estey to a transportation official, published
Tuesday by the Ottawa Citizen, rejected requests that he hear new
testimony.
   Estey said he had no direct comment on the Citizen's report, but
remarked that the terms of reference for his 90-day review were to
decide if a new hearing is needed and not to hold one now.
   The safety board's report on Canada's worst air disaster was
released in December after internal disputes that often went public.
   Five of the nine members approved the report saying the probable
cause of the Dec. 12, 1985, crash was ice on the wings of the Arrow
Air charter DC-8.
   Four members released a minority report saying an in-flight fire
or explosion was the most likely cause.
   The plane carrying U.S. soldiers from Middle East peacekeeping
duties to Fort Campbell, Ky., crashed shortly after taking off from
a refueling stop at Gander. Killed were 248 U.S. servicemen and
eight crew.
   According to the letter obtained by the Citizen, Estey decided
to base his review on existing records of the crash investigation.
   This upset some members of the safety board and families of
crash victims, who hoped Estey would let them testify on why they
believe a full-scale judicial inquiry into the disaster is
warranted.
   In an April 5 letter to a Transport Canada official, the Ottawa
Citizen reported, Estey wrote he had heard some safety board
members planned to submit new information.
   ``If I were to entertain submissions from board members, I
believe that that would be both improper in law and would oblige me
to hear submissions from all interested parties on an equal
footing,'' it quoted the letter as saying.
   Transportation Minister Benoit Bouchard named Estey to review
the investigation last month.
   Theresa Griffin, widow of pilot John Griffin, wrote Estey last
week asking to testify. She is among those trying to clear the name
of Griffin, indirectly blamed for the accident by not having the
plane de-iced before takeoff.
   ``This is not going to be an impartial review,'' said Jerry
Rusinowitz, a Griffin supporter. ``The fact that we are being
excluded is intentional. It's part of the game plan. It's a
cover-up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
