<HEAD>East German Urges More NATO Disarmament Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany said Tuesday the Western alliance
should make greater efforts toward disarmament.
   Its official news agency ADN said Foreign Minister Oskar
Fischer, at a meeting of Warsaw Pact colleagues, ``stressed his
wish that NATO countries soon decide to become reliable
(negotiating) partners who not only do not apply the brakes but
also help bring about a rapid pace in disarmament.''
   Warsaw Pact officials frequently accuse the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization of responding slowly to recent disarmament
initiatives by the Soviet Union.
   Missing from the East Berlin meeting was the Soviet foreign
minister, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, who was in his native republic of
Soviet Georgia because of unrest there. Alexander Bessmertnykh,
first deputy foreign minister, attended in his place.

