<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey     04-11 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ozal Government Wins Vote Of Confidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The center-right government of Premier
Turgut Ozal, whose party suffered defeat in local elections last
month, won a vote of confidence in Parliament on Tuesday, 289 to 95.
   The 57 members of the centrist True Path Party boycotted the
vote in the one-house, 450-seat Parliament. The chief opposition,
the Social Democrat Populist Party, voted against the government.
   Ozal's Motherland Party has an overwhelming majority in the
legislature.
   After the setback in local polling, Ozal overhauled his Cabinet
and then sought the confidence vote.
   About 300,000 workers meanwhile joined a campaign of passive
resistance called by Turk-Is, the nation's largest labor union
confederation, to protest what it said were low incomes at a time
of high inflation.
   The protest includes a work slowdown, a boycott of
company-provided luncheons, the growing of beards, a refusal to
work overtime, and going for hospital visits en masse, said Turk-Is
spokesman Erkin Okay.
   Turk-Is President Sevket Yilmaz, whose federation has 1.8
million members, said on Tuesday that the campaign was prompted by
deadlock in contract negotiations for more than 600,000 workers
employed by state agencies such as sugar factories, the Electricity
Authority and State Highways Department.
   In March 26 local elections, Motherland won only 22 percent of
the vote nationwide and trailed both the Social Democrat and True
Path parties.
   Ozal has vowed to stay on until his term ends in 1992, but many
in his own party concede that early elections are inevitable and
say Ozal wants to delay the voting until 1990.
   He apparently hopes to win voter support if given more time to
lower inflation, which reached 75 percent last year.
</TEXT>
