<HEAD>Storms Lash Wales and Southwest England, Then Head North</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winds up to 99 mph lashed western Wales and
southwest England on Tuesday, knocking down power lines, damaging
houses and blocking roads.
   Thousands of homes in Devon and Cornwall in southwest England
and in southwest and mid-Wales were without power Tuesday night
after trees brought down overhead cables.
   The London Weather Center said the storms moved through the
English Midlands and northern England.
   Two jetliners being readied for flight were grounded at
Manchester airport after they were blown onto equipment by winds
gusting up to 70 mph and a third plane carrying 70 passengers twice
overshot the runway before being diverted to Birmingham, airport
authorities said.
   The storms were caused by a deepening depression over the Irish
Sea with winds up to 99 mph recorded at Milford Haven in south
Wales, where roofs were stripped and windows blown out, the weather
center said.
   Falling trees blocked roads and strong winds overturned trucks
and cars, police reported.
