<FIRST>r w AM-BRF-NavyExercise 130   04-11 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-Navy Exercise, 130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Exercise Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon announced Tuesday the annual
``Solid Shield'' naval exercise would be conducted next month and
would involve some 43,000 servicemen from all the military branches.
   The exercise, conducted each year by the U.S. Atlantic Command,
will center on 27 Navy ships led by the aircraft carrier USS
Eisenhower, the Pentagon said.
   Beyond naval operations, mock amphibious assaults will be
conducted at Camp Lejeune, N.C., by Marine and Army units.
   ``Multi-service aircraft and Navy and Coast Guard surface
(warships) will simulate attacks against the amphibious task force
to practice anti-air, anti-surface and anti-submarine tactics,''
the Pentagon added.
   The exercise will range up and down much of the East coast and
will run from May 1 to 20, the Pentagon said.
</TEXT>
