<FIRST>r w AM-WaterFight 1st-LdWritethru   04-11 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Water Fight, 1st-Ld Writethru,a0669,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Following INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf pvs to update with
comments from Rep. Miller and attorney for environmental groups. Pickup
6th grav pvs: The Friant etc.</HEAD>
<HEAD>California Water Program Renewed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Department, faced with a
long-running fight over central California water, announced the
renewal Tuesday of a long-term contract to supply water to farmers
despite objections from environmentalists.
   But Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan Jr. directed that an
environmental assessment of the lease renewal be done and he
suggested that state officials and other interested groups could
solve any environmental problems.
   While the lease only involves the Orange Cove Irrigation
District in the San Joaquin Valley, the action is likely to set a
precedent for other central California irrigation projects which
serve farmers who also rely on the delivery of federal water
through an elaborate system of dams and canals.
   Environmentalists have opposed a renewal of the long-term leases
because they argue the leases lock the government into supplying a
certain volume of water well into the next century at a time when
rapid population growth also is putting new demands on non-farming
water needs.
   As water continues to be diverted for both agriculture and urban
use, streams will dry up and seasonal wetlands, which support
migratory waterfowl, will disappear, the critics maintain.
   Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., chairman of the Interior
subcommittee on water, power and offshore energy resources, sharply
criticized the decision to resume renewing the leases at a time
when there are uncertainties about their environmental impact.
   ``This decision further corrodes the environmental credentials
of the Bush administration,'' Miller said.
   Randall Block, an attorney who represents several environmental
groups that have challenged the lease renewals, said, ``It's kind
of backward to sign the leases and then order an environmental
assessment.''
   The Friant Unit of the Central Valley Project, as the huge
irrigation system is called, receives 1.5 million acre-feet of
water a year from Interior's Bureau of Reclamation, providing water
for both large and small farms and orchards.
   The decision to renew the lease came as different agencies of
the Bush administration also continued to disagree sharply on
whether new California water contracts running 40 years should be
issued without resolving all their potential environmental
ramifications.
   After the Interior Department indicated last November that it
planned to renew the 40-year leases without first developing formal
environmental impact statements, the Environmental Protection
Agency challenged the leases, elevating the matter to the White
House.
   More than a dozen environmental groups also protested and the
Natural Resources Defense Council filed suit in California arguing
that another 40-year water commitment is such a significant act
that it requires a formal environmental assessment under the
National Environmental Policy Act.
   A federal judge recently said, in response to the suit, the
leases could be issued, but he reserved the right to void any such
lease, depending on the outcome of the government debate over
environmental issues.
   The president's Council on Environmental Quality has scheduled
meetings in Washington and California on Thursday and Monday to
gather information on the environmental issues surrounding the
lease renewal controversy.
   While the presidential council has no authority to block the
leases or order environmental assessments, its opinions on such
matters historically have carried considerable weight among federal
agencies and in Congress.
   In a statement, Lujan said the department action on the Orange
Cove lease renewal should not have an impact on the CEQ
proceedings. He said he has ordered the head of the Bureau of
Reclamation to proceed with an environmental assessment of
continuing water deliveries to the massive Central Valley Project,
of which Orange Cove is only a small part.
   ``The renewal of long-term water supply contracts may pose
legitimate environmental concerns,'' said Lujan, adding that the
assessment he ordered should be ``considered by the state and
(local) districts as they adopt environmentally sensitive operating
procedures and water policies.''
   ``That is essentially different than doing an EIS (environmental
impact statement under federal law),'' suggested Richard Sanderson,
director of the office of federal activities at the Environmental
Protection Agency. He said Interior officials are essentially
``sidestepping'' the National Environmental Policy Act in the
procedures being used to consider the environmental issues.
   ``Our position (at EPA) is the entire water issue for California
needs to be reviewed in light of today's environmental standards
and particularly the environmental requirements 40 years hence,''
said Sanderson in an interview.
   Lujan said the lease renewal would encourage increased water
conservation among the farmers by charging ``substantially higher
prices'' for the water. Uder the new contract with Orange Cove, the
cost of federal water would quadruple from $3.50 to $14.94 per acre
foot, he said.
   An acre foot is an amount of water need to flood an acre of land
one foot deep, or about 350,000 gallons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
