<FIRST>r w AM-OverseasRadio     04-11 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Overseas Radio,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jamming Halt Seen as US Chance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's decision to stop jamming
Radio Free Europe and Radio Liberty presents an unparalled
opportunity to spread American ideals and policies in Eastern
Europe, an official said Tuesday in seeking new money for the
U.S.-operated networks.
   Malcolm S. Forbes Jr., the publishing magnate and chairman of
the Board for International Broadcasting, told a Senate
subcommittee that the greatest challenge for RFE@RL is to respond
to the end to jamming despite severe budget constraints.
   He said Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's new policy of
openness has placed the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe ``at a
crossroads of history.''
   Soviet jamming stopped late last year, making the mission of
RFE@RL ``more important than at any time in its nearly 40-year
history,'' Forbes said. ``The United States can affect the nature
and direction of reforms in the East bloc by ensuring that all
citizens of the region have access to the full range of information
necessary for making intelligent political decisions.''
   The Board for International Broadcasting, an independent federal
agency that oversees RFE@RL, is seeking a $425.2 million
appropriation in fiscal 1990 to beam its broadcasts into the Soviet
Union and Eastern Europe.
   More than 55 percent of that amount _ $234.8 million _ is a
one-time expense to complete modernization of RFE@RL's transmitting
system.
   About $207 million will go to build a new relay station in
Israel, with the rest to be the final installment on a refurbishing
program for existing relay stations that began in 1985.
   ``Funding of BIB modernization needs is critical in fiscal year
1990,'' said Pat Schlueter, the agency's financial manager. ``This
is very important for the Israeli relay station, so the major
contracts can be let in 1990.''
   The relay station will be used jointly by RFE@RL and Voice of
America, the radio network operated by the U.S. Information Agency,
and will increase the stations signals by 300 percent in Central
Asia beginning in 1992, Forbes said.
   Marvin L. Stone, acting director of USIA, proposed a 1990
appropriation of $949.2 million at the hearing before a Senate
Appropriations subcommittee.
   Stone said the budget request is a $66.9 million increase over
this year, but that losses in funds from the State Department and
other cost increases will mean an actual cutback in USIA's
operating funds.
   He said USIA will be forced to cut back VOA's Greek and Turkish
language broadcasts, close some relay stations and overseas posts
and cut staff.
   House and Senate appropriations subcommittees have been
supportive of the budget requests, but ``neither have made any
promises,'' said an agency official who spoke only on condition of
anonymity.
   The USIA budget does not call for any money for the
controversial TV Marti project, which is to beam VOA broadcasts to
Cuba. But Stone said USIA is negotiating with the Office of
Management and Budget for a 1990 budget amendment for TV Marti.
   USIA's 1989 appropriation included $7.5 million in startup funds
for TV Marti, which faces strong opposition from U.S. broadcasters
who fear it will interfere with their TV signals.
   A presidential commission in January questioned TV Marti's
legality and technical feasibility.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., who is chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, has opposed TV Marti, particularly in
light of the Soviet decision to stop jamming U.S. broadcasts in
Eastern Europe.
   The House is expected to vote on new TV Marti funding Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
