<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Bribe     04-11 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Bribe,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Adviser Charged With Accepting Bribes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An adviser to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir was
indicted Tuesday on charges of accepting bribes in land deals in
the occupied West Bank, and Israel radio said the money was passed
to Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc.
   A Tel Aviv district court accused Michael Dekel, a former deputy
minister of agriculture, of soliciting $233,000 in bribes from land
developers in return for help in obtaining government permits for
buying land in the West Bank.
   The indictment said Dekel began demanding the money in April
1984, after national elections were announced, and that Dekel's
assistant, Avi Tzur, passed the money to the Likud and other
organizations linked to the political bloc.
   The elections, held in July 1984, ended in a stalemate between
the Likud and the left-leaning Labor Party, and the two formed a
joint unity government.
   Prosecutor Rachel Shiber said Dekel received money from at least
four land dealers.
   Dekel, now Shamir's adviser on settlements in the occupied
lands, was charged with soliciting and accepting bribes, breach of
confidence and conspiracy. He faces a maximum sentence of 10 years
in prison if convicted.
   As deputy agriculture minister for settlement affairs from
August 1981 to October 1984, Dekel was instrumental in involving
private entrepreneurs in projects for building Jewish settlements
in the West Bank.
   About 70,000 Jewish settlers live in more than 130 settlements
among 1.7 million Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
which were captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</TEXT>
