<FIRST>u a AM-CopterDown     04-11 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Copter Down,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MI3,4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chopper Goes Down In Milwaukee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter being used to work on a high-rise
building crashed Tuesday morning near the Lake Michigan shore, but
the pilot escaped serious injury, authorities said.
   Ben Moore, 43, of Elmhurst, Ill., was taken to the Milwaukee
County Medical Complex, where he was treated for cuts to the leg
and face, said hospital spokeswoman Pam Hansen.
   The helicopter went down around 10:25 a.m. next to the U.S.
Coast Guard Station on Milwaukee's south side.
   A Milwaukee Fire Department dispatcher said the crash occurred
as the pilot was trying to remove an air-conditioning unit from the
top of a 25-story condominium.
   A homemade videotape showed the helicopter going out of control
suddenly while lowering the air conditioning unit.
   Bill Bruce, an investigator with the National Transportation
Safety Board, said he reviewed the videotape and concluded that the
helicopter lost power to the tail rotor. Bruce gave the pilot
credit for avoiding the building once he lost control.
   ``He did the best he could with it and brought it down,'' he
said.
   Ray Seaberg, a Coast Guard seaman, said he was watching the
helicopter work when the vehicle's tail rotor hit the building and
the aircraft went into a spin. Seaberg and others helped pull the
pilot from the helicopter.
   Lt. Keith Cameron of the Coast Guard estimated about 20 gallons
of fuel leaked into the lake, but he said workers had the spill
contained and were cleaning it from the water.
</TEXT>
