<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-11 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>April Chill Threatens Crops in the South</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures dipped below freezing Tuesday through much of the
nation east of Rockies and in the South, where farmers scurried to
save their crops. More than 40 cities reported record lows.
   The low of 29 degrees at Dallas-Fort Worth was a record April,
and lows of 31 degrees at Shreveport, La., and 26 at Hot Springs,
Ark., tied records for the month.
   Frost and freeze warnings were posted Tuesday night for parts of
Virginia, Maryland, Delaware, North Carolina, South Carolina, West
Virginia, Tennessee, Alabama, Pennsylvania and New Jersey.
   Tennessee fruit growers assessed the damage from the cold snap
that apparently cut heavily into peach, plum and strawberry crops.
   The cold wave sent temperatures into the upper 20s in many parts
of the state and left behind dead or dying plums and peaches,
officials said. Apple and pear crops weathered better because they
had not yet bloomed as much as the peaches, plums and strawberries.
   In Alabama, a record low of 28 degrees had apple, peach and plum
farmers worried about their crops.
   In Indiana, many growers rushed Monday night to light smudge
pots and activate irrigation systems to save their crops as
overnight lows dipped to the 20s in much of the state.
   In North Carolina, a record-breaking springtime snow hit the
eastern part of the state early Tuesday, dusting streets and lawns
but causing few problems other than delayed school openings.
   Morning snowfall totals in northeastern North Carolina reached 5
inches in Camden County, with 4 inches in Currituck County. By
Tuesday afternoon, the snow had changed to rain or moved off the
coast.
   The Southwest basked in higher temperatures, with readings in
California and southern Arizona in the 80s and 90s.
   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation, with sunny
skies over much of the West and the Southeast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 31
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 93 degrees at
Needles, Calif. The nation's low for Tuesday was 9 degrees at
Yellowstone.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for snow showers scattered
across the Great Lakes; showers and thunderstorms in southern
Florida, the southern Plains and the southern Rockies; and sunny
skies over the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 50s and 60s over much of
the nation; in the 40s from the upper Mississippi Valley to New
England; in the 70s across Louisiana and southern Texas; in the 70s
and lower 80s across the Florida peninsula; above 70 degrees across
Oregon, California, western Nevada and southern Arizona; and in the
80s and 90s in the California valleys and the Southwestern deserts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
