<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2dLd-Writethru a0666 04-11 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0666,0867</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Wave Outlawed Flags in Funeral Procession</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs at end with military court accusing two Palestinians
of belonging to illegal organizations.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of masked youths marched through the
Old City's narrow streets Tuesday, waving outlawed Palestinian
flags and carrying the coffin of a Palestinian killed by a Jewish
gunman the day before.
   One policeman fired tear gas and another fired rubber bullets at
stone throwers, wounding one in the leg, during the hourlong
procession. Police said they had detained three Jews ``suspected to
be linked to'' Monday's shooting, in which three other Palestinians
were wounded.
   When the mourners reached the Al Aqsa mosque compound, four
young men climbed to the mosque roof and raised a large Palestinian
flag while the crowd sang the Palestinian anthem ``Biladi, Biladi''
(My Homeland, My Homeland).
   On Monday, a man dressed in army fatigues opened fire with an
Uzi submachine gun near the Jaffa Gate entrance to the walled Old
City, killing Khaled Shawish, a 26-year-old blacksmith, and
wounding three companions.
   He fired from a distance of about five yards and escaped on foot
before police arrived.
   Police commander Yosef Yehudai said he believed the killer was a
reserve soldier.
   ``We seem to be speaking about an army reservist,'' he told
Israel television. ``There is a serious direction toward what I
would call nationalist motives,'' he told Israel television.
   Responsibility was claimed for an underground extremist group
named after the Sicarites, the Jewish assassins who fought the
Roman forces nearly 2,000 years ago. A man who said he spoke for
the Sicarites told Israel army radio they would increase attacks
``to improve the situation of Jews'' in the occupied lands.
   About 70,000 Jewish settlers live in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, which have a Palestinian population of 1.7 million.
   Most merchants in Arab east Jerusalem closed their shops in a
three-day strike to protest the shooting.
   At Shawish's house in a blind alley hung with two huge
Palestinian flags, dozens of angry young men raised more flags and
pictures of Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   They chanted: ``Arafat, don't worry, we have people for you! God
is great!''
   Many wore improvised black masks or bags with eyeholes over
their heads. Others had wrapped their faces in checkered scarves
called keffiyehs.
   One masked protester told a journalist: ``The Israelis must
choose if they want peace or war. We are not afraid of them. We
want our state in the West Bank and Gaza with Jerusalem its
capital.''
   As the funeral marchers moved through the cobblestone streets,
their ranks grew to about 1,000. They circled the Al Aqsa complex,
a holy site of Islam that also houses the Dome of the Rock mosque,
from which the prophet Mohammed is said to have ascended to heaven.
   Several of the young mourners attacked a nearby police station,
smashing windows and doors with their fists, legs and rocks. A
policeman responded with rubber bullets.
   Tension has increased in Jerusalem, home to 350,000 Jews and the
135,000 Palestinians of east Jerusalem, which Israel captured from
Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war.
   A riot outside Al Aqsa on Friday spilled over into the area of
the Western Wall, Judaism's holiest shrine. The holy sites are on
Temple Mount, known in Arabic as Haram al Sharif, or Noble
Sancutary.
   Police retaliated by saying people who might riot, mainly young
Palestinians from the occupied West Bank and Gaza, would not be
allowed to pray at Al Aqsa.
   In Tel Aviv, an Israeli teen-ager wounded two Gaza Strip youths
with a knife Tuesday, one of them seriously. The dispute apparently
began over a parking space, but police spokeswoman Dalia Gilad said
the possibility of an ethnic motive was being investigated.
   A general strike virtually closed the Gaza Strip. The
fundamentalist movement Hamas (Zeal) urged it to protest Israel's
deportation of more than 40 Palestinians during the 16-month-old
uprising against Israeli occupation.
   Arab reports said Israeli soldiers firing on stone-throwers in
Gaza wounded nine Palestinians, including a 90-year-old woman
struck in the left leg.
   The army confirmed one of the wounded and said it was
investigating the other incidents.
   The uprising has taken the lives of 423 Palestinians and 18
Israelis.
   In Lod, Israel, a military court indicted two Palestinians on
charges of belonging to illegal organizations. The defendants were
identified as Saman Khouri,41, and Adnan Shalalda, 35, both of
Jerusalem. They were arrested March 5.
   The indictment accuses Khouri of being a member of the Marxist
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine and Shalalda of
belonging to the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   It claims the two men prepared leaflets for the Palestine
Liberation Organization and its underground leaders of the uprising
in the occupied territories.
   Khouri, who worked as a correspondent for Agence France-Presse,
also was accused of receiving $1.5 million from a Palestinian
organization in Jordan and distributing it to PLO-affiliated groups
in the Gaza Strip and West Bank.
</TEXT>
