<FIRST>r w AM-PeaceCorpsVolunteers 250   04-11 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peace Corps Volunteers, 250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Peace Corps Volunteers Honored at White House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Peace Corps volunteers were honored at
the White House by First Lady Barbara Bush Tuesday for their work
overseas in Mauritania, West Africa; the Phillippines and Ecuador.
   Mary Monique Slater, 27, St. Louis, Mo., Michael C. Bainum, 25,
San Antonio, Tex., and Charles Campbell Rhoades, 27, Arvada, Colo.,
were honored as the 1989 John F. Kennedy Volunteers of the Year.
   For the past four years, the Volunteer of the Year award has
been given to one volunteer in each of Peace Corps' three overseas
regions whose work and demeanor exemplify the agency's goal of
building peace and understanding through mutual development.
   Slater was chosen as an example of a majority of the agriculture
volunteers in Mauritania involved in reforestation, dune
stablization and the introduction of improved cooking stoves. She
represented volunteers serving in sub-Saharan Africa, where almost
half of all 6,000 volunteers serve.
   Bainum has worked to offset environmental degradation in the
Bicol National Park near his site in the Philippines through
community organization and education, particularly among young
people. He represented the more than 1,425 volunteers workin
nations in North Africa, the Near East, Asia and the Pacific.
   Rhoades is credited with producing change in the attitudes of
many Ecuadorian farmers and protecting remaining native forests
through plantings that will fulfill local forestry needs. He
represented the almost 2,000 Peace Corps volunteers in Central and
South America and the Caribbean.
</TEXT>
