<FIRST>r a AM-People--FatsDomino     04-11 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People--Fats Domino,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fats Domino Honored in New Orleans Jazz Fest Poster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fats Domino is New Orleans' latest pinup star
_ four times over.
   Four identical portraits of Domino smile out of the 1989 New
Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival poster, which was unveiled here
Tuesday.
   ``That's just fine,'' the 62-year-old singer said of the poster.
``It represents when I was young and I like that about it.''
   The poster was done by New Orleans artist Richard Thomas, who
tinted 1960s pictures of Domino in four colors.
   ``After I was chosen to do the poster they told me they either
wanted Louis Armstrong or Fats Domino and I said `Let's do Fats,'''
Thomas said. ``I love them both, but people always kid me about how
much I look like Fats.''
   Domino, who said he works five to six months a year now, will
play May 7 at the 20th annual Jazz Fest this year.
   ``I play there every couple of years. I been at it since I was
18 so I'm slowing down a little now,'' he said.
   Wherever he plays, Domino said, the crowds ask for his old hits,
particularly ``Blueberry Hill.''
   ``All I need is a good piano and a good mike and I'm happy,'' he
said. ``I don't care if it's 10 people or 4,000 _ as long as I see
people enjoying themselves it makes no difference. I have a good
time too.''
