<FIRST>r a AM-MarriedCops     04-11 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Married Cops,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chief Decides To Fire Wife Of Police Lieutenant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police records clerk said Tuesday
that she was being fired from her job because she married another
member of the police force, even though she and her husband have
since filed for divorce.
   ``I'm going to appeal,'' said Evelyn Atencio, whose marriage
last August to Lt. Bob Larson placed their jobs in jeopardy because
of the city's nepotism policy.
   Atencio and Larson filed for divorce last month in an effort to
save their jobs. Despite that, Atencio said, Police Chief Bob Evers
decided to fire her as of April 20. It was not clear why she was
singled out and not her husband.
   Evers and City Manager Mark Achen did not return telephone calls
seeking comment Tuesday and the police chief told a reporter
waiting outside his office that he would have nothing to say about
the case.
   Atencio has worked in the police department for nine years and
her husband for 16. She said she wasn't interested in another city
job that paid less than her current job.
   ``I can't afford a cut in pay,'' she said. ``I was left
destitute after my (previous) divorce and I'm not going to let that
happen again.''
   The 34-year-old mother of three children said she ``didn't marry
Bob for him to support my kids.''
   City officials say that Larson, as administrative services
lieutenant, is in charge of Atencio's direct supervisor and as such
has control over his wife's job.
   Larson and Atencio say that because Larson doesn't directly
supervise his wife, they aren't violating the nepotism policy.
   Atencio said the couple filed for divorce March 13 after city
personnel director Claudia Hazelhurst agreed that they would be
given more time to find new jobs ``if we could show intent to
divorce and documentation that divorce proceedings were under way.''
   Colorado law requires at least 90 days before a divorce becomes
final.
</TEXT>
