<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 2052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Sudan     04-11 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Sudan,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Donors Pledge All Funds Needed for Sudan Relief Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donors pledged all $133 million needed to
stockpile food in Sudan before the rainy season isolates villages,
but a U.N. official said Tuesday not all Sudanese who need help can
be reached.
   James P. Grant, head of Operation Sudan Lifeline and director of
the U.N. Children's Fund, told reporters the goal of aiding 1
million people and preventing more than 100,000 deaths by
starvation ``may be unrealistic, but it's what is needed.''
   ``We have no alternative but to try.''
   The operation hopes to move 110,000 tons of food to isolated
villages in Sudan before the rains begin in May, washing out roads
and airstrips.
   In August 1985, at the height of the Ethiopian famine,
international agencies delivered only 85,000 tons of food under far
more favorable conditions.
   The United Nations estimates 250,000 Sudanese starved to death
last year because of flood, drought or war-induced famine.
   Grant said about 22,000 tons of food have been delivered so far,
divided about equally between areas controlled by the
Moslem-dominated government in Khartoum and rebel areas in the
south, which is mainly Christian or animist.
   The emergency program had received $77 million in pledges by the
time Grant led a U.N. planning conference a month ago in Khartoum
and received pledges for te rest of the $133 million needed at a
donor pledging meeting Tuesday.
   Pledges include $11 million from the United States, $10 million
from the European Community, and the donation by France and West
Germany of the services of four Transall aircraft to carry relief
supplies, said Grant.
   Grant denied reports that Juba in southern Sudanese was cut off
from airlifts by threats from the rebel Sudan People's Liberation
Army or that Ethiopia closed its border to food convoys.
   ``There is no cease-fire,'' Grant acknowledged, but he said two
relief flights are reaching Juba daily.
   The co-coordinator for Operation Lifeline Sudan, Vincent
O'Reilly, said Monday that Ethiopia's President Mengistu Haile
Mariam closed the border.
   Grant said Mengistu has cabled Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar reaffirming his complete support for the convoy program,
and negotiations are under way on details of road shipments.
</TEXT>
