<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 2053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HandicappedAccess     04-11 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Handicapped Access,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration To Appeal Wheelchair Lifts Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government wants to appeal a
decision requiring wheelchair lifts on all new public buses, saying
the ruling would cost the nation's mass transit systems $90 million
a year.
   Groups representing the disabled praised the Feb. 13 ruling by
the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals as a means to help put
handicapped people into the mainstream, but transit agencies said
the costly lifts are rarely used.
   In petitioning Monday for a rehearing by the full court, the
government said the ruling contradicted Congress' intent. In
addition, the government argued, the court failed to comprehend the
full cost of the order.
   In the 2-1 decision, the court ordered the U.S. Department of
Transportation to rewrite regulations that allow communities to
offer only ``paratransit'' service, such as van rides, to the
disabled. The court said the 24-hour reservations that van riders
need hindered spontaneous use of mass transit.
   The judges said instead that all new buses must be equipped with
lifts.
   Since the decision, disabled people nationwide have demonstrated
in hopes of persuading the Bush administration to allow the ruling
to stand.
   The case was brought by the American Disabled for Accessible
Public Transit and other groups for handicapped people.
   Stephen Gold, an attorney for ADAPT, said the Bush
administration's decision to appeal is ``a slap in the face'' and
renders the president's pledge of a ``kinder, gentler nation'' a
hollow promise.
   `It'll keep disabled people out of the mainstream and out of
jobs for years and years to come,'' he said.
   In its petition, the government argued the legislation does not
require ``wholesale restructuring of mass-transit services or
imposition of the attendant financial burdens on an already
overburdened public transportation system.''
   The government said transit agencies across the country would
pay $90 million a year for the lifts. In addition to $10,000 for
each lift, the government said, maintenance and operating expenses
would add $9,600 over 12 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
