<FIRST>r i AM-France-Crash     04-11 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Crash,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Seek To Determine Why Plane Flew Off Course</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALENCE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators recovered two flight
recorders Tuesday from the Fokker 27 which crashed into a mountain
cliff, killing all 22 people aboard, and sought clues as to why the
plane strayed from its flight path on its final landing approach.
   Transport Minister Michel Delebarre set up a commission to
investigate the crash, which occurred Monday night about 15 miles
east of Valence.
   The twin-engine Uni-Air plane, chartered by Europe Aero Service,
was bound from Paris to Valence on a domestic flight. Air
controllers lost contact with it about 10 minutes before it was to
land.
   Delebarre came to Valence to convey government condolences to
kin of the 19 passengers and three crew. He said an investigating
commission must ``make clear what happened and, mainly, why this
plane was not within its itinerary.'' According to preliminary
information, the aircraft also was flying too low, the French news
agency Agence France-Presse reported.
