<FIRST>r a AM-WPPSSBonds     04-11 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WPPSS Bonds,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorneys Defend Settlement In Massive WPPSS Fraud Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for a group of bondholders said Tuesday
that a $750 million settlement in the $2.25 billion Washington
Public Power Supply System default case was the best deal they
could get.
   U.S. District Court Judge William D. Browning heard the
appraisal at a hearing on how to distribute money from settlements
made late last year in the WPPSS fraud case, the biggest default in
U.S. municipal bond history.
   The settlement must be divided among more than 24,000 plaintiffs
and attorneys.
   However, representatives of a separate group of bondholders in
the class-action suit said they will argue that no settlement
should be allowed until after the court decides individual
bondholders' and attorneys' shares in the settlement.
   The attorneys also want to argue that the state of Washington,
the Bonneville Power Administration and WPPSS should bear more
responsibility for their roles in the case.
   The legal action grew from WPPSS' 1983 default on $2.25 billion
in bonds sold to finance two nuclear power plants that were
abandoned before completion.
   Melvyn Weiss, a plaintiff attorney, said he and other attorneys
for bondholders felt that the best they might achieve if they won
the case was a $1.4 billion settlement.
   The $750 million settlement was much more realistic, ``and it
could well be much less,'' said Weiss.
   Weiss said he recognized it's ``a horrible thing'' for people to
lose money that could have meant their retirement or savings for
education, but ``we also understand if you get nothing, it's
nothing.''
   Attorneys for the bondholders unhappy with the settlement
promised to press their argument before Browning.
   ``We have a hard fight,'' Arthur Hoffer, who is pursuing a
separate class-action suit against the state of Washington on
behalf of bondholders, said Monday night. ``But we're not going to
give up.''
   Defendants in the federal lawsuit, which incorporated dozens of
separate suits filed as early as 1983 in federal court in Seattle,
included the supply system, the 88 utilities that contracted with
WPPSS to build the two plants, engineering firms, the Wall Street
bond underwriters, utility and WPPSS directors and the advisory
firm of Blyth Eastman.
</TEXT>
