<FIRST>r a AM-ChemicalFire     04-11 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Fire,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Causes Problems For Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SATICOY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that turned into a ``real witch's
brew'' of dangerous chemicals burned itself out after about 1,600
people were evacuated and 17 were taken to hospitals, authorities
said Tuesday.
   The fire at Pacific Intermediates, a company that blends
chemicals for pharmacies and other businesses, started about 6 p.m.
Monday, and burned through the night. It kept people from their
homes for more than 12 hours.
   The Red Cross housed 357 people at an evacuation center set up
at Buena High School until they were allowed to return home at 5:15
a.m. Tuesday, about 75 minutes after the fire burned itself out.
   One hundred people were ordered to evacuate and another 1,500
were asked to leave their homes voluntarily, said Ventura County
Fire Department Dispatcher Vicki Crabtree. The unincorporated town
of Saticoy is about 75 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
   Noxious fumes sent 17 people to hospitals, firefighters said.
All were treated and released except Ventura County Fire Department
Capt. Sam Turner, who was in stable condition Tuesday at Los Robles
Regional Medical Center in Thousand Oaks.
   The fire's cause was still under investigation Tuesday, Ms.
Crabtree said. She said there was no damage estimate yet.
   The 35,000-square-foot industrial building housed several
businesses, but only the chemical plant and an auto repair firm
were gutted.
   Pacific Intermediates had stocks of several kinds of hazardous
and toxic chemicals, including cyanide, hydrogen, corrosives, and
several materials that react violently with water, said fire Capt.
Tom Kruschke.
   With the mix of chemicals and fire, he said: ``We don't know
exactly what we're coming up with here. It becomes a real witch's
brew for us.''
   More than 130 firefighters were sent to the plant, but they
could not spray water on the chemicals. Besides the fear of
chemical reaction, there was concern that water runoff would
contaminate the Santa Clara River, Kruschke said.
   ``The best thing to do is just let it burn itself out,''
Kruschke said.
   Firefighters said Pacific Intermediates was cited last year for
having larger quantities of chemicals than allowed on its premises.
The citation for violating county ordinances has yet to reach
court, they said.
</TEXT>
