<SECOND>AM-Israel-Elections,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabin Says Elections Possible Within Six Months</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said in an
interview published Tuesday that Israel's proposed elections in the
occupied lands could take place in six months if the United States
can persuade ``whoever needs to agree to elections.''
   Rabin did not mention the U.S. dialogue with the Palestine
Liberation Organization that began in December, but repeated
several times that Washington will have to play to play a major
role in negotiating the elections process, according to the Yediot
Ahronot newspaper.
   It quoted unidentified Israeli officials as saying a U.S. Middle
East envoy was expected to open talks next month.
   The paper quoted Rabin as saying it would be possible to have
Palestinians from outside the occupied lands take part in the
negotiations on the final status of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
He offered no names but mentioned past proposals to include
prominent Palestinian professors in America, it added.
   Rabin, of the center-left Labor Party, said he believed
elections were possible within six months but that Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir thought nine to 12 months would be needed.
   ``I presume that the Americans, who support the idea, will do
all they can to persuade whoever needs to agree to elections,''
Rabin was quoted as saying.
   Shamir, leader of the rival right-wing Likud bloc, said Monday
he stood by his view that the PLO could play no role, even
indirectly.
   The PLO, in a statement issued Monday by its WAFA news agency,
rejected the Shamir plan. It said elections could be held only
under international supervision after Israel withdraws from the
lands it has occupied since capturing them from Jordan and Egypt in
the 1967 Middle East war.
   Hanna Siniora, a prominent Palestinian moderate in Jerusalem,
said Tuesday elections were a possibility even without complete
Israeli withdrawal.
   But he said Israel would have to deal at least indirectly with
the PLO and link the vote to an overall negotiating strategy that
promised a land-for-peace trade.
   Siniora said Israel's suggestions ``are suspended in thin air
without any regard to the future. They are trying to sidestep
talking about land for peace and withdrawal by trying to spotlight
elections.''
