<FIRST>u a AM-EmbattledEducator 2ndLd-Writethru a0740 04-11 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Embattled Educator, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0740,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Schools Chief Took Bumpy Ride From the Start</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, ``Wilson had ...,'' to ADD that Wilson subject
to professional review.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boston School Committee voted 7-6 Tuesday
night to approve a two-year contract keeping embattled Laval S.
Wilson in charge of the nation's oldest school system.
   The decision on the divisive issue was made on the deadline set
by the board. It was announced by committee President Tom O'Reilly
after members met behind closed doors for about two hours.
   Wilson said he was delighted with the vote and looked forward
``to continuing to work for the young people of Boston.''
   He admitted having had some differences with committee members
but said he believed he could work with them productively.
   ``It's not a working situation,'' retorted committee member
Robert Cappucci, a Wilson opponent. ``I don't see how Dr. Wilson
thinks he'll be able to get anything done.
   ``If I were him, I'd see the handwriting on the wall, realize
what I've tried to do hasn't worked and bow out,'' Cappuci said.
``He is not the man for the Boston job.''
   But committee member John Nucci, who supports Wilson, said it
was everyone's duty to try to make the uneasy union work.
   ``I hope they realize that personal vendettas have to be put
aside in the interest of the school system,'' Nucci said.
   Wilson had spent the past two weeks trying to work out a new
contract with three of the school committee members. Under Tuesday
night's action, Wilson is subject to a professional review every
six months, at which time the committee can reconsider his contract.
   The arrival of Wilson, whose four-year contract expires in June,
was heralded as a mature step for Boston. A black man was going to
run schools in a city that erupting in racial violence over federal
court-ordered busing in 1974.
   Only days after Wilson was hired, he asked for and got a $15,000
raise, to make his yearly salary $85,000.
   Since then, white flight to private schools has left the system
mostly black. Of the system's 1972 enrollment of 96,000, 60 percent
was white. Today, there are 59,000 students, 24 percent of them
white.
   Critics of the 53-year-old Chicago native complain he is aloof
and autocratic.
   ``This isn't a racial issue, it's a competence and quality
issue,'' school committee member Peggy Davis-Mullen, who is white
and is one of Wilson's fiercest detractors, said Monday. ``He's a
diligent worker, but his approach isn't meeting the needs of the
children of Boston.''
   ``He lacks the insight and the philosophy that this system needs
to move forward,'' Mrs. Mullen said. ``Although we've had $100
million added to the budget (now $361 million) since Dr. Wilson
arrived, the dropout rate has increased.''
   Supporters praise Wilson's hard work and honesty, saying he
needs more time.
   ``You really can't get anything done changing horses in
midstream. Just changing who it is right now isn't going to change
a thing,'' said Jean McGuire, a former school social worker and one
of four black school committee members.
   In a self-assessment requested by the School Committee, Wilson
gave himself high marks for dedication and for raising math and
reading scores on national standardized tests and for lowering the
dropout rate.
   Wilson says fewer youngsters are quitting school each year. The
school system figures, however, show increasing attrition in class
size between ninth grade and graduation day. The Class of 1983 was
33 percent smaller than when it began; the Class of '87 eroded by
40 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890411-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 0759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:ChildProdigy Adv14   04-11 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Child Prodigy, Adv 14,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, April 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Musical Prodigy Gets Balanced Education In Denver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Diego Alonso is a young Mozart, his parents
don't want to make too much of a fuss about it.
   That's why they whisked the 5-year-old out of their native
Spain, where the press hailed him as a genius and a virtuoso, and
enrolled him in kindergarten at the Mackintosh Academy, a school
for gifted children in Denver.
   ``We wanted him to get a well-rounded education, and be with
children his own age who are more like him,'' said Rosa Alonso
Plaza, 29, Diego's mother.
   She and her husband, Manual, 49, are amateur musicians who set
out to create a musical child. While pregnant they played scales to
the fetus because, she said, ``we love music, and we think music is
very important for the development of the child's mind _ the
creative, abstract mind.''
   Diego began singing scales when he was 6 months old, his parents
say, and at 2 began to read music.
   At 3, he could play simple Bach pieces on the piano.
   Alan Weber, a teacher at the National Conservatory of Music in
Paris who tested Diego, said the 3-year-old showed exceptional
gifts and could listen to music and then play it back by memory.
Weber said Diego should not be schooled with children his own age.
   In February 1988, when he was 4, Diego had an audience before
Queen Sofia of Spain, but declined to play. Instead, he showed the
queen a game he played in which he stands with his back to a piano
and identifies any note that is struck.
   All the attention, however, soon made Diego stop playing for
several months. He was, after all, only 4, and according to his
parents has a stubborn streak.
   ``It was too much pressure,'' his mother said.
   So they brought him to the United States this fall and to the
Mackintosh school. In Denver, he has had to learn English, and he
takes piano lessons and dance classes after school. But he
practices piano only about five minutes a day, and his parents say
they don't want to force him to concentrate on his music any more
than that yet.
   ``We think, little by little, he'll do it,'' Rosa Alonso Plaza
said.
   Carolyn Shaak, Diego's piano teacher in Denver, says he is
exceptional for his age and has perfect pitch, but the child would
love to do anything else but play the piano.
   ``He has put up certain barriers. He wouldn't want to be forced
to sit there,'' she said. ``The potential is there. ... It depends
what he does with it. He certainly has the intelligence.''
   She said his coordination was about average for a 5-year-old.
   Eve Mackintosh, the director of the school, calls the boy a
genius who has caught on quickly in all subjects. She thinks his IQ
is higher than the 139 at which he tested when he was 4.
   Rosa Alonso, a former secretary and a violinist, played scales
and repetitive melodies on the violin at least three times a day at
regular intervals while she was pregnant _ ``at the same beat as
the mother's heart.''
   Manual, who worked for the telephone company in Spain, plays the
piano. He said Diego showed an early fascination with the
instrument, peeking around his father's back to watch him play and
crawling underneath the piano to watch the pedals move.
   The couple filled their home with classical music during the
pregnancy, and when Diego was born they would sing him to sleep
with scales.
   The Alonsos are unemployed in Denver, writing a book about
child-rearing and hoping for an extension of their visa, which runs
out this month. Living on savings, they are not sure how long they
will stay in Denver but would like Diego to finish eighth grade at
Mackintosh before returning to Europe for high school.
   Diego is on a partial scholarship at Mackintosh, and the Alonsos
are hoping a foundation or university will step in and help support
his education.
   But they don't like the child to be bothered by the press, and
asked that reporters and photographers not talk to Diego at school
because that might draw attention to him.
   In a recent music class at the academy, however, Diego drew
attention all by himself. When music teacher David Glenn asked each
child in the kindergarten class to name their favorite musicians,
Diego pulled up two names many of the children could barely
pronounce: Tchaikovsky and Rachmaninoff.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri April 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
