<DOCNO> AP890411-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv12   04-11 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 12,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, April 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Repeat of 1974?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the most abrupt changes ever taken by
those who seek to direct the American economy's course occurred
about 15 years ago under circumstances somewhat similar to those of
today.
   It was during the administration of Gerald Ford, and inflation
was on everyone's mind. The popular patriotic slogan of the day was
``Whip Inflation Now.'' It was printed on lapel buttons and
splashed in advertisements.
   The campaign had an ignominious ending when the facts were
realized _ that the nation was stumbling into recession and that
recession far more than inflation was the big threat to the economy.
   It was not the first time the economic ship of state had been
nearly driven onto the shoals and it wasn't the last either. Almost
all of America's recent presidents have been accused of erratic or
even irresponsible steering.
   In relatively recent history, for example, Herbert Hoover,
Franklin Roosevelt, Dwight Eisenhower, Richard Nixon, Lyndon
Johnson, Jimmy Carter and Ronald Reagan have suffered criticisms
for their tenure at the wheel.
   But nothing quite matches the abrupt realization in 1974 that
the economy was headed to recession while all eyes were on
inflation. And now, some critics contend there could be a repeat of
the scenario in 1989.
   These critics cannot as yet demonstrate their thesis by means of
the popular statistics, which show the economy still has some
forward momentum. But when you're steering a ship as big as the
U.S. economy you never really know.
   When you flip the control buttons or turn the wheel a few
degrees, for example, nothing seems to happen. A big ship doesn't
turn on a dime; it takes time to observe a change. And when change
comes you cannot reverse it quickly.
   In effect, gloomy analysts are saying that maybe too many
buttons have been pushed already, and that while we haven't seen
the effect so far it is bound to show up in the next few months.
Therefore, they say, beware of recession.
   Adding conviction to their fears, or vice versa, is the uncanny
coincidence of the same man being in the control room.
   In 1974, as chairman of the President's Council of Economic
Advisers, Alan Greenspan led the inflation fight. Today, as
chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, he has given inflation
priority over recession.
   Few economists doubt Greenspan's knowledge, or that he is
capable of absorbing wisdom from experience, but one of them, Eric
Heinemann of Ladenburg, Thalmann &amp; Co., a securities firm, offers
this typical cautionary view:
   ``In sum, we think the economy is vulnerable. A slowdown, if not
worse, is in the cards. Alan Greenspan's zeal to Whip Inflation Now
is commendable. But let's hope he doesn't give us a replay of the
crunch of 1974.''
   The question, says Heinemann, is whether Greenspan will get the
mild slowdown he wants, ``or will we go through something more
sinister?''
   In short, will the economy scrape bottom and continue on its
way? Or will it run aground, spring a leak and spill its energy
like the Exxon Valdez?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, April 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
