<DOCNO> AP890411-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-MissouriAbortion-Choice Adv16   04-11 1193</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Missouri Abortion-Choice, Adv 16,1228</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Forces: `I Say God Is on My Side, Too'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Suggested for use with AM-Missouri Abortion-Anti, b0566.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   On April 26, the U.S. Supreme Court will convene
for a 60-minute hearing on one of America's most polarizing issues
_ abortion. The debate centers on a Missouri law that restricts
abortion and declares that human life begins at conception. The two
sides in this Missouri case represent in microcosm the deeply
divided sentiments felt across the country. In two stories, part of
an intermittent series on abortion issues, The Associated Press
profiles key players in this Missouri case: the pro-choice
advocates and the clinic at the heart of the dispute, and the
leader of the anti-abortion forces, a man committed to a fight he
sees as good vs. evil.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By SHARON COHEN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   B.J. Isaacson-Jones has days when she knows
that dressing in red will provoke the ugly taunts again.
   ``B.J., you're wearing red,'' scream the protesters sometimes
gathered outside her office. ``Does that match the blood on your
hands?''
   The taunts have taken a toll on the director of Reproductive
Health Services, the abortion clinic at the heart of an emotional
and explosive debate before the U.S. Supreme Court.
   ``It's not unusual for me to close my office door and sob,'' she
said. ``I'm proud of the way I live my life. It's hard when you're
standing close to people and you can feel the hatred. I don't hate
people.''
   The intense feelings are likely to grow even stronger as April
26 draws nearer, the day the Supreme Court hears arguments over a
Missouri statute that could chip away or overturn the 1973 ruling
that legalized abortion.
   For anti-abortion advocates who've been waiting and working for
this day for 16 years, it's a time of great hope. But for
pro-choice supporters, just as eager to prevent this moment, it's a
time of high anxiety.
   ``We are gravely concerned about this case,'' said
Isaacson-Jones, whose non-profit clinic is the largest in the
Midwest. ``What's at stake here is women's lives. It's that
complicated and that simple.''
   Missouri's pro-choice forces have grown from a small underground
movement to a group of determined activists challenging a state
whose Legislature has passed anti-abortion measures by 5-1
majorities.
   Two veteran advocates are key players in this case: Frank
Susman, a lawyer who will be arguing his fifth Missouri abortion
case before the high court, and Judith Widdicombe, a former nurse
at a Roman Catholic hospital and the founder of the clinic.
   Together, with Isaacson-Jones, they've shared not only their
convictions, but also death threats, pickets at home or outside the
clinic, obscene phone calls and harassment of their families.
   Susman, who represents the clinic, says someone once placed a
bogus newspaper ad saying his house was for sale. A picket sued him
for $250,000, claiming he'd assaulted her as he escorted a woman
into another clinic where protesters were gathered. A jury cleared
him.
   Reproductive Health is only one of seven plaintiffs _ Planned
Parenthood of Greater Kansas City is another _ but it has been the
target of some of the most vicious attacks. Once, protesters stood
on clinic desks and jumped through a reception window.
   In 1986, five gallons of gas were poured under the waiting room
door and ignited. The blaze caused more than $100,000 damage. No
one was arrested.
   ``This is a very violent movement,'' said Widdicombe, now a
consultant for Voters For Choice in Washington, D.C. ``I think it
has become a rapidly escalating war in the last 10 years.''
   Abortion opponents in Missouri, however, insist they repudiate
violence and say verbal harassment is the wrong way to sway hearts
and minds.
   ``If I have a sincere desire to point out the error of their
ways, I'm not going to be able to accomplish that by screaming and
hollering at them,'' said Sam Lee, a Missouri anti-abortion leader.
   The name-calling and pickets do prompt soul-searching.
   ``I stand in the shower the next morning and go over everything
that was said,'' said Isaacson-Jones, who started at the clinic as
a volunteer. ``I think, could they possibly be right? I go back
stronger in my conviction. I will examine that again. I know I
shall.
   ``But what I return to are the faces of the women I see,'' she
added. ``I always, always understand the reason why a woman has
chosen to terminate her pregnancy. I may not like the reasons she's
waited so long. ...
   ``The antis say God's on their side,'' she said. ``I say God's
on my side as well.''
   Isaacson-Jones' support of abortion rights stems from her high
school days in the '60s when she saw pregnant classmates shunned
and forced to drop out of school. ``I realized the incredible
impact of one sexual experience on the rest of a woman and her
family's life,'' she said.
   Today, she runs a clinic with 64 staff members, 35 volunteers
and two offices. It counsels 15,000 women each year; more than
8,500 choose abortion. The women come from eight states: Illinois,
Indiana, Iowa, Kentucky, Missouri, Oklahoma, Tennessee and Texas;
30 percent are poor.
   It's a long way from the late '50s, when Widdicombe, then a
nurse, saw women disfigured trying to abort themselves, sometimes
with lye.
   She later worked at a Catholic hospital, caring for new mothers
in the labor and delivery section, then spending her free time
arranging legal and illegal abortions _ sometimes as far away as
Puerto Rico and Mexico.
   ``The hospital found that totally incongruent,'' Widdicombe
said. She resigned.
   It was a scary time, too. ``There was a level of paranoia,
absolutely,'' Widdicombe said. ``I did think about what it would be
like to go to jail.''
   Susman provided legal advice at the time. He now represents
about 20 abortion clinics nationwide on a part-time basis,
estimating reproductive issues account for about 10 percent of his
work.
   In 1973, Widdicombe opened the clinic. Three hundred protesters
marched outside.
   ``I though we'd just provide a clinic and work ourselves out of
business,'' she said. ``It was pretty naive. We really felt we
would decrease the need for abortion'' with education and research.
   Pro-choice leaders say they've been far less successful in
organizing than their opposition. They also claim abortion foes
misrepresent their cause.
   ``We have allowed this small group to define pro-choice as
pro-abortion,'' said Isaacson-Jones. ``Think about the vivid
pictures the anti-abortion people (display). Who's going to argue
with that? They have signs ... `Money, Blood, Murder' ... That's
not the reality of choice.''
   Unlike her opponents, Isaacson-Jones says she isn't interested
in converting anyone.
   ``I really don't want to change their minds,'' she said. ``I
wish they'd leave us alone and allow us to work in dignity.''
   Susman expresses optimism about this case: ``I do not believe
the court is prepared to turn back the clock 16 years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sharon Cohen is the AP Midwest regional
reporter, based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
