<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 0122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights    04-11 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, </SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' striking unions reached 5-year
agreements with Peter V. Ueberroth that apparently resulted in
changes to Ueberroth's agreement to buy the airline from parent
Texas Air Corp., sources said.
   After four days of almost continuous bargaining, Ueberroth's
group and the three striking unions, representing the Machinists,
pilots and flight attendants, struck their deals at about 6 a.m.
Monday in Washington.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Union Co., a privately owned
Northeast-based supermarket chain, will be acquired by a
partnership of investment banks in a deal worth about $1.2 billion,
the buyers said.
   The acquisition announced Monday would mark the latest big
supermarket takeover by Wall Street firms, which are attracted to
the business because it is considered largely recession-proof and
generates large quantities of cash.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration tried to squelch an
effort by members of the House Banking Committee to weaken the
administration's savings and loan reform plan by diluting a
proposal to toughen capital standards.
   A senior Treasury Department official said Monday the
committee's proposed capital rule ``has the cosmetic appearance of
going in the right direction'' but would ``undermine the
effectiveness of the capital discipline.''
   In reply, a committee aide, also speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the proposal is in some ways tougher, although a
greater number of solvent S&amp;Ls would be able to meet it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state banking commissioner said it could take
up to 18 months _ three times the normal period _ to review NCNB
Inc.'s bid to acquire Citizens &amp; Southern Corp.
   C&amp;S officials said Monday the long wait may kill the takeover
attempt, but NCNB said it feels there are no legal or regulatory
impediments to the merger.
   The C&amp;S board last week rejected a $2.4 billion stock exchange
offer that NCNB said would create the nation's sixth-largest
banking company.
