<FIRST>r f PM-BoeingOrders     04-11 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Orders,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean, Mideast Airlines Order Boeing Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Asiana Airlines will spend about $1 billion to
buy nine Boeing Co. jetliners and take options on seven more
because the new airline doesn't want to risk its reputation on
older planes, an Asiana executive said.
   In a separate announcement Monday, Gulf Air of Bahrain said it
will spend $1 billion over the next five years to buy six Boeing
767s and 12 Airbus Industrie A-320s.
   The combined value of the Asiana and Gulf Air orders to Boeing
would be about $1.4 billion.
   S.Y. Park, chairman of Kumho Business Group, Asiana's parent
company, said that in addition to wanting new planes, it chose
Boeing was because the Seattle-based plane builder took the new
airline seriously.
   Asiana, based in Seoul, Korea, began operations within that
country on Dec. 23. It said it will use its new jets to expand to
other Asian markets and eventually to North America and Europe.
   ``In the short term, we could have saved a few dollars by buying
or leasing older planes,'' Park said. ``However, a new airline has
enough problems establishing its market base without the burden of
heavy maintenance responsibilities and the uncertainty of whether
older planes will perform reliably.''
   Asiana ordered five 737-400s and took options for another five.
It also signed letters of intent to order two 747-400 jumbo jets
and take options for two more, and to convert two previous options
for widebody 767-300s to firm orders.
   Boeing normally doesn't announce letters of intent, said Boeing
Commercial Airplanes spokesman Randy Harrison, but Asiana had made
it clear it intended to buy the planes.
   Harrison described a letter of intent as just short of an order,
with the major difference being no money is paid to begin
construction.
   Asiana began its Korean service Dec. 23 with six 737-400s leased
from GPA Group Ltd.
   Deliveries of Asiana's new planes will begin in July 1992.
   Gulf Air spokesman Abdullah Abdel-Karim said it was ordering its
new planes on an optional basis, allowing the airline to drop the
order without liability to compensate the manufacturer.
   Gulf Air is owned by the governments of Bahrain, Qatar, Oman and
Abu Dhabi. The announcement came one day after Gulf Air's board met
in the Qatari capital of Doha.
   Abdel-Karim said the 18 jets will be delivered between 1990 and
1994. Gulf Air is currently spending $260 million to lease four
Boeing 767-300s as part of a modernization program.
   Abdel-Karim said that by June the airline will have nine
Lockheed L-1011 Tri-Stars, eight Boeing 737s and six Boeing
767-300s. The fleet will increase to 40 to 42 aircraft by 1994, he
added.
   Not counting the Gulf Air planes, Boeing has announced orders
for 110 jetliners worth $8.7 billion this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890411-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 0127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ford-Recall     04-11 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford-Recall,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Recalls 340,000 Trucks and Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has recalled more than
340,000 cars and trucks for safety-related and other problems.
   The company said Monday it was asking owners of 26,000 1988-89
F-Super Duty trucks and truck chassis to return the vehicles
because of front-end suspension problems that could cause shaking
and loss of steering control.
   Ford said a bolt attaching the front axle track bar bracket to
the front cross-member may loosen. The company said it was aware of
about 120 cases of front-end ``shimmy,'' but no injuries because of
it.
   The company also said 750 of its 1989 Lincoln Continental cars
were being recalled to tighten a bolt in a rear seat-belt
attachment. Those cars were assembled between late November and
early December last year.
   In a non-safety-related matter, Ford said it was asking 302,000
owners if some 1988 Lincoln Continentals, Mercury Sables and Ford
Taurus cars and some F-Series trucks and Econoline vans to return
their vehicles for alternator inspections.
   The company said a problem with an epoxy bond could cause
electrical system problems.
   Ford also said it would provide coverage for about 12,500
1985-86 Merkur XR4Ti cars with leather interiors. The upholstery
may harden, crack or discolor and the seams may fail, the company
said.
   Owners of all vehicles involved in the four announcements will
have repairs performed free of charge.
</TEXT>
