<DOCNO> AP890411-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 0127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BurgerKing     04-11 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burger King,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burger King Divides Distron Into Supply, Distribution Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burger King has announced it will split its
procurement and distribution arm, Distron, into separate entities
as part of a previously announced restructuring of the fast-food
chain.
   ``This reorganization is the latest step in our restructuring of
the entire Burger King operation to make the company more
competitive and more focused on the customer,'' Ian Martin,
chairman of Burger King Corp., said Monday.
   Distron will be replaced by Burger King Supply Management and
Burger King Distribution Services.
   The supply management operation will be responsible for buying
corporate restaurant food and supplies at the local and national
levels. Distribution services will deliver food and supplies to
restaurants.
   British conglomerate Grand Metropolitan PLC bought Burger King
and its parent Pillsbury Co. in January after a tough takeover
battle.
   ``Before we acquired Pillsbury and Burger King, our external
analysis of Distron indicated that it would be advisable to sell
the division, because it appeared to hinder the Burger King
system,'' Martin said.
   ``However, now that we have acquired the company and performed
our own in-depth analysis, we have concluded that a reorganized
internal procurement and distribution system will be a tremendous
asset to Burger King,'' he added.
   According to the company, the reorganization will allow it to
consolidate its buying and maximize purchasing power for a more
consistent product.
   Thomas C. Highland will serve as president of Burger King
Distribution Services. He had been president of Distron since June
1988.
   The supply management department will be headed by senior vice
president Christopher Dams. He comes to the Miami-based chain from
Grand Metropolitan Retailing Ltd., where he was retail trading
director.
   Both will report to Barry J. Gibbons, Burger King chief
executive officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
