<SECOND>PM-Formica Offer,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Formica Corp. Rejects $244 Million Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Formica Corp. says further discussions are
expected between a special committee of the board of directors and
parties interested in acquiring the laminated products company.
   However, Formica announced Monday that it rejected a revised
$243 million takeover offer from a management-led group, one of
several offers made for the company in recent months.
   Formica officials declined to elaborate on the denial of FM
Acquisition Corp.'s bid, voted on by a special committee of the
board of directors.
   According to the $18.75-per-share offer, additional financing
for the offer would have been provided by an industrial corporation
that signed a confidential agreement with Formica.
   Formica, which makes laminated products used in kitchen
countertops and tables, announced two weeks ago that it received a
$256 million bid, but would not identify the bidder.
   At that time, Formica also said its committee of independent
directors instructed Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. to begin
negotiations with the company.
   Last fall, Malcolm Glazer, a Rochester, N.Y., businessman,
offered $20 a share in cash and securities for Formica and was
rebuffed. After the management group announced its offer, Glazer
said he was considering a new bid.
   It was not known if the $256 million bid came from Glazer.
   Shearson also is continuing discussions with six other
interested third parties, but Formica spokesman Robert Way would
not comment Monday beyond the contents of the news release.
   FM Acquisition previously offered $18 a share for Formica.
Formica has said its directors approved a definitive merger with
FM, but they also told Shearson to see if others might be
interested in bidding.
   Formica stock closed at $19.75 a share Monday, down from
Friday's closing price of $20.50 a share in New York Stock Exchange
composite trading.
</TEXT>
