<FIRST>r f PM-Gulf&amp;Western Bjt   04-11 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf &amp; Western, Bjt,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>G&amp;W's Plan To Sell Financial Unit Should Produce Cash Hoard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf &amp; Western Inc. should be able to get $2.5
billion or more for its giant consumer finance subsidiary that
could be used to buy more media and entertainment properties or
repurchase stock, analysts say.
   Gulf &amp; Western stock rose Monday following its weekend
disclosure that it plans to sell The Associates, the nation's
third-largest consumer finance company, and concentrate on its
entertainment and publishing businesses.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Gulf &amp; Western rose
$2.37{ a share to $51.87{.
   Some analysts predicted Chairman Martin S. Davis would use the
huge cash hoard to make acquisitions in the media and entertainment
business, but others said he may use the money to accelerate the
company's stock repurchase plan that has gobbled up more than 45
million shares since 1983.
   ``I'm taking the contrarian view here _ I'm not convinced there
are attractive assets available at prices they would be willing to
pay,'' said Jeffrey Logsdon, an entertainment industry analyst for
the investment firm Crowell, Weedon &amp; Co. in Los Angeles.
   He said he expects Gulf &amp; Western could get $3 billion to $4
billion for The Associates and use the proceeds for stock
repurchases.
   But Carol Neves, who follows Gulf &amp; Western for Merrill Lynch
Research in New York, said a cash-rich Gulf &amp; Western could be
vulnerable to a takeover.
   ``If they don't know what they are going to do with the cash,
they may have put themselves in play,'' she said.
   Sony Corp., the Japanese electronics giant, already has
indicated interest in buying a U.S. entertainment company.
   Davis was unavailable Monday to comment on what he planned to do
with the proceeds of the sale. The company said in Sunday's
announcement that sale proceeds would be used to expand the
company's communications operations globally through product
development and distribution as well as acquisitions and
investments.
   The sale of The Associates would leave the company with a
Paramount Pictures operation that includes such successful movie
titles as ``Beverly Hills Cop,'' ``Fatal Attraction'' and
```Crocodile' Dundee'' and a TV library with more than 2,000
episodes of network shows such as ``Family Ties'' and ``Cheers.''
   Gulf &amp; Western also is a major force in consumer and textbook
publishing through its Simon &amp; Schuster-Prentice Hall division. It
also has interests in cable programming, theaters and sports.
   Some analysts said Davis is under no immediate pressure to
outline acquisition plans. They said finding a buyer for The
Associates and closing the deal could take months.
   They said Gulf &amp; Western already is a big enough force in
entertainment and the media that its place among the global media
giants is assured.
   But the announcement appeared to stir renewed interest in
several media and entertainment companies mentioned recently in
takeover speculation.
   For instance, Tribune Co. was up $1.25 a share to $44.75, Time
Inc. rose $1.87{ to $115.37{, CBS Inc. rose $4.12{ to $182.62{ and
MCA Inc. rose 62{ cents to $56.25.
   Since he became chairman of Gulf &amp; Western in 1983, Davis has
narrowed the scope of the once far-flung conglomerate. He sold
businesses ranging from cigarmaking and chemicals to racetracks
while making selective acquisitions in publishing, motion picture
houses and cable television.
   J. Kendrick Noble, a media analyst for PaineWebber Inc., said
the proposal to sell the financial unit may help Davis boost the
stock price by simply focusing the investment community's view of
the company.
   Gulf &amp; Western earned $384.7 million, or $3.21 a share, on
revenue of $5.1 billion in 1988.
   The consumer finance operations accounted for 46 percent of its
operating income and 40 percent of its revenue last year.
Entertainment accounted for 31 percent of operating income and 37
percent of revenue, while publishing and information services
contributed 23 percent of operating income and revenue.
</TEXT>
