<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 0731EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     04-11 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Inches Up, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rebounded
sharply today while the dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
after remarks by Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita about his links to
a stock scandal reassured Japanese investors, dealers said.
   The dollar closed at 132.62 yen, up 0.09 yen from the previous
day's 132.53-yen finish. It opened at 132.87 yen and ranged between
132.60 yen and 132.89 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which fell 186.03 points on
Monday, shot up today by 250.56 points, or 0.76 percent, closing at
33,249.58.
   ``Early morning trading started amid a cautious mood concerning
what Prime Minister Takeshita was going to say before Parliament,''
said Kenji Ishizuka with Daiwa Securities in Tokyo.
   ``But the index started to rise as participants discovered
Takeshita said nothing worse than what had already been
disclosed,'' he added.
   Volume traded on the first section in the first hour was only
200 million shares, but activity quickened later, and the full
day's estimated volume was 1.1 billion shares, Ishizuka said.
   Addressing Parliament Tuesday morning, Takeshita said he had
received 130 million yen (about $1 million) in donations from
Recruit Co., the firm at the heart of a major stock-profiteering
and bribery scandal.
   But he denied taking bribes and continued to reject opposition
calls for his resignation.
   Investors were more or less reassured as Takeshita said nothing
new, while agreeing to give a parliamentary committee records of
donations and stock profits he and his office have received,
Ishizuka said.
   Opposition parties have halted parliamentary proceedings,
demanding a full accounting of ruling Liberal Democratic Party
politicians' involvement in the scandal.
   In currency dealings, there was some yen buying as exchange
market participants also were reassured by Takeshita's remarks,
said a dealer with Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   He said the exchange rate was likely to change little in the
next few days as the market awaits the release of major indicators
for the U.S. economy later this week.
   The United States is to announce the nation's trade figures for
February and wholesale price index for March.
</TEXT>
