<FIRST>r f PM-HollyFarms     04-11 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holly Farms,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merger Worth $60 A Share To Holly Farms Stockholders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. stockholders would get
1.875 shares of ConAgra Inc. stock for each of their Holly Farms
shares if a proposed merger between the two firms goes through, the
companies announced.
   The exchange agreed upon Monday would be worth $60 a share to
Holly Farms stockholders, or a total of $1.08 billion for the
company, based on Monday's closing market prices.
   In an attempt to fend off a buyout by rival poultry producer
Tyson Foods Inc. of Springdale, Ark., Holly Farms announced plans
last November to merge with with ConAgra.
   The tentative stock exchange rate was set then at between 1.875
and 2 shares of ConAgra stock for each Holly Farms share traded.
The exchange rate was settled in anticipation of meetings Friday
during which Holly Farms and ConAgra shareholders will vote on the
merger proposal.
   Tyson is offering Holly Farms stockholders $63.50 a share in
cash, or a total of $1.1 billion, but Holly Farms managers are
urging shareholders to reject it.
   Holly Farms president R. Lee Taylor II said the ConAgra proposal
would be a better deal for Holly Farms shareholders.
   ``It gives stockholders an equity interest in a company that
should be strategically the best performing food company in the
United States,'' he said.
   Tyson has turned to full-page newspaper advertisements to urge
Holly Farms employees who are stockholders to reject the ConAgra
merger.
   In advertisements published Sunday in editions of The Commercial
Appeal at Memphis, the Winston-Salem Journal in North Carolina, and
The Des Moines Register, Tyson touted its $63.50-a-share offer and
criticized the proposed stock-for-stock offer by the Omaha-based
ConAgra.
</TEXT>
