<FIRST>r f BC-Scott-Timber     04-11 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scott-Timber,0167</SECOND>
<UNK>Scott Paper Sells Northwest Timberlands</UNK>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scott Paper Co. announced Tuesday it will
sell 194,000 acres of timberlands in western Washington to Crown
Pacific Ltd. for about $230 million.
   Scott first announced plans to sell its northwest timberlands in
1983, and the agreement with Crown represents all but about 16,000
acres of the land to be sold.
   ``As we indicated in 1983, our northwest timberlands are best
suited for producing lumber and building materials products which
are not strategic directions for Scott,'' Scott chairman Philip E.
Lippincott said.
   Pulp and paper manufacturing at Scott's Everett, Wash. mill,
which typically receives only a small amount of its wood fiber from
the northwest timberlands, will not be affected.
   The agreement calls for Crown Pacific, of Portland, Ore., to
supply wood fiber to the mill from the purchased land.
   The sale, which is subject to approval by Scott's board of
directors, is expected to be completed this summer.
</TEXT>
