<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-11 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Gain On Report Of Declining Crop Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices moved moderately higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade on signs of a deteriorating
winter wheat crop. Corn and soybean futures were narrowly mixed.
   In its weekly report on crop conditions, released Monday after
the markets closed, the Agriculture Department found a net decline
in the condition of the winter wheat crop during the week ended
Sunday.
   The finding was somewhat surprising since a recent increase in
precipitation in some key wheat-growing areas had led many traders
to expect an overall improvement in the crop.
   Corn futures prices were slightly lower in early trading, due in
part to slack export demand.
   Slow foreign demand also limited early gains in the soybean
market, but higher cash prices and strengthening chart signals
provided a generally bullish tone.
   Cautious trading was expected ahead of the USDA's monthly grain
supply-and-demand report, which was due out after the close today.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 5} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.97{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to \ cent higher with May at $2.66\ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to } cent lower with May at $1.86{ a bushel; soybeans
were unchanged to 1 cent higher with May at $7.20 a bushel.
   Livestock futures were mixed while pork bellies were slightly
lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent to .47 cent lower with April at 77.70
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .23 cent higher with
April at 77.30 cents a pound; hogs were .07 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with April at 39.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.17 cent to .30 cent lower with May at 33.90 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower on Monday while pork futures
were mixed.
</TEXT>
