<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Ramada-Pritzkers     04-11 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ramada-Pritzkers,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pritzkers Sell Part of Ramada Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The billionare Pritzker family said today it has
cut its stake in Ramada Inc. to 4.8 percent from 7.2 percent,
indicating the Arizona-based hotelier has won a fight to remain
independent.
   HCC Corp., a Chicago-based company headed by Jay A. Pritzker,
said in an April 5 filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission it had sold a total of 959,100 shares of Ramada stock
from March 16 through April 5 at an average price of $11.29 a share.
   Ramada stock was trading at $11.62{ in early New York Stock
Exchange trading today.
   Pritzker would not comment on the reasons for the stock sale,
said his secretary, Rhonda Scheiss.
   Last September, Ramada rejected HCC's $10-a-share offer for all
of the company's stock and embarked on a corporate restructuring
that included the sale of its 825 hotels.
   Ramada plans to retain its hotel-casino operations in New Jersey
and Nevada and is still seeking a buyer for its hotels, said
spokesman Joe Cole from company headquarters in Phoenix, Ariz.
   Cole said Ramada had heard nothing from the Pritzkers since
October, ``so I don't think we have any comment on what they've
just done.''
</TEXT>
