<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Philippines-Westinghouse     04-11 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Westinghouse,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Secretary Says Settlement Possible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippines could drop a lawsuit
against Westinghouse Electric Corp. over an allegedly defective
nuclear power plant if the U.S. company helps provide alternate
power, an official said Tuesday.
   The government of President Corazon Aquino claims the
620-megawatt plant rests on an earthquake fault and has structural
defects.
   ``Of course we are seeking recovery of damages, but damages ...
can be paid in services and facilities,'' Justice Secretary Sedfrey
Ordonez said in a television interview.
   The $2.3 billion plant on the Bataan peninsula, 60 miles west of
Manila, was completed in 1985 several months before President
Ferdinand Marcos was driven into exile. The plant was never started.
   The Aquino government sued Westinghouse, its subsidiary
Westinghouse International Projects Inc., and contractors Burns and
Roe Enterprises Inc., in U.S. District Court in Newark, N.J., last
December.
   The Philippines government also accused Westinghouse of bribing
Marcos to win the contract to build the plant. The suit is intended
to cancel the contract and recover the money spent on the plant. It
also seeks unspecified damages.
   Westinghouse has denied the bribery charges and claims the plant
is safe.
   Ordonez said an out-of-court settlement was ``not out of the
picture.''
   ``Our concern now is to develop alternate sources of energy,''
he said. ``If that can be met, the money aspect can be minimized.
What is important is that we get something for the same value which
would help us solve our power needs.''
   A Justice Department source said the remarks were hypothetical.
Philippine and Westinghouse officials held lengthy negotiations
before the decision to file the suit.
   Ordonez was interviewed after Salvador Laurel, Mrs. Aquino's
estranged vice president, called on the administration to operate
the plant because of the country's power shortage.
   Ordonez and Mrs. Aquino said they did not understand Laurel's
position because the vice president voted with the cabinet in 1986
to close the plant. Laurel quit as foreign secretary in 1987 and
joined the political opposition last year.
   ``According to our lawyers, we have sufficient evidence in the
matter of proving that we got a raw deal from Westinghouse,'' Mrs.
Aquino said Monday.
   Robert F. Pugliese, a Westinghouse executive vice president,
said in a statement released in Pittsburgh that the company was
willing ``to explore how we can help bring the Philippine nuclear
power plant into service.''
   ``We are confident we built a safe plant,'' he said. ``Prior to
its mothballing by the Philippines government, it had passed every
official inspection of its readiness to load, fuel and begin
startup testing.''
   In Newark, attorneys for the Philippine government asked U.S.
District Judge Dickinson R. Debevoise to have the case heard in
federal court. Westinghouse asked the judge to send the case to
arbitration before the International Chamber of Commerce in Geneva,
Switzerland.
   Philippines' attorney Mark Augenblick said a contract clause
prescribing arbitration of disputes is invalid because the
state-run National Power Corp. was forced to sign the agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
