<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1425EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ConstructionOutlook     04-11 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Construction Outlook,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Contracting To Decrease In 1989, Forecast Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction contracting will fall about 3
percent in 1989, pulled down by sharp drops in office and other
commercial instruction, a forecast released Tuesday says.
   A glut of commercial space on the market and rising interest
rates are the main reasons for the projected decline, according to
the Dodge-Sweet's Construction Outlook by McGraw-Hill Information
Systems Co.
   Total construction contracting is expected to fall to $247.4
billion from $255.2 billion, according to the forecast, which is an
update from the original 1989 outlook released last October.
   Among particular segments, McGraw-Hill projected a 7 percent
drop in non-residential construction contracting, a 2 percent drop
in residential construction contracting, and a 2 percent increase
in non-building construction, such as construction for
transportation, environment and utilities.
</TEXT>
