<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     04-11 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0372</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were trading near session highs in
relatively slim volume as many market participants remained on the
sidelines awaitng new economic data later in the week.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 11.36 to 2,313.23
at 2 p.m. EST. An hour earlier, the blue-chip indicator was up
13.75.
   Advancing issues outpaced decliners by almost 2 to 1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 872 issues up, 463 down and 564 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 106.33 million shares, slightly
ahead of Monday's session, when the market had recorded one of the
slowest days of the year.
   Analysts said speculative buying helped push the market higher,
with takeovers still a big concern. In the afternoon session, a few
investors began venturing out as well.
   ``There is some anticipatory nibbling with people watching the
market to see if they can get enough courage to do some bying,''
said Michael Metz, vice president of Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   But many institutional players remained noncommittal ahead of
the economic data due out later in the week that could give them a
better idea of the economy's direction.
   The employment report last Friday provided mixed signals about
the economy. Although the jobless rate slid to 5 percent, fewer
than 100,000 new jobs were created.
   ``The market is going to languish in volume with little
institutional participation until then,'' said Philip Puccio,
senior vice president at Dillon, Read &amp; Co.
   The government is scheduled to report on producer prices,
merchandise trade, retail sales and industrial production.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
holding at 0.73 at 167.62.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
1.63 at 333.03.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Campbell Soup was up
1| to 39~ amid speculation of a possible sale of the Dorrance
family's majority stake, analysts said.
   Oil stocks were strong with Chevron up ] at 53], Atlantic
Richfield up \ at 89} and Pennzoil up { to 85. However, Exxon was
down ] at 41|.
