<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Coffee     04-11 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Coffee,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Export Quota Cut to Shore Up Falling Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Coffee Organization cut its
global export quota by 351,000 bags Tuesday to shore up falling
prices.
   The cut in the October 1988-September 1989 quota was triggered
automatically by a fall in the average coffee price below $1.15 a
pound. One bag equals 132 pounds.
   The coffee organization's 15-day composite indicator for Monday,
calculated on Tuesday, dropped to $1.1498 from $1.1523 on Friday.
   The organization, made up of coffee producer and consumer
nations, has set a target price for coffee of $1.20-$1.40.
   In February, it twice cut the global export quota when the
average price fell below $1.20 a pound.
   The three cuts affect only the quotas of countries producing the
poorer grade robusta beans, principally the Ivory Coast, Uganda and
Indonesia. The organization wants to boost supplies of the prized
arabica beans grown throughout Latin America.
   Only if the price of arabica falls from its current level of
$1.40 a pound to under $1.30 will arabica producers face a
reduction in their export quotas.
   The robusta producers affected by Tuesday's cut, with the size
of the reduction in parentheses, are Cameroon (38,500 bags),
Indonesia (78,000), Ivory Coast (101,500), Madagascar (20,000),
Philippines (13,000), Uganda (67,000) and Zaire (33,000).
</TEXT>
