<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-11 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Advance On Crop-Damage Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weather-damage fears drove wheat futures prices
to a moderately higher close Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
Other grain and soybean futures finished narrowly mixed.
   The gain in wheat prices was partly a reaction to the
Agriculture Department's weekly report issued after the close
Monday showing a net decline in the condition of the winter wheat
crop for the week ending Sunday.
   Dry conditions in the Great Plains were cited for the
deterioration, and the cold weather of the past three days added to
traders' crop-damage fears.
   ``The weather's a little nippy, to put it mildly, in some areas,
slowing development of wheat by about two weeks,'' said Katharina
Zimmer, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
   She said other buying was prompted by perceptions that the steep
decline in wheat prices over the past two weeks was not entirely
warranted.
   Corn and soybean futures closed mixed in cautious trading ahead
of the USDA's monthly supply-and-demand report.
   In that report, the USDA revised upward its estimates for
1988-89 corn and wheat ending stocks but let stand its estimate for
1988-89 soybean ending stocks.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 6 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.00{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
lower to { cent higher with May at $2.65\ a bushel; oats were 1\
cents to 3} cents lower with May at $1.83\ a bushel; soybeans were
2{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with May at $7.21 a bushel.
</TEXT>
