<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Banks     04-11 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Banks,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>NCNB Reports Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Corp., which recently emerged as an unwelcome bidder for
the Atlanta-based bank holding company Citizens and Southern Corp.,
reported Tuesday that its first-quarter profit jumped 8 percent
over a year ago.
   Net income for the three months ended March 31 totaled $75.8
million, or 82 cents a share, compared with earnings of $70.02
million, or 83 cents per share, in 1988.
   Chairman Hugh McColl attributed the improvement partly to a rise
in net interest income and strong loan growth.
   The results included $10.8 million in earnings contributions
from NCNB Texas, formerly First RepublicBank Corp. of Dallas, of
which NCNB owns a 20 percent stake. They also included $5 million
in dividends on convertible preferred stock issued to fund the
investment.
   Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB took over the management of the First
RepublicBank banks last year after getting financial assistance
from the government.
   NCNB grabbed the attention of the banking industry earlier this
month by making an unsolicited $2.4 billion stock-swap buyout for
Citizens. The company has rejected the bid as inadequate and urged
NCNB to withdraw it.
   The combination of the two banks would result in a bank with
assets of around $75 billion, placing it firmly in the top 10 among
the nation's bank holding companies.
</TEXT>
