<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-11 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gasoline Prices Up Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline futures surged in hectic trading
Tuesday, reflecting continued seasonal demand and concern that a
California refinery fire might sharply curtail production.
   Prices for unleaded gasoline futures traded on the New York
Mercantile Exchange had jumped more than 3 cents a gallon at one
point Tuesday, before profit-taking helped push the closing price
down to a gain of just under 2 cents.
   Crude prices also rose slightly, while wholesale home heating
oil declined.
   Bob Baker, an energy analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., attributed the uproar in the gasoline pits to news of a fire
at Chevron Oil Co.'s busy Richmond, Calif., refinery.
   He said traders speculated that gasoline and jet fuel production
there could be curtailed by up to 25 percent as a result of the
blaze.
   ``The markets are a bit distrustful of supply capabilities
lately anyway,'' said Baker.
   Oil prices, particularly gasoline, have gotten a boost in recent
weeks from the massive Exxon oil tanker spill off the coast of
Alaska. Strong seasonal demand and new summer octane regulations
that are likely to strain refinery capacity gave the market its
initial strength.
   On the New York Merc, the May contract for unleaded gasoline
jumped 1.71 cents to settle Tuesday at 69 cents a gallon. The
contract had risen 2.34 cents on Monday.
   The May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, closed 4 cents higher at $20.63 a barrel,
after gaining 57 cents on Monday.
   May wholesale heating oil, which rose 1.85 cents Monday, fell
0.22 cent to 53.23 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
