<HEAD>Swiss Judge Lifts Order Blocking RJR Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge in Switzerland has lifted a temporary
restraining order that could have blocked a portion of the
acquisition of RJR Nabisco Inc. by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   Polly Howes, a spokeswoman for RJR Nabisco at the food and
tobacco company's headquarters in Atlanta, on Tuesday confirmed the
decision by Swiss Judge Gorg Zogg in Basel.
   Ms. Howes said the matter was handled entirely overseas and she
could not provide further deatails.
   The judge issued the temporary restraining order March 20 in
response to a lawsuit filed by three bondholders in Switzerland who
contended that the $25 billion buyout of RJR Nabisco last year
diminished the value of their holdings.
   The judge's order was directed at the merger as it pertained to
the assets of certain Swiss subsidiaries of RJR Nabisco. The
company argued during a hearing March 28 there was no basis for the
order, according to an RJR Nabisco proxy statement.
   A Forsyth County, N.C., judge last week also issued a temporary
restraining order blocking the KKR-RJR Nabisco merger that stemmed
from the Swiss suit.
   At the time, County District Judge James Harrill Jr. set an
April 17 hearing on a motion by Swiss investors to block the
merger. It was not immediately clear what effect the Swiss judge's
decision would have on the case in North Carolina.
   But Ms. Howes said neither case was expected to delay the
closing of the merger.
   At least three other U.S. lawsuits are pending, claiming that
the merger reduced the value of RJR Nabisco bonds.
