<FIRST>u f AM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru f0235 04-11 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0235,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats' Minimum Wage Plan Moves Ahead After Rejection of Bush
Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 5 grafs to raise reference to $4.55 level, insert
reax from Mrs. Dole; PICKS UP graf 4 pvs, `More amendments...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate rejected President Bush's minimum
wage plan Tuesday and moved closer to confronting him with
legislation raising the hourly figure to $4.55, which he repeatedly
has promised to veto.
   The Senate, on a 61-39 vote largely along party lines, backed an
amendment to legislation sponsored by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., that brought the measure essentially in line with a
House-passed bill that would boost the minimum wage to $4.55 by
October 1991.
   Rejected, by 58-41, was Bush's proposal to increase the minimum
wage by 30 cents a year from the current $3.35 an hour to $4.25 in
January 1992. It was the second time Bush's proposal was defeated
in Congress; the House rejected it three weeks ago.
   The Senate's action brought a quick response from the Bush
administration.
   ``Today Congress had a golden opportunity,'' Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole said after the vote. ``But Senate Democrats
squandered the chance, the first chance in eight years, to raise
the minimum wage.''
   More amendments were being considered before the legislation
faced a final Senate vote, likely to come Wednesday, but no further
significant changes were expected before then.
   ``We compromised,'' said Kennedy, referring to his past
proposals to raise the minimum wage even higher. He also noted a
number of other changes in the legislation, including expanded
exemptions for small businesses, to meet Republican concerns.
   ``The president's approach is a far superior approach,'' Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said in his unsuccessful effort to win support
for substituting Bush's proposal for the Kennedy bill.
   The action seemed to guarantee the first domestic-policy
showdown between Congress and Bush, barring a compromise while the
bill is before a conference committee that will work out minor
differences between the House and Senate versions.
   Such a deal, however, appears unlikely.
   ``There isn't going to be a compromise,'' said Senate Republican
leader Robert Dole of Kansas. ``It's going to be $4.25 an hour and
a six-month training wage, period.''
   Democrats nonetheless called on Bush to accept their proposal.
   ``If there is any one thing that the 101st Congress must do it
is to increase the minimum wage,'' said Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell, D-Maine, chastising Bush for opposing a $4.55 an
hour minimum wage while supporting expanded capital gains tax
breaks for the wealthy. ``This legislation will be a test of
whether we indeed are seeking a kindler, gentler nation,'' said
Mitchell.
   Both the defeated Bush proposal and the amended Kennedy bill
contain provisions allowing some workers to be paid a wage below
the federal minimum wage.
   Bush has insisted that provision extend for six months to all
newly hired workers, regardless of prior work experience.
   Kennedy, like the sponsors of the House bill, balked at that
proposal but to win the support of moderate and conservative
Democrats agreed on a two-month period during which some employees
could be paid 85 percent of the minimum wage.
   That provision was contained in the amendment, offered by
Democratic Sens. Bob Graham of Florida and David Pryor of Arkansas.
   ``Our training wage proposal is a proper balance of the need to
train new workers and the need to set a fair minimum wage,'' said
Graham.
   The Graham-Pryor amendment requires an employee to hold one job
for at least 30 days before the two-month training period would
expire. The House-passed bill also allows for a two-month training
period at a subminimum wage but only if the affected employee had
no prior job experience.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
