<HEAD>Wheat Futures Climb On Crop Report, Export Hopes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, Unleaded gasoline... to CORRECT quotes for West
Texas Intermediate.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Weather-damage fears and expectations of new export business
gave wheat futures prices their strongest boost in more than two
weeks Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Other grain and soybean futures finished narrowly mixed ahead of
an Agriculture Department supply-demand report that was issued
after the close and interpreted as bullish by market analysts.
   On other markets, gasoline futures surged while other oil
futures were mixed; livestock and meat futures retreated; and
precious metals were mixed.
   Wheat settled 3 cents to 6{ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.01 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to { cent
higher with May at $2.65{ a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to 3{ cents
lower with May at $1.83\ a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents lower to
1{ cents higher with May at $7.20{ a bushel.
   The gain in wheat prices was largely a reaction to Monday's
weekly USDA crop-weather report, which showed a net decline in the
condition of the winter wheat crop for the week ending Sunday.
   The USDA said winter wheat was ``mostly fair'' but noted
deterioration of the crop in the central Great Plains and the
Pacific Northwest due to unusually dry, cold weather.
   ``The weather's a little nippy, to put it mildly, in some areas,
slowing development of wheat by about two weeks,'' said Katharina
Zimmer, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
   She said other buying was prompted by perceptions that the
40-cents-a-bushel decline in wheat prices since early March was not
entirely warranted.
   Additional buying was spurred by Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter's statement Monday that an agricultural trade agreement
reached over the weekend would not constrain U.S. spending to
subsidize export sales.
   Corn and soybean futures closed mixed in cautious trading ahead
of the USDA's monthly supply-and-demand report, in which the
government raised its estimates for 1988-89 corn and wheat ending
stocks but let stand its estimate for 1988-89 soybean ending stocks.
   Karlin said the increased estimates were lower than most traders
had expected and should lend support to the markets on Wednesday.
   Unleaded gasoline futures soared on the New York Mercantile
Exchange following wire-service reports that a fire at Chevron
USA's second-largest West Coast refinery could shut down the
refinery's main unit for up to two months and reduce the refinery's
output by about 25 percent.
   Gasoline prices have recently risen sharply on tight-supply
fears linked to the Exxon Valdez oil spill in Alaska.
   The American Petroleum Institute released its weekly
petroleum-stocks report after the close, showing a 4.7
million-barrel decline in U.S. gasoline stocks last week, which
could lead to more buying on Wednesday. The API said crude oil
stocks rose by 451,000 barrels while supplies of petroleum
distillates increased by 440,000 barrels.
   Unleaded gasoline futures settled .44 cent to 1.71 cents higher
with May at 69 cents a gallon; West Texas Intermediate crude oil
was 23 cents lower to 4 cents higher with May at $20.63 a barrel;
heating oil was .06 cent to .29 cent lower with May at 53.23 cents
a gallon.
   Live cattle futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in a late round of selling linked to expectations for a
sharp increase in supplies of market-ready cattle beginning next
month. Profit-taking pressured pork futures prices.
   Live cattle settled .35 cent to 1.15 cents lower with April at
77.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with April at 77.17 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent
lower to .40 cent higher with April at 39.62 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .30 cent to 1 cent lower with May at 33.20 cents
a pound.
   Gold futures drifted lower while silver advanced slightly on New
York's Commodity Exchange in cautious trading ahead of Friday's
economic reports, which include merchandise trade data for
February, the producer price index for March, and March
capacity-utilization and industrial-production figures.
   Gold settled 20 cents to 40 cents lower with June at $389.90 a
troy ounce; silver was 1.3 cents higher across the board with May
at $5.863 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
