<HEAD>Prime To Seek Buyer Above $20 A Share Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `MAI Basic ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
reax from LeBow and to CORRECT company name to MAI Basic Four sted MAI
Basic.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. said Tuesday it will
seek a buyer willing to pay more than the $20 a share offer by
hostile suitor MAI Basic Four Inc. that values the company at $970
million.
   Prime said its financial advisors, First Boston Corp. and Smith
Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co., had been instructed to ``actively
solicit proposals and to pursue discussions and negotiations'' to
sell the company for more than $20 a share.
   The computer firm also said it would provide confidential
information to interested parties.
   Prime climbed to $19.87{, up $1.87{, in heavy New York Stock
Exchange trading Tuesday. More than 2.85 million shares changed
hands.
   MAI Basic Four Inc., a Tustin, Calif.-based computer firm
controlled by investor Bennett S. LeBow, launched its bid five
months ago for Prime, which is four times its size.
   In a statement Tuesday, LeBow said he endorsed Prime's move if
it is the company's intent to sell itself to the highest bidder.
``However, if this is another one of Prime's delaying tactics, we
intend to vigorously oppose it,'' he said, adding that he would
continue to pursue his tender offer for Prime.
   Prime spokesman Joe Gavaghan said estimates valuing Prime at $23
to $28 a share are more credible than MAI Basic's offer, especially
since Prime acquired Computervision Inc. in February 1988.
   He also said Prime's board of directors has not been opposed to
a sale ``if it provides the share holders with a good (price).''
   Prime Chairman David J. Dunn said in a statement that the MAI
Basic offer ``does not reflect the intrinsic value in the company
today and the long-term values achievable for all our
stockholders.''
   Prime said it was delaying its annual meeting to June 14 from
May 12 to ``provide for an orderly and effective sale process.''
