<FIRST>r f AM-DiamondShamrock     04-11 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diamond Shamrock,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge: Diamond Shamrock Insurer Liable For Agent Orange</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge has ruled that insurance
companies don't have to pay for a $25 million dioxin cleanup at the
site of a former Diamond Shamrock plant, but must fund payments to
Agent Orange victims, insurance company attorneys said Tuesday.
   The case centers around dioxin produced as a byproduct of
herbicides, including Agent Orange, made at a Newark plant between
1951 and 1969 by the old Diamond Alkali company, a predecessor to
Shamrock. Diamond Shamrock has restructured and now is called Maxus
Energy Corp., of Dallas, Texas.
   The company sued more than 100 insurers seeking coverage for the
cleanup of the dioxin, which is linked to certain cancers, liver
disease and a severe skin rash known as chloracne.
   In a decision released to lawyers on Tuesday, Superior Court
Judge Reginald Stanton in Morristown, N.J., ruled that Diamond's
actions removed it from coverage, said Bates. Stanton heard a
non-jury trial that began in September.
   The decision could have wide-ranging effects in other cases in
which companies seek to have their insurers handle millions of
dollars in chemical and toxic waste cleanups, said Robert Bates,
who represents American Re-Insurance Co. of Princeton, N.J.
   The opinion was to be filed Wednesday morning. Insurance company
attorneys provided excerpts from it, but Diamond Shamrock lawyers
could not be reached for comment. Stanton, reached at home,
confirmed his ruling but declined to discuss it, referring
questions to the written opinion.
   ``Even by the standards of the 1951 to 1969 period, Diamond's
conduct in operating the Newark plant was unacceptably wrong and
irresponsible,'' Stanton wrote.
   ``Diamond always put its narrowly perceived economic interest
first. It deliberately and persistently cheated on the limited
environmental regulations which were in place.''
   But Stanton also found that the insurance companies have to pay
the bulk of Diamond's $23 million share of a $180 million
settlement reached in 1984 between makers of Agent Orange used in
the Vietnam War and those who sued over its health effects.
   Stanton interpreted the company's insurance contracts to mean
that the insurers would have to bear most of the Agent Orange
payments, and established how the payments would be distributed
among the carriers, according to Bates.
   Lawyers for the company could not be reached. They either had
gone home for the evening or did not return phone calls.
   A Maxus spokeswoman, Ginger Shearburn, could not be reached.
There was no answer at the company and she did not return a
telephone call left on her home answering machine.
</TEXT>
