<DOCNO> AP890411-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-89 2109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru f0219 04-11 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0219,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Negotiators Say Major Issues Remain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, inserts 1 graf after 11th graf to UPDATE. Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House and congressional budget
negotiators, driving toward a deficit-reduction deal, said Tuesday
that major issues remain and pledged not to let any deadline ``blow
up'' the talks.
   ``When we get one issue resolved, we run into another,'' said
Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico, senior Republican on the
Senate Budget Committee.
   ``We have not closed on any of the major ones (issues),'' said
Rep. Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., the House majority leader. ``You
just have to keep plodding on, one step after another.''
   Privately, some participants said there was an eagerness to
finish so that President Bush and congressional leaders could
announce a pact at the White House this week. But no announcement
was scheduled by the time the group broke for the night Tuesday,
and Bush planned to leave Washington for the weekend early Thursday,
   But Foley said the group was not working against any deadline.
``It's silly to blow up a long negotiation over an artificial
deadline,'' he said.
   The goal of the talks is agreement on the general outlines of a
budget to bring the fiscal 1990 deficit down to $100 billion as
mandated by the Gramm-Rudman law.
   The talks have dragged on far longer than expected and are now
pressing against a Saturday deadline for passing a budget
resolution.
   Bush proposed his $1.16 trillion budget in February, estimating
that about $27 billion needed to be slashed from current government
programs _ or revenues increased _ to meet the Gramm-Rudman goal.
   The negotiating team has been working on a $28 billion plan,
with about half the deficit savings coming from new revenues and
half from spending restraint.
   On the spending side, more than $7 billion in savings would be
made by restraining entitlement programs _ those requiring direct
benefit payments to individuals. More than $2.5 billion of that
would be from holding back some of the expected growth in Medicare
spending.
   They tentatively agreed last week that the revenues would
include roughly $3.4 billion from selling government assets, $5.2
billion from raising various fees for government services and $5.6
billion from unspecified taxes.
   However, the revenue mix has been changing this week as the
group has consulted the White House and the congressional
committees responsible for putting the agreement into legislation.
Less money would be raised with new fees, and more through asset
sales, sources said.
   Although the tax figure is about the same as Bush proposed in
his budget, the president's plan relied heavily on his proposal to
cut the tax rate on capital gains. Bush contends a lower capital
gains rate would actually increase government revenues by $4.8
billion next year.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater on Tuesday denied Bush
was abandoning his support of capital gains tax reduction, but it
was subject to negotiation.
   ``He will believe in the capital gains tax cut forever and
ever,'' Fitzwater said. ``I'm not making any commitments in terms
of the budget deal. The budget deal is up to negotiation.
Everything is under discussion.''
   Actually, the details of the tax package and specific spending
decisions would be left for later.
   The negotiators have been working to produce a very broad set of
guidelines, setting forth total figures for a handful of revenue
and spending categories. It would be left for the normal
legislative process to produce the steps to enact those totals.
   Participants in the talks said they were sworn to secrecy about
the specifics, because of the sensitivity of the current
discussions on possible cuts in Bush's $300 billion defense budget
and in domestic programs.
   Bush proposed that military spending be allowed to grow with
inflation. Democratic negotiators have asked for slower defense
growth so that more domestic demands can be met.
   If the negotiators complete a package, the House and Senate
budget committees would then draft more detailed spending plans for
each chamber to consider. Then, the two chambers would need to
approve a single, compromise plan.
   The budget serves as the guide for annual spending bills and tax
legislation for the new fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
   If Congress and the president don't enact legislation to reduce
the deficit to within $10 billion of the $100 billion goal, the
administration is required under the Gramm-Rudman law to order
across-the-board spending cuts to make up the difference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
